<HEAD>Administration Bars NIH From Experiments On Aborted Fetal Tissue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The National Institutes of Health may not conduct experiments using tissue from aborted fetuses _ considered promising in early work on Parkinson's disease _ under a ruling by the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, according to a published report. `` This is a very difficult process,'' Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, assistant secretary of health at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday about his decision last week. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported the decision in Friday's editions. `` The morality and science are all mixed together,'' <PERSON> Windom </PERSON> said. `` They need to be evaluated before we rush ahead. We just ca n't afford to move too hastily on this.'' <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>'s decision was prompted by an <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> proposal to implant fetal tissue into patients with <ORGANIZATION> Parkinson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>, the newspaper reported. <PERSON> Windom </PERSON>, in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyngaarden </PERSON>, said he was `` withholding my approval of the proposed experiments'' due to `` ethical and legal'' questions that had not been addressed satisfactorily. He directed <PERSON> Wyngaarden </PERSON> to create an outside advisory committee to examine such questions, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Windom </PERSON> wrote that he does not oppose the use of fetal tissue from miscarriages or stillbirths, but researchers contacted by the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said proper planning is necessary to retrieve the tissue while it is useful and that it is rarely possible to use fetuses that have been aborted spontaneously. Researchers contacted by the newspaper expressed dismay over the decision, with Dr. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebel </PERSON>, professor of medicine at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Toronto </ORGANIZATION>, saying: `` <ORGANIZATION> NIH </ORGANIZATION> sets the pace, and this will cripple fetal research in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ... It is an extraordinarily valuable research tool with immense potential. Depriving research scientists of this material is a great disservice to humanity.'' But abortion opponents praised the decision. `` If the parents were a part to the killing, they have no right to assign organs to another person,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Willke </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Right-to-life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` that is desecration of a corpse.''
