<HEAD>Pranksters Make Statue Do About-Face</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The one ton bronze statue of <ORGANIZATION> Rice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> founder <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Marsh </PERSON> <PERSON> Rice </PERSON> has been festooned with such things as hats, coats and military regalia since it was placed on campus 58 years ago. But on Tuesday, it was facing south instead of north. Just before dawn, a campus police officer spotted about 20 people around the statue and noticed a spotlight that usually illuminates it was dark. As he approached, the group scattered, said <ORGANIZATION> Campus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> Chief <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Voswinkel </PERSON>. Ms. <PERSON> Voswinkel </PERSON> said the officer was able to stop one student, who was driving a pickup truck away from the quadrangle. The officer took the student's name and let him go, then sped back to the statue to investigate. The statue appeared intact _ but was facing the <LOCATION> Fondren </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Library </LOCATION> to the south instead of the Lovett Building to the north. It took 3 -LCB- hours for a crew of professional movers using a crane to fix the statue. `` It was a student prank,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Noblitt </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rice </PERSON>'s director of university relations. `` It was a rite-of-spring type thing.'' <PERSON> Noblitt </PERSON> said the vandalism could have had serious consequences because students apparently used an A-frame built from 4-by-6 beams to lift the statue. The devices that were found had cracked, and the statue could have fallen. The pranksters apparently climbed to the roof of the Architecture Building to disconnect the spotlight and had painted the A-frame black to help conceal it. The student who was questioned will face disciplinary action from the university, but officials did not release further details.
