<HEAD>Whisky-Maker Says San Francisco Water Not Good Enough</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The drought-threatened <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> region is getting a little help from an unlikely quarter _ the makers of Famous Grouse Scotch whisky. The manufacturers of the liquor, <ORGANIZATION> Matthew </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gloag </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Sons of <LOCATION> Perth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>, kicked off their latest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales campaign, but decided they could n't bear the thought that <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Franciscans </LOCATION> might mix their prized whisky with local tap water. `` The fact is that <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> tap water does not taste very good,'' said local Famous Grouse spokesman <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwartz </PERSON>. So this month, it started selling a $ 14 package containing the scotch and a bottle of water from <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Strathmore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>, a combination the company says is necessary to bring out the best features of the liquor. `` Serious scotch drinkers in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> have been loath to mix Famous Grouse with the infamous chlorinated city water,'' read several hundred invitations to a scotch and bagpipe bash Wednesday at a chic watering hole. Famous Grouse, stung by the mere 1.5 gallon-per-capita consumption of distilled spirits in this country, is trying to heighten the figure with a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> campaign initially targeting <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> D.C </ORGANIZATION>. In the Bay region, a fringe benefit will be to ease ever so slightly the water shortage threatened by an exceptionally dry winter.
