<HEAD>Opposition, But No Violence A Farrakhan Speaks On Penn Campus</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with quotes from speech as
delivered, add that university disputes number of people at rally.
No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nation of Islam leader <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> told a cheering audience at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> `` you should thank God <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has emerged'' as a leading presidential candidate. The black Muslim minister, whose appearance set off a week of controversy and a protest rally by up to 1,000 people, brought most of the 2,000 in the auditorium to their feet when he said, `` <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is running to save a people; he is running to save the nation. `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is growing up to respect men of wisdom in black skins, but it has n't grown up yet,'' <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, during his 1984 presidential campaign, accepted <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON>'s support, leading to harsh criticism, particularly from Jews. <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> has been reported to have praised <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> and called Judaism a gutter religion, but he denied Wednesday ever making the statements. During this campaign, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has had no contact with <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON>. The Muslim minister, whose visit was guarded by strict security measures that cost the university $ 6,000, insisted that those opposing <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, especially in the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> primary next week in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, are using `` me to galvanize Jews against <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>.'' `` They are using me to try to derail him,'' he added. The comments came in two-hour speech in which he predicted, without being specific, that `` a very dark and tragic day is coming to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and to humanity.'' Over and over <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> told how whites dominate the western world. Referring to the days, more than 125 years ago, when blacks were slaves in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> said he was joining `` my dear Jewish friends in saying ` never again,''' referring to the phrase Jews use in condemning the Nazi Holocaust. `` I am considered a hater, but I am a reminder to the black people of what has happened to us,'' he said. `` For if we forget it will happen again.'' Before his evening speech, the black Muslim minister said the community would benefit by the controvery his visit has generated. `` Even though the atmosphere is charged, I did not charge it,'' he said at a news conference. `` My presence hopefully will help the students to judge me better.'' Students gathered for an hour-long demonstration before the speech, waving signs saying: `` Unity, Yes. Anti-Semitism, No.'' and `` Free Speech, Yes. Hatred, No.'' `` No matter what <PERSON> Farrahkan </PERSON> says, it does n't erase what he said in the past,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Genulka </PERSON>, the rally organizer and chairman of the Council of Jewish Students. `` We must work together as a community instead of being at odds.'' Last week, university officials refused a Jewish group's request to cancel the visit, saying they respected <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON>'s right to free speech. A letter condemning <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> and signed by more than 700 students and teachers appeared in the Wednesday student paper. The visit comes in the wake of the 18-month suspension of a predominantly Jewish fraternity for hiring two black women to perform as strippers at a party. Party-goers reportedly shouted racial epithets. University President <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Hackney </PERSON> defended the Farrakhan visit. `` In an academic community, open expression is the most fundemental value. We ca n't have free speech just some of the time for some of the people,'' he told the rally. Security officers estimated the number of protesters at 1,000, but university spokesman <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> said no more than 400 attended the rally and the others were waiting to clear the tight security into the auditorium where <PERSON> Farrakhan </PERSON> was speeking. The sell-out crowd of 2,000 paid $ 4 apiece to see <PERSON> Farrakan </PERSON>, who received $ 10,000 plus travel expenses from the two groups sponsoring the appearance: the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consciousness </ORGANIZATION> and the predominantly white <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>.
