<HEAD>Provisions of Afghan Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghan-Signing, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the main features of the agreement to withdraw Soviet troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The provisions, outlined before the signing today in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, include: _ Withdrawal of all Soviet troops within nine months starting May 15, with half the total gone by Aug. 15 _ Pledges by <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> of non-interference in each other's affairs _ Voluntary return of about 5 million Afghan refugees from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> _ Supervision of the settlement and the return of refugees by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> _ Guarantees from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s future non-alignment In addition, a U.S.-Soviet understanding will allow <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to continue military aid to the Afghan guerrillas, and <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to continue sending arms to the Afghan government.
