<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     04-14 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MADISON, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's not much you can buy for a penny these days. But with 1,000,131 of them, you can make your way into the Guinness Book of World Records. This weekend, a local group trying to raise money for a $ 40,000 playground will try to lay down at least that many coins in a high school gymnasium to set a world record in length for a line of pennies. Volunteers plan to begin creating 58 lanes 3 feet wide and 44 feet long on the gym floor Friday night. When they are finished sometime Saturday, they hope to have 1,540,500 pennies set down in rows an inch apart, creating a line 13.66 miles long. The Guinness-recognized record is 1,000,130 one-cent coins put down in a 12.29-mile line Nov. 15, 1985, by students at <ORGANIZATION> Blacktown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Girls </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. `` We figured out that, in order to accomplish the whole thing in a 12-hour period, we would have to lay down something like 30 pennies a second,'' volunteer coordinator <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. Coordinators have lined up 30 people for each two-hour shift of penny-laying. The group also has planned ahead how to get the pennies picked up after the record attempt. `` We'll start vacuuming them up on Sunday morning,'' said volunteer <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolf </PERSON>. The group received donations for the effort from children, businesses and service groups. One problem, however, was that the three banks in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> only keep about $ 300 each in pennies at one time. The banks arranged for 800,000 pennies to be shipped in by armored car from <LOCATION> Davenport </LOCATION>, and paid $ 1,000 to have the pennies wrapped and shipped, which took about three weeks.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State officials are n't quite ready to file for a patent, but they're definitely taking a `` pro-pie-tary'' interest in Key lime pie. Under a bill approved in committee Wednesday, the creamy concoction would be designated the official state pie. Key lime pie, legislators explain, is `` properly'' made only with limes from the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Keys </LOCATION>. State symbols are serious business in identity-conscious <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, which already has a state tree, beverage, shell, stone, gem, animal, freshwater and saltwater fish, marine and saltwater mammal, air fair, festival and litter control symbol. In 1987, lawmakers designated the American alligator as the official state reptile. According to a committee staff analysis, `` by being officially designated, the Key lime pie would be in greater demand, thereby promoting this fruit unique to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>.'' The Intergovernmental Relations Subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 5-0 for the bill, which must be now be approved by the full House.
