<HEAD>Q &amp; A on Afghan Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghan-Signing, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here in question and answer form is a discussion of the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> agreement: Q: Who is involved in the settlement? A: Signing the documents were the Soviet-supported Afghan government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, in which 3 million Afghan refugees live, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> signing as guarantors. The mujahedeen gurrellias who have been fighting the Afghan government and the Soviet troops in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> have not signed and have vowed to carry on their struggle to establish an Islamic government. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, which shelters about 2 million Afghan refugees, did not participate in the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> talks. Q: What is in the four-part accord? A: The text of the accord was being published only after the signing, but <ORGANIZATION> U.N </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> and spokesman for the parties involved outlined the provisions. The documents include Afghan-Pakistani agreements for non-interference and non-intervention in each other's affairs and for the safe and voluntary return of Afghan refugees. Another part are <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet declarations guaranteeing <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s future non-alignment and the rest of the settlement. A fourth document sets the timetable for the withdrawal of Soviet troops and ties the other three together. Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> has said the pullout of an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops will begin May 15. The process is to be completed within nine months but <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has indicated it hopes to bring the last soldier home early. Q: How will compliance be monitored? A: An annex sets up a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> supervisory role for the settlement. About 50 <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> officers in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will monitor implementation until two months after all refugees return. The repatriation will be overseen by the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> high commissioner for refugees. Q: Will the settlement stop the civil war? A: The mujahedeen alliance of Moslem guerrillas says it will continue fighting until Soviet troops leave and the Marxist <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government is overthrown. The <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government has said it will continue to exercise power. Both sides are well armed and believed capable of carrying on the fighting. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> is convinced the bloodshed will not end, and the refugees will not return, until the creation of an interim Afghan government. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> says <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s political future is for its people to decide. Q: What about superpower support of the rivals? A: The accords say nothing about that. But the superpowers have reached an understanding allowing both to continue aid _ the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to the mujahedeen. Diplomats have said the understanding is that arms shipments will be phased out, with each superpower reserving the right to resume arms supplies if the other does so.
