<HEAD>Government Authorizes Use of Contraception</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NIAMEY, Niger (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government authorized the use of contraceptives to help control population growth and the spread of disease. The move was regarded as significant in a predominantly Moslem country of 7 million people, where the use of contraceptives has been illegal without a doctor's prescription since independence from <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> in 1960. The government said on Wednesday the use of condoms, diaphragms and spercmicides would no longer require a doctor's prescription. The communique did not say if the government also would begin distributing contraceptives. <LOCATION> Niger </LOCATION>, located in the arid <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahel </LOCATION>, suffers from recurring serious food shortages related to drought and poor farm land. Its population is growing at an annual rate of 2.9 percent. The government has predicted the population will grow to 10 million by the year 2000.
