<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A months-long recall effort to oust Mayor <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> <PERSON> Pena </PERSON> failed Wednesday when an elections official announced that petitions submitted fell more than 2,000 names short of the number required by law. The backers of the drive delivered 21 bundles of petitions to the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday afternoon, beating a 5 p.m. deadline by several hours. They said they believed there were enough valid signatures to support calling a new mayoral election. But late Wednesday, <PERSON> Felicia </PERSON> <PERSON> Muftic </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Denver </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, said that even without checking for validity, the number of signatures was only 36,960. For a recall, the petitions would have to bear the valid signatures of 39,091 registered <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> voters, which is 25 percent of the number of votes cast in the last mayoral election, said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarkington </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. `` It appears that unofficially there's just not enough signatures to continue,'' <PERSON> Muftic </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Pena </PERSON>, 41, one of the first Hispanics to be mayor of a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> city, reacted immediately with pleasure. `` The time for negativism and doubt is behind us. To those people who opposed the recall I thank you. To those who supported the recall I urge you to join with the city to help move the city forward. These are critical times facing our city and we ca n't afford to have disunity,'' he said at a news conference at his office late Wednesday Recall organizer <PERSON> Marge </PERSON> <PERSON> Doty </PERSON> said earlier Wednesday that she had no exact count on the number of signatures, but said she was confident there were `` more than enough'' to continue the recall process. <PERSON> Doty </PERSON>, who launched the recall effort in January, requested a police escort to and from the <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> office after she reported receiving threats. The recall drive was started by a group angry over what its members claimed was fiscal mismanagement by the <PERSON> Pena </PERSON> administration. The group gathered support among residents stranded for several days by a major holiday snowstorm when maintenance crews plowed only major traffic arteries while <PERSON> Pena </PERSON> was vacationing out of state. While there is some dispute about precise procedures, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s charter calls for an entirely new, nonpartisan election if the petitions are validated to recall <PERSON> Pena </PERSON>, a second-term Democrat Any candidate who collected 300 names on a nominating petition could run, and if no candidate mustered a clear majority, a run-off would be held next. There have been hints of illegalities in the petition campaign. <PERSON> Pena </PERSON> appeared on a <ORGANIZATION> KOA </ORGANIZATION> radio call-in show Wednesday morning, and one caller informed him her daughter had been approached by petitioners. The daughter said she was told she `` had to sign,'' and when she said she was not a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> resident, she was allegedly told, `` We'll give you a <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> address.''
