<SECOND>PM-City Smelters, Bjt,0654</SECOND>
<HEAD>Annual Spawning Brings Smelt And Fish Stories To Chicago Lakefront</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On spring nights, pearls of light from lanterns and campfires sparkle along <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s dark seawalls and breakwaters as thousands of people wait for tiny silvery fish to wander into their nets. The smelt are spawning again, a decades-old rite of spring that is part social event, part business and part recreation along the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> during the six-week season from April 1 to May 15. Smelting is almost a way of life. `` I've been doing it for 30 years, and I've run through friends, family, my kids _ nobody loves it quite as much as I do,'' said <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Telkamp </PERSON>, who staked out his spot four hours before he could legally lower his net at 7 p.m. `` My wife wo n't clean fish anymore, so I spend all night smelting and all day cleaning.'' Rainbow smelt, 6 - to 8-inch members of a family resembling the trout, have been eaten in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> for centuries In the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, the rite began after 1912, when the smelt, orginally a salt-water fish, escaped into the Great Lakes from a small lake in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> where they had been stocked. The best smelting at <LOCATION> Montrose </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> was on the breakwater, which was lined with Vietnamese, <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> and Korean families, and a few <LOCATION> Polish </LOCATION> immigrants. Fathers lower and raise the nets, children pull the fish from the mesh and mothers gut and clean. `` A lot of those fish are going to <LOCATION> Argyle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>,'' said one onlooker, referring to a nearby neighborhood with Vietnamese and <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> restaurants. With the right water temperature, current and wind, the smelt head in from open waters in great numbers. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> smelters run their square gill nets out on anchored ropes, raising the nets several times an hour. Nightly yields can reach 5,000 fish a person, but on nights when the fish are fewer, it's time for six-packs and smelt stories. Like the one <PERSON> Rob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohagan </PERSON>, 24, of <LOCATION> Darien </LOCATION>, tells about the tipsy smelter who weighted his net with his keys. `` A lot of guys fish without licenses and just abandon their nets when the wardens come by,'' <PERSON> Ohagan </PERSON> said. `` They figure it's cheaper to lose a $ 35 smelt rig than to pay a $ 50 fine `` This guy remembered that his keys were on the net, and he could n't get into his car, so he had to take the fine,'' <PERSON> Ohagan </PERSON> said. There's also the matter of upholding a tradition observed by younger smelters: biting the head off the first smelt of the season. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Flowers </PERSON>, 25, of <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Grange </PERSON>, pulled up his first net of the spring and saluted the four dangling fish with a beer, but he would n't take the bite. `` Now you wo n't have any more luck,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Falduto </PERSON>, 25, of Park Ridge. <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Laurie </PERSON>, had set up a net, a fire and a tent for their two young daughters, <PERSON> Nicole </PERSON> and <PERSON> Chris </PERSON>. `` We've been smelting about five years _ always at this very same spot,'' <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> said. `` We only ran out of last year's frozen smelt last month.'' The Roths, of Park Forest, like their smelt marinated in home-made hot sauce, but <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON>, also casting his net along the breakwater, cooks his in a beer batter. `` I keep a couple of gallons for myself and give the rest away _ to friends or in the tavern,'' <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON> said. `` They're a lot easier to give away than zucchini or tomatoes.'' <PERSON> Wolfgang </PERSON>, 45, said this night he was catching a wedding present. `` My sister's getting married tomorrow in <ORGANIZATION> Eau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Claire </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` She likes smelt, but they're hard to come by that far from the lakes.''
