<FIRST>r w PM-PresidentialWords     04-14 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Presidential Words,670</SECOND>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: When a President's Words Are Not His Words</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Question: When are the president's words not the president's words? Answer: A lot of the time. Past and present <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> aides say former presidential spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> went too far when he quoted President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as saying things in meetings the president did n't say. It is nevertheless common practice for press secretaries and other aides to craft statements of various kinds which, usually after being approved by the president, are issued in his name. `` The whole business of communication is the drafting of materials that the president may use in one form or another, whether it's a speech or a statement or quotes on a various issue that tell what the president thinks,'' says <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. `` As long as it is approved by him and reflects his thinking and so forth, that is what it is,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> told reporters Tuesday. `` It is the president's thinking.'' But, said <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>, it is wrong to attribute fabricated quotes to the president in the way <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> did it. Former presidential press secretaries made similar distinctions. `` You try to portray what the man is, what his thoughts are, and you try to put them in words that would be his kind of words, but you always have to rely on his approval of those speeches and those words; that's a given,'' said <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> ter </PERSON> <PERSON> Horst </PERSON>, who was President <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>'s first press secretary. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziegler </PERSON>, who was President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>'s press secretary, said, `` It's common practice for press secretaries to develop quotes and get somebody's approval. That's been practice since the beginning of time.'' Both ter <PERSON> Horst </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ziegler </PERSON>, however, said <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> was out of line. Why? What was he doing that was different? What he did, on one occasion, was to have an aide make up quotes, polish the quotes himself, and then pass them off as things the president said in his <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> summit meeting with <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> defended the practice, saying, `` I think it was an accurate reflection of the president's thinking, the way I approached it. We talked many times in the preparation for the summit, so I knew how he felt.'' On another occasion, <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> says he put words that were spoken by Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> into the president's mouth after a <ORGANIZATION> Korean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> jet was shot down in 1983 with 61 Americans aboard. Any president has much of his material written for him by aides who presumably help him to express his own view. There is a speech writing department to turn out speeches for him. He goes into meetings armed with talking points from which to speak. If he misspeaks at a news conference, a clarifying statement, prepared by aides, is issued in his name. When foreign journalists submit questions in writing, the answers are in his name but are staff-written. Even his answers at news conferences are frequently not spontaneous. According to <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> and others, the president is given briefing books in question-and-answer form for study and practice before each session. Reporters who cover the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, however, know and often report that such materials are written for the president. They did not know, and were not able to report, that the quotes given them by <PERSON> Speakes </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> were not actually spoken by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. In addition, as <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Reedy </PERSON>, former press secretary to <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> noted, at least some of the <LOCATION> Speakes-Reagan </LOCATION> quotes were fabricated in the context of a major international meeting. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON>, White House reporter for the <ORGANIZATION> Sheridan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION>, when asked whether he was surprised to find that the quotes had been faked, replied, `` These quotes, yes. We're not talking about the president speaking to the Jaycees or the Future Farmers of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. We're talking about a meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> covers the White House for The Associated Press.
