<HEAD>Shultz Confident Soviets Will Honor Afghan Agreement</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Top expected after Shultz arrival in Geneva, approximately 7
a.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> says he is confident the Soviets will keep their promise to withdraw from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> under an agreement hailed as the first step toward ending the bitter Afghan struggle. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> flew to <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> today to join Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> at the ceremonial signing of a series of settlement accords. Among them is a Soviet pledge to withdraw an estimated 115,000 Red Army troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> also plan to issue statements reaffirming their nations' right to continue aiding the Afghan factions _ assuring that the war will go on as a civil conflict. There was fresh evidence of continued warfare on the eve of the signing. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, confirmed reports from Western diplomats in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> earlier in the week that Soviet forces near <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> were sent to relieve <LOCATION> Gardez </LOCATION>, a beleaguered <ORGANIZATION> Afghan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> garrison south of the capital, amid fierce fighting with U.S.-backed guerrillas. The units were said to consist of an undetermined number of soldiers and 420 vehicles, including T-72 tanks, armored personnel carriers and mobile rocket launchers. <LOCATION> Gardez </LOCATION> is 80 miles south of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and 60 miles from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, staging area for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to the resistance. <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas recently cut the road to <LOCATION> Gardez </LOCATION>, where a Soviet special forces regiment is garrisoned, said one source. Another source said convoys of trucks also were sent into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in the past week, but it was not clear if the trucks were filled with troops or were empty. Before leaving for <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told members of <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> foreign affairs committees that he had faith in the Soviet promise, committee members said. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, one of Capitol Hill's ardent champions of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support for anti-Soviet guerrillas in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, said after meeting <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> he accepted the assurances. `` The bottom line is that the Soviets are getting out,'' <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> said. Under the withdrawal agreement, the Soviets are supposed to pull out 50 percent of their troops within 90 days, and the entire contingent by Feb. 15, 1989. That would mark the end of a Soviet troop presence in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> that began with a December 1979 airlift of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> forces into <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> to back pro-Moscow Afghan leaders in their war against insurgents. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> analysts believe the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> will pull back from exposed positions and concentrate in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> and around the northern city of <LOCATION> Mazar-i-Sharif </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had hoped to reach agreement with the Soviets to cut aid to both sides _ the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> backed guerrillas and the Soviet-sponsored Afghan government _ but <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> rebuffed an aid cutoff and now both sides will continue arming their clients. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said he hoped <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON>, who arranged the Soviet pullout, will be successful in arranging a peace accord between the Afghans. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the Afghan government have agreed under the accords to stop interfering in each others' affairs and the superpowers are signing the pact as `` guarantors.'' Despite the likelihood of continued fighting, the prospect of a Soviet withdrawal has been hailed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials as a potential milestone in superpower relations. Since 1979, the <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administrations have told the Soviets that their continued presence in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> has made it difficult for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to trust Soviet professions of peaceful intent.
</TEXT>
