 At the immigration service, Assistant Commissioner <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said it was his job to recommend to Commissioner <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> whether to stay in the Chester Arthur Building or move. If <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a close friend of <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s from the days when they worked together in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, had demanded a move, the <ORGANIZATION> GSA </ORGANIZATION> would have found a new building, according to <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> GSA </ORGANIZATION> officials. But <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> recommended staying even though he was displeased with the building management, particularly its maintenance of the air system. `` At one point, a downtown, new building came on the market and people thought about that for a while,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` But when you look at the logistics of uprooting your entire headquarters staff for a month, it's not worth it.'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said other events tied his hands: The first immigration reform bill in a generation was enacted Oct. 17, 1986. `` We could n't even consider a move at that time, because of the demands of the new act,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` We had to get thousands of new employees on board.'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said when he discussed the lease with <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> `` there were no options. When you look at the cost of moving and all that, it's kind of the decision that does n't have to be made.'' But during this period, the immigration service outgrew <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON>; some employees were put in two other buildings, five and 10 blocks away. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> says no one pressured him, and that he never heard whether <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> had an opinion on the lease or about <PERSON> Ursula </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s salary being paid indirectly by the building owners Sources famil