<HEAD>Student Judicial Board Disallows Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A student judicial board at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wednesday </ORGANIZATION> declared invalid an election in which an avowed communist and another student were chosen as co-presidents of the student body. The board said the constitution of the Student Government Association prohibited more than one person from holding the presidency. `` Only one person can run for and hold the office of <ORGANIZATION> SGA </ORGANIZATION> president,'' the three-member student court said in an opinion issued late Wednesday night. The student court, whose decisions are binding on the student government, ordered a new election. A date was not immediately set. Student attorney general <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> asked the court to declare the <PERSON> Jason </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabinowitz-Shari </PERSON> <PERSON> Silkoff </PERSON> ticket invalid because of the joint candidacy. <PERSON> Rabinowitz </PERSON>, a 20-year-old member of the <ORGANIZATION> Young </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION>, is believed to be the first such member elected campus president since the group was formed five years ago. He and <PERSON> Silkoff </PERSON>, also 20 and a self-described progressive, were elected March 15 with 1,454 votes, 391 more than conservative candidate <PERSON> Aram </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamparian </PERSON> at the 19,000-student campus. `` This was a travesty of justice,'' <PERSON> Rabinowitz </PERSON> said after the decision was announced. `` We're going to beat this. We want to fight for the rights of the students.'' A professor who testified at the hearing last week on behalf of <PERSON> Rabinowitz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Silkoff </PERSON> said the constitution's language about the presidency was vague. `` It could be read in different ways,'' said political science professor <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfange </PERSON> said. On whether it prohibited co-presidents, he said: `` That language does not necessarily mean that to me, as a layman reading this document.'' Conservatives in the student senate had filibustered last week to keep the election from being ratified and to stop <PERSON> Rabinowitz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Silkoff </PERSON> from taking office.
