<HEAD>PBS Film Recounts World War II on Alaskan Frontier</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> thinks it's time to remember what he calls `` a forgotten piece of history.'' `` Well, at least it's forgotten down here, but certainly not back home,'' says the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Republican. `` A lot of people down here in the lower 48 think we're overseas, we're some kind of foreign country.'' The history to which <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> referred is the little-known role played by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> in World War II, when the <LOCATION> Aleutian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> were invaded and occupied by Japanese troops for 14 months until the summer of 1943. It was the first time since the War of 1812 that a foreign nation had occupied <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> territory. The story is eloquently told in `` <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> at War,'' which will air April 25 on the Public Broadcasting System. The one-hour film, written and produced by <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> for the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, was previewed Wednesday in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing room at a reception hosted by <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> legislators. In 1942, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> was a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> territory, still 17 years away from statehood. It was largely undeveloped, a frontier land where conditions were primitive and life was hard. There were few paved roads and little development. <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> native who has lived in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> since 1970, spent two years making the film, spending much of that time digging up rare historical footage. Among the film he used was rare color footage taken by the late director <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> came under attack on June 3, 1942, when Japanese planes bombed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> base at <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> in the Aleutians chain. Although damage was relatively light, 25 Americans were killed. The attack was part of the overall Japanese drive on <LOCATION> Midway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, the small but vital American outpost in the middle of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>. The Aleutian attack was intended as a feint, a move designed to draw away from Midway some of the already thin American forces which were still reeling from the attack on <LOCATION> Pearl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> six months before. But unknown to the Japanese, American intelligence had broken Japanese codes and did n't fall for the <LOCATION> Aleutian </LOCATION> gambit. Instead, Adm. <PERSON> Chester </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimitz </PERSON> concentrated his forces at Midway and dealt the Japanese <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> a crushing attack in one of history's greatest sea battles. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> never recovered. While the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> was reeling at Midway, Japanese army troops were landing in June 1942 on two Aleutian islands at the western end of the far-flung chain. About 2,600 troops landed on <LOCATION> Attu </LOCATION> and another 5,600 at <LOCATION> Kiska </LOCATION>, 200 miles away. For the next year, as <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON>'s film makes clear, <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> bombers steadily pounded the two Japanese installations, but were unable to dislodge the invaders. One tragic footnote was the forced removal of about 900 Aleut Indians to a new home 2,000 miles away. But conditions at the new location were harsh and preparations were few; many of the Aleuts died. `` Many people do n't realize what was done to the Aleuts. It's time their story was told,'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said In the spring of 1943, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces prepared to retake the two Aleutian islands and the decision was made to attack the smaller base at <LOCATION> Attu </LOCATION>. On May 11, 1943, 11,000 American troops invaded <LOCATION> Attu </LOCATION> under dreadful weather conditions. What was supposed to be a three-day job took three weeks of often-brutal fighting through the rocky hills and valleys of the desolate island. When the Japanese on <LOCATION> Attu </LOCATION> realized they were surrounded, the hundreds of soldiers remaining alive committed suicide, a fact well documented by the film. Only 29 of the 2,600 Japanese troops survived; <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> casualties totaled 549. Two months later, under cover of fog, the <ORGANIZATION> Japanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> was able to evacuate its base on <LOCATION> Kiska </LOCATION>. Even now, <LOCATION> Attu </LOCATION> remains a little-visited place, and for good reason, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> noted. `` There are still a lot of Japanese relics out there,'' he said. `` We believe there are some unexploded shells on the island, so people are kept away. We considered making it a historic site, but it would cost a fortune to sanitize it and so the job has never been done.''
</TEXT>
