<FIRST>r w PM-WorldOutlook     04-14 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-World Outlook,400</SECOND>
<NOTE>For release at 9:30 a.m. EDT; time set by source</NOTE>
<HEAD>Economic Prospects Improving in US But not in Poor Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Economic prospects have improved slightly over the past six months in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other industrial countries, but have dropped sharply in poor countries, according to estimates made public today by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the fund predicts that production will increase this year by the same 2.9 percent as it did in 1986 and 1987, with a slower increase of 2.7 percent in 1989. It predicts declining unemployment from 6.2 percent last year to 6 percent this year and 5.9 next year. Inflation in the industrialized countries is pegged at 3 percent in 1988. But in the Third World, the report says, prices paid by consumers will go up by 46.7 percent. Total growth in the Third World is put at 3.7 percent. The report does not include population figures, but since Third World birth rates are high, the rise in income for each individual may be only about half as much. For industrial countries, the new growth figure is 3 percent. `` An important positive development in 1987 was the strengthening of policy coordination among the major industrial countries,'' says the fund's new `` World Economic Outlook.'' `` The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal budget deficit fell substantially, as did deficits in other large countries with troublesome fiscal positions.'' In the <ORGANIZATION> IMF </ORGANIZATION>'s parlance, a country gets into a `` troublesome fiscal position'' when its government fails to collect enough taxes to cover its expenses. The fund says the three most economically important Latin American countries _ <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> _ have had serious setbacks in curbing inflation and there are signs of rising prices elsewhere. Fund officials doubt if their governments can do anything effective to stabilize their economies. Sluggish growth in the Third World is blamed in part on a slowdown in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> due to drought, and to lower pay and less investment in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> because of rising inflation. Growth in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, on the other hand, was called `` particularly buoyant.'' The predictions are made on the assumption that government policies and currency exchange rates will not change. For the major industrial countries taken as a group the predictions include these for the years 1990 to 1992: a 2.8 percent increase in production and a slight increase in the jobless rate to 6.9 percent.
</TEXT>
