<HEAD>Last Minute Filers Can Save Time With Short Form</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you are among millions of taxpayers waiting until the last minute to file federal returns, you might save time and expedite any refund by avoiding the long Form 1040. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, found during a check of one of the 10 <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> processing centers that 14.1 percent of filers had used 1040 when they could have filed the simpler 1040A or the one-page 1040EZ. Many of those probably were taxpayers who in the past itemized deductions and thus had to file the long form, and stuck with it this year even though repeal or reduction of several deductions made it no longer profitable to itemize. The shorter forms are less complicated to fill out and present fewer opportunities for errors. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> requires less time to process them. But the shorter forms are not for everyone. If your itemized deductions total more than your standard deduction, you'll save money by itemizing, which requires the long form. And you must file the long form if taxable income is $ 50,000 or more. Midnight Friday is the deadline for most individuals to file their returns _ the first that reflect the far-reaching tax-law revision enacted in 1986. So far, despite confusion about the law and new forms, taxpayers and the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> seem to be holding their own. `` This has been a very good filing season to date,'' <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> said. `` But it has been challenging ... because of the number of changes made in the 1986 act.'' Through April 8, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> had received 64.5 million returns, compared with 65.7 million before the last week of the 1987 filing season. The agency has processed 52.7 million this year, down slightly from 52.8 million at this time last year. Refunds have been certified for 78 percent _ 41 million _ of the returns that have been processed, compared with 79 percent at this time last year. Refunds are averaging $ 830, up from $ 815. New restrictions on itemized deductions and higher standard deductions have significantly reduced the number of couples and individuals who are itemizing, <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> said. The one dark spot on this tax season, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> agree, is that taxpayers still find it difficult to get the correct answer when they telephone tax questions to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> provided the right answer to only 62 percent of the 1,523 test calls made by <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. A broader <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> survey, 15,000 calls, produced the correct response to 72.1 percent of the questions. In each survey, the accuracy rate was up slightly from a February check. `` You get better odds in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>,'' grumbled Rep. <PERSON> J.J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickle </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> oversight subcommittee. `` We must and will improve our accuracy rate for our customers,'' <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> promised. He mentioned plans to make telephone `` assistors'' full-time, rather than seasonal, employees; to raise their pay and to give each immediate access to computerized information necessary to answer questions. Despite all the confusion about new laws and complicated forms, the subcommittee was told, taxpayers are having fewer problems than anticipated: _ The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has received 15.7 million telephone calls for information this year, up 12.6 percent from last year but 7.8 percent fewer than expected _ Errors are showing up on 20.7 percent of returns, about 1.4 percentage points above last year `` The amount of the increase has been less than expected,'' said <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> Deputy Director <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Finch </PERSON>. _ About 42 percent of the returns filed so far have been prepared by professionals, up from 40 percent last year but less than in 1986 Some experts had predicted most taxpayers would have to turn to professionals because of the new law. <PERSON> Finch </PERSON> said 48 percent of 892 taxpayers surveyed in four states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> had more trouble filling out this year's returns than last year's. Another 30 percent found little difference, and 12 percent said this year's were easier. Ten percent were not sure.
</TEXT>
