<SECOND>PM-Banking Deregulation,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nader Asks Congress to Keep Banks Out Of Securities Deals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumer advocate <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> wants <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to reject efforts to restructure the nation's financial system to allow banks and securities firms broad latitude to affiliate for the first time since 1933. <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Responsive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION>, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee Wednesday that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should not repeal the provisions of the 1933 Glass-Steagall Act which prohibit banks and bank holding companies from underwriting and dealing in corporate securities. Specifically, <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> said banking organizations should continue to be barred from dealing in the following securities activities: _ Underwriting or dealing in corporate debt or equity securities _ Sponsorship or investment management of mutual funds comprised of corporate debt or equity securities _ Underwriting securities collateralized by their own loans <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> told the subcommittee that commerical bank underwriting and dealing in corporate securities `` involves serious conflicts of interest that can injure public investors, undermine the integrity of capital markets and are not readily controlled by any realistically available set of safeguards.'' Before <PERSON> Nader </PERSON> testified, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, told the subcommittee the regulatory agency endorses Senate-passed legislation to permit banks to enter the securities business `` so long as adequate safeguards are established to address investor protection concerns.'' <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> believes the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> legislation, sponsored by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wisc </LOCATION>., has adequate safeguards for the repeal of Glass-Steagall Act, which separated banking from the securities business in the aftermath of the 1929 financial crash `` The commission supports modification or repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act as long as the investor protection concerns arising from the entry of banks into securities activities are simultaneously addressed,'' he said.
