<HEAD>Hollywood In Charge Of Look, Sound, Feel of Democratic National
Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hollywood will add its touch to the ready-made theater of the Democratic National Convention this summer, but producers say the professional flourishes will be tasteful and relevant. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hired the entertainment production company of Smith-Hemion to produce and stage the <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> convention _ believed to be the first time the Democrats have brought in theatrical producers to stage their convention. Smith-Hemion has a history of staging `` events'' and has earned 20 Emmy awards over the years for its television extravaganzas, said partner <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. Festivities like the Liberty Weekend celebration in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, television's `` We the People 200'' featuring <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Cronkite </PERSON>, and <ORGANIZATION> Disneyland </ORGANIZATION>'s 25th anniversary party were produced by the company. Smith-Hemion will work with the media, create `` the look'' of the arena, design the podium, oversee the sound and use big screens to provide visual elements that have been pre-taped in support of the speeches, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> explained. `` Even in a convention there is room for relevant entertainment _ tasteful and relevant,'' he said, adding that in his opinion a convention should be more than a series of speeches. The agenda of the convention is up to the Democrats, he emphasized, but the producers will supply `` things that are emotionally effective or emotionally motivated and good information that is visually enhanced.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said it was too early to identify entertainers or special effects to be used during the convention. Those things will be part of the it, he said, `` but the Democrats have not gone into show business. The most important priority is the need to maintain their agenda.'' <PERSON> Smith-Hemion </PERSON>'s team of about 100 people started working six weeks ago and will continue working until the convention is staged July 18-21 in The Omni. `` This is a news event that TVs are picking up. Opening ceremony on Liberty Weekend was a bit created. This convention is an official American event. We would do it whether it was on television or not,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. He said the convention is more meaningful to him because `` if I have ever been affiliated with any party, it would be Democratic. But I have always voted for the person, not the party.'' In addition to the staging and production work, Smith-Hemion will provide closed circuit, gavel-to-gavel coverage that will be available by satellite to every television station in the country, he said. The art director for the convention is <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Lagler </PERSON>, who worked on both Liberty Weekend and the 1984 Olympics in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` He is designing the look of the podium and how the arena will look from a scenic standpoint,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. How will Smith-Hemion rate the success of its work? `` I do n't think ratings will enter into it whatsoever,'' he said of the television ratings which usually tell networks whether they have scored a commercial success. Emmy nominations and awards are a measure of creative success, but that wo n't be a good gauge in this case either, he said. It will come down to whether `` the <ORGANIZATION> DNC </ORGANIZATION> says we did a good job,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, who refused to identify a favorite candidate. If the Democratic nominee wins the presidential race in November, `` that would make us feel pretty good. Obviously that is the ultimate goal _ to win the election come November,'' he said.
