<HEAD>One In Five Train Crews In Accidents Had Positive Drug, Alcohol
Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> report shows that drug and alcohol abuse by railroad crew members has become `` a runaway train,'' a senator says. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., offered that characterization on Wednesday after the report was released by <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> It reported that one in five crews involved in train accidents during 1987 had at least one member test positive for drugs or alcohol. The finding came during a review of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s policy of requiring railroad workers in major accidents to submit to drug and alcohol tests. On Feb. 11, the testing was struck down as unconstitutional by the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. But the program remains in place while the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration appeals. `` Substance abuse on the rails is fast becoming a runaway train,'' said <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, who requested the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study. Of 179 accidents during 1987, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> found at least one positive drug or alcohol finding in 37, or about 20 percent. However, the report did not identify in how many of those cases the drugs or alcohol actually figured in the accident. In all, 42, or 5.5 percent, of 770 rail workers sampled last year following accidents tested positive for alcohol or illicit drugs, said the <ORGANIZATION> FRA </ORGANIZATION>, which released its own figures this week in answer to a reporter's query. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> also reported that the amount of time needed to report drug and alcohol test results has substantially improved. In April 1987, it took an average of 16.2 working days to report initial screening test results for accidents where all crew members tested negative. By October, the reporting time had been reduced to 4.8 working days, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. It takes longer when positive results are found, because they must be confirmed. <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> had complained that long lags were hampering investigations and unfairly placing suspicion on innocent crew members. FRA ended an agreement with a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> laboratory in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> in March 1987 because it said it discovered discrepancies in the results, according to <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. In April, <ORGANIZATION> FRA </ORGANIZATION> contracted with a toxicology center at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> for the tests.
