<FIRST>r w PM-ElderlyAlone     04-14 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elderly Alone,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independent Elderly Live Longer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elderly people living alone are more likely to maintain their independence and live longer if they visit with friends and neighbors and attend church or other group events, a government study reports. And people over age 70 who live alone are more likely to survive over a two-year period than those who live with someone, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> found in the study made public Wednesday. Both living alone and engaging in various activities were indications of better health. The less active elderly were more likely to die or become institutionalized over time. There is a noticeable difference for those people who have contact with friends ands neighbors, who go to church or synagogue or attend sports events, reported Dr. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Kovar </PERSON>, author of the study. Her findings in `` Aging in the Eighties, People Living Alone _ Two Years Later'' are based on interviews in 1984 and 1986 with people who were 70 and older in 1984. Of those living alone who reported regular meetings with friends and neighbors in 1984, 92.5 percent were still alive two years later and 89.3 percent were still living on their own. On the other hand, of those who had no such contact, 86.6 percent survived two years and 81.5 percent still lived alone. For regular churchgoers in 1984, 94.9 percent survived two years and 91.9 percent were still alone. Of those who did n't attend church or synagogue, 86.2 percent survived and 81.9 percent lived on their own. But regular contact with family did not seem a significant factor in longer life and more independence. Perhaps those reporting extra family contacts needed the help because they were not well, <PERSON> Kovar </PERSON> speculated. `` Children may have come around more frequently ... just to make sure'' the older folks were all right, she said. `` The most important thing -LRB- found in the study -RRB- is the stability,'' <PERSON> Kovar </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. `` Most of these people, two years later, are still living in the community. Those who were living alone are still alone, and those with someone else are still with someone else,'' she said. `` As you would expect, because these people are 72 or older, death rates are high. But relatively few of them are in nursing homes,'' she noted. Of nearly 6.4 million elderly people living alone in 1984, 89.8 percent were still alive two years later, she found. By comparison, 89.0 percent of those living with a spouse survived two years and 84.3 percent who had been living with someone else were still alive. Of those who had been on their own in 1984, <PERSON> Kovar </PERSON> found that by 1986, 77.8 percent were still living by themselves. Some 7.4 percent of them had moved in with someone else _ most often family _ and 4.6 percent were in an institution. `` It certainly appears that for some of them life is better'' two years later, she added. `` Some have remarried _ not many but some _ and when we asked those who had moved why ... we got'' answers ranging from health to being nearer to children to spending the summer in <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and winter in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. One, she said, even cited lower golf fees for moving. A major factor in continued independence is likely that those living alone were more healthy at the start of the study, she concluded in the report. Health was also a factor in the stability of those living alone, she found. For example, people who needed help with basic daily activities such as bathing, dressing, eating or using the toilet, were much more likely to have died over the two year span. While only about 10 percent of all those living alone died in the two year period, 25 percent of those who had needed help in basic daily activities died and 16 percent were in nursing homes after two years. `` It is very difficult ... to disentangle'' all the factors affecting these people, she said. Another follow-up series of interviews is scheduled for this summer, to compare the same group of elderly in 1988. Overall, she found that nursing homes appear to be a last resort for the elderly. These is evidence of a progression, she reported, `` people live alone, then with other people if others are available, then they may become nursing home residents.''
</TEXT>
