 Former Attorney General <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> is representing the survivors of 15 Libyans killed during the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing raid of <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION> two years ago in a civil suit for damages against the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, who has been criticized in the past for dealing with nations hostile to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, filed the lawsuit Wednesday to collect unspecified damages for the deaths, property damage and injuries to 40 other Libyans. The suit, filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, charged that the April 14, 1986 bombing violated `` settled principles of international law'' in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Charter and numerous treaties and declarations. It charged the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration purposely hid the real purpose of the bombing _ which the suit said was to kill <LOCATION> Libyan </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Moammar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ghadafi </PERSON> and to `` terrorize Libyans by inflicting injury upon the civilian population in order to undermine support'' for their leader. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said the raid was in retaliation for the anti-American attacks authorized by <PERSON> Ghadafi </PERSON>, including the bombing of a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> discotheque frequented by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> servicemen that killed two and injured 150 others. The lawsuit charged that top governent officials, including President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, `` are guilty of conduct constituting clear violations of settled principles of international law prohibiting the use of force by a state against the territorial integrity of political independence of another state.'' Among the victims of the bombing raid was a 3-month-old girl who died when hit by shrapnel while asleep in her home in <LOCATION> Benghazi </LOCATION>. The child's 38-year-old father was also killed by shrapnel, according to the complaint. The suit, filed under the Alien Tort Statute and the Federal Tort Claims Act, said claims for compensation by the victims or their survivors were rejected last October by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>. The suit named <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> individually and in his capacity as commander in chief of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed forces. British Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> was sued for approving the use of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military bases in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to launch the attacks. Also sued were former <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> and top military officials, including Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION> and retired Gen. <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, former supreme allied commender in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The estate of the late <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> was also named as a defendant in the case, which was assigned to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Penfield </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, who served as attorney general under President <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, has been criticized over several years for dealing with foreign governments whose interests conflict with this country. In 1980 he attended a `` Crimes of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' conference in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> while American hostages were being held in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>. He also was criticized in 1972 for traveling to <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION> to investigate the effects of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bombing during the Vietnam War.
