<HEAD>Few Of The Large Voting Blocs Have Settled On Democratic Favorite</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Most black and Jewish voters have coalesced around the two chief competitors in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Democratic presidential primary but other potentially large voting blocs remain fragmented, political analysts say. Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>'s attempt to outflank Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for the Jewish vote appears destined to fall short, an expert in Jewish opinion said Wednesday. And <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s strength remains greatest with blacks, said other experts. The analysts said other major groups _ such as union members, homosexuals and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholics </ORGANIZATION> _ do not seem to be drawn to any of the candidates by a single overriding issue in next Tuesday's vote. What then may come into play for these <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> voters is the pragmatic issue of which candidate is most likely to win the presidency, said <PERSON> Meyer </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Frucher </PERSON>, a leading political strategist. A key battle has been for Jews, up to a quarter of the Democratic vote. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> has sought their support by placing himself to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' right on <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> policy, flatly opposing formation of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state. The hard line may help <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, where 25 percent of the 400,000 Jews are in the Orthodox sect, said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, a sociology professor at <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> who has polled Jewish attitudes for a decade. But the effort likely will fail overall, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said, because <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> are close enough on <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> policy for either to be acceptable to the majority of Jews, and <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> appeals to them on other grounds. `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is seen as friendly because he's a Northeast liberal ethnic,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. `` He's our type of guy.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has received black backing in the 90-percent range in other states, and blacks, like Jews, account for up to a quarter of the Democratic vote in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. He also may count on broad support from Hispanics, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Alicea </PERSON>, a Hispanic leader. But in 1984, Hispanics made up just 4 percent of the state primary vote. Organized labor is divided, said <PERSON> Theodore </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kheel </PERSON>, a longtime labor mediator in the city. The Central Labor Council and the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> are neutral, he said, while local leaders `` are all over the lot.'' In the absence of a defining issue, <ORGANIZATION> Catholics </ORGANIZATION> also do not constitute a strong voting block, and `` I do n't think there's going to be a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> groundswell for any <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON>, editor of The Tablet, the newspaper of the Archdiocese of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION>. Nonetheless, said pollster <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Miringoff </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Marist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opinion </ORGANIZATION>, `` I think the white ethnic vote is going to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> at this point.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a Greek-American, also expects enthusiastic support from the <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> community, which has about 65,000 adult <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens in the city. Homosexuals are in far more of a quandary. Many activists reject <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> because of his opposition to homosexual couples as foster parents, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Lambda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> and Education Fund. But many fear <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> or <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> would lose to the Republican. The result is that some voters will go for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who is viewed overall as better on homosexual issues, said <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON>. Those less concerned about the foster parent issues will back <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. A few will vote for <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, whose standing is `` uncertain'' on homosexual issues other than AIDS. `` Some,' <PERSON> Stoddard </PERSON> added, `` will simply stay home.''
