<HEAD>Lawmakers Ask Unions to Accept End to Trade Bill's Plant-Closings
Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democratic leaders are asking unions to go along with dropping mandatory notice of plant closings from the sweeping congressional trade bill because of threats of a presidential veto. But union representatives refused to relent Wednesday in a three-hour meeting with the leaders behind closed doors, according to sources who asked not to be identified by name. `` We're still searching,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, told reporters following the session in the office of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. Va.. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> declined to go Warnings that the plant-closings measure could prompt President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to use his veto power and thus scuttle the entire 1,000-page trade bill failed to move representatives of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> and several other labor groups, according to the sources. Under the provision in question, companies with at least 100 employees would be required to provide 60 days notice of plant closings and layoffs involving at least one-third of their work force. Layoffs involving 500 workers or more would have to be preceded by notice even if less than one-third of the work force is involved. Labor representatives called on the leaders to push forward with the plant-closings provision in defiance of repeated veto threats from members of President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s Cabinet. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> issued the latest warning Tuesday. Labor representatives left the session without commenting to reporters, as did a number of congressional participants. Besides <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, those on hand were <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass The disputed measure, part of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version of the trade bill but not that passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, has aroused passionate opposition among several business groups. They say it could be the first step toward taking control of companies away from management. Supporters say something must be done to end circumstances in which factory workers with families arrive at work to find that the plant is closed permanently and their job has vanished. At the heart of the trade bill are provisions that would transfer to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative authority to retaliate against international violations by the nation's trading partners and other `` unjustifiable'' practices. The president currently has that authority. Main provisions also would streamline machinery for imposing import curbs to aid threatened <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industries. The bill contains scores of other provisions ranging from repeal of the windfall profits tax on oil companies to tighter monitoring of lamb imports. In recent days, a chief concern of lawmakers has been finding a formula that would guarantee that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would sign the bill. A hint that leaders were leaning toward dropping the provision came earlier Wednesday when <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told reporters it would still represent `` a good bill'' if shorn of the plant-closings feature. He did say it would be `` a better bill with that provision'' included. Republicans, who furnished much of the opposition to the plant-closings provision, were not party to the talks with labor representatives. But dropping the provision could prove a touchy matter. Sponsors, including Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, and Rep. <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, D-Calif., pressed ahead and succeeded in inserting the feature in the bill amid a hailstorm of administration veto threats <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the only plant-closings sponsor in the afternoon session, was asked during a brief break whether he was making any progress in saving the measure. He said merely: `` We'll see.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>, in a study last year, estimated that two out of every three workers are not told they are losing their job until the day they are taken off the payroll. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> said in a report last June that the voluntary notices advocated by the administration and business do not now provide workers with the `` minimum two or three months necessary to adjust successfully to job loss.''
