<HEAD>Administration Waited Four Years To Act On Law Protecting Dolphins</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senators are criticizing the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration for taking four years to implement a law aimed at reducing the number of dolphins that drown when they are snared by huge tuna nets in the eastern <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>. `` Wholly inadequate,'' says <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass. `` An embarrassment,'' adds <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>., one of the authors of the 1984 law passed by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in an effort to put teeth into the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972 The 1984 statute requires the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to bar importation of tuna caught by a foreign nation if its tuna boats fail to take steps to protect dolphins, as the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tuna industry is required to do. `` The foreign tuna fleet in the eastern tropical <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> is killing over 100,000 dolphins a year and our government agencies have done little to implement the 1984 changes designed to address the problem,'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said Wednesday at a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> hearing. <PERSON> Dolphin </PERSON> kills began increasing in the late 1950s, when tuna fishermen switched from baited hooks to gigantic seines. For reasons unclear to biologists, the popular yellowfin tuna congregate beneath groups of surface-swimming dolphin, which then serve to mark the tuna schools to fishing boats. Conservationists estimate that some 6 million of the mammals have drowned over the years after being trapped in tuna nets. `` We face a serious situation in the tropical <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>,'' testified <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mammal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. He said preliminary findings from a dolphin census show some stocks are smaller than thought and others are declining. Because of improved netting techniques, the number of Dolphin kills by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> tuna boats has dropped from 368,000 in 1972 to 13,992 last year, the hearing was told. Foreign kills reportedly fell from 423,678 in 1972 to an estimated maximum of 82,000, compared to 108,767 in 1986 and 37,505 in 1985. Only recently did the fisheries service publish regulations to carry out the 1984 law. They would give foreign tuna fleets until 1991 to match the performance of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> fleet, which is allowed to kill up to 20,500 dolphins a year. `` Why are we waiting until 1991?'' asked Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif. `` I think we should pursue why it will take until 1991 to impose these import restrictions. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said, `` It bothers me enormously we've allowed this situation to drag on. It's really sad. I do n't know what you people are doing sitting down there.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s acting assistant administrator for fisheries, said, `` we're not particularly proud of the amount of time it took to do these regulations.'' He said regulators walked a tightrope, wanting to reduce foreign fleet dolphin kills without causing other nations to give up the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market and continue to fish for tuna without adopting techniques to save dolphins. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Burney </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tuna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, an industry group, said foreign tuna fleets should adopt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> methods. `` There is no excuse for them not having done that,'' he said. `` It should have been done three years ago.''
