<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGRA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrat <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> says <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> lacks foreign policy experience and `` simply does n't know what he's talking about'' when it comes to using nuclear weapons and American military power. Trying to catch up with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> before Tuesday's important <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> maintained Wednesday that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had made `` a major blunder'' by discussing in a newspaper interview when he would use nuclear weapons against the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. He stood by his criticism in the face of a strong denial by <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor said he had merely reflected existing American and <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> policy in holding open the option of a nuclear response to a successful Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> with conventional forces. The <LOCATION> Tennesse </LOCATION> senator offered broader criticism as well, faulting <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for advocating a ban on flight testing of ballistic missiles and for what he said were remarks supporting the commitment of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> troops in the event of Communist invaders in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` I think in a lot of these matters he simply does n't know what he's talking about, and he needs an opportunity to clarify his remarks and I want to give him an opportuhity to do so,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said to reporters. A long-distance exchange between the two candidates was touched off by an interview with <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> published Wednesday in the Daily News of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> characterized <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' remarks as amounting to saying `` he would launch a nuclear first strike against the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> if they invaded <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> with conventional forces.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, insisted <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> was distorting his comments. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said his position was that he would consider the use of nuclear forces as an option in the event of a successful Soviet invasion of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` That has been the policy of our government,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` It is the policy of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance.'' In a transcript provided by the newspaper, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was asked if he could conceive of a scenario in which he would use nuclear weapons first, `` as a strategic weapon.'' His response began, `` Yes, yes. I would hope I would n't have to.'' He said he was for `` a policy of no early first use. But our present strategy in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> assumes that if the Soviets were to invade and conventional forces could n't stop them that we'd reserve the right to use nuclear force.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON>, the defense and foreign policy adviser to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> started answering the question thinking he was being asked about tactical nuclear weapons. The reference to `` strategic'' was made after <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had started speaking, <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Steinberg </PERSON> said he assumed <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> would have given a different answer had he understood the question to be about strategic nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> campaign manager <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> insisted <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> had not distorted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' words. Both <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had erred in getting into a discussion of nuclear first use. `` I think it is most unwise for a president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or a major candidate for the presidency to be drawn into a hypothetical discussion of when we would launch our nuclear forces and trigger destruction of human civilization,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. `` To specify in advance when we would make that fateful step is most unwise and irresponsible.'' Appearing later before <LOCATION> Westchester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Democrats in <LOCATION> Rye </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> stressed that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had been asked about `` strategic'' nuclear weapons. `` <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> has purposely refused to respond to that hypothetical,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. `` The president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has traditionally refused to respond to that hypothetical.'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s criticism and the ensuing flap overshadowed an event Wednesday when <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> went to the Love Canal toxic waste site at <LOCATION> Niagra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> to underscore his commitment to environmental protection and blast the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. As a congressman, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> chaired congressional hearings that looked into the dumping of toxic wastes at the site.
