<FIRST>r a PM-HolocaustTutor     04-14 0590</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holocaust Tutor,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sociologist Explains the Holocaust to New Hampshire Children</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CR1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETSY HENDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KEENE, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a junior high classroom in a state with fewer than 3,000 Jews, sociologist <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> holds up a photograph of <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> and speaks about the need to be a `` witness'' to the Holocaust. `` What were Aryans?'' <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> asked his <ORGANIZATION> Keene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Junior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> students Wednesday. <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> directs the <ORGANIZATION> Keene </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holocaust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resource </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, a library of more than 1,400 books, thousands of articles, films, slides and videotapes that opened in 1983. The five `` gifted and talented'' children whose parents permitted them to attend the optional, after-school course screwed up their faces, indicating they did n't know about Aryans. `` They were supposed to be the super-race with blonde hair, blue eyes, tall and strong,'' said <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON>. `` The supermen that would conquer the world, the super-race that would destroy all these inferior races like the Jews.'' The children, who like <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> are <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION>, nodded solemnly. This week, as groups across the country hold Holocaust memorials to mark the 45th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> ghetto uprisings, <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> is doing his part to ensure that the 6 million Jews who died in Nazi death camps are not forgotten and that similar atrocities never happen again. Education is `` what it's all about,'' he said. His lesson is not lost on some of his students. `` It's not going to happen again because we listen and because they're teaching us about it. If no one had said anything, then it could easily happen again,'' said 11-year-old <PERSON> Erin </PERSON> <PERSON> Buzuvis </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> was asked why <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION> needed the Holocaust center, since its Jewish population is estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manchesterat </ORGANIZATION> at fewer than 3,000, or less than one-third of one percent of the population. `` Why not?'' he replied. `` There should be a center everywhere.'' As the state's handful of concentration camp survivors and liberators die, it's even more important to convey the facts, he said. <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> says many textbook writers are minimizing the Holocaust; some even question the facts. `` There has to be a witness,'' he said. <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> does not dwell on the horror, but believes that explaining the true events gradually is important. But how does a teacher gradually describe genocide? How can gas chambers and starvation be introduced without trauma? <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> advises elementary school teachers simply to begin with classes on prejudice and less gruesome topics. For more advanced children, he recommends two books: One is about a little girl, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Blanche </PERSON>, who sneaks food through the barbed wire fence at a death camp. Her name, which means white rose, is also the name of a German youth group that resisted <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> and eventually was eliminated. Another is about a little girl discovering concentration camp numbers tatooed on her grandfather's arm and his explaining how they got there. The book, illustrated by photographs of a girl and an <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> survivor, ends with the granddaughter saying, `` You should n't be ashamed to let people see your number. You did n't do anything wrong. It's the Nazis who should be ashamed.'' By junior high and high school, <PERSON> Hildebrandt </PERSON> says, students generally are better able to hear a more complete truth. Still, a couple of the children displayed some prejudices that seem to indicate why Holocaust education is important _ especially in areas with few minorities. `` It could n't happen again because ... Jews are n't so Jewish anymore,'' said one. `` They're more civilized,'' said another. `` They know more. They act more like regular people.''
</TEXT>
