<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets 3rdLd-Writethru a0458 04-14 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0458,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Dollar And Stock Prices Fall Slightly In Early Tokyo Activity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing figures</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s key stock market indicator closed Thursday at an all-time high, surpassing the 27,000-point level for the first time, while the dollar eased against the Japanese yen. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 54.71-point winner Wednesday, added another 125.80 points, or 0.46 percent, finishing the day at 27,111.35. The dollar closed at 126.15 yen, down 0.30 yen from its 126.45 yen finish on Wednesday. It had opened the day at 126.20 yen and ranged between 126.10-126 .43 yen A dealer at a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment firm, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Wednesday's meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of top finance officials from seven major industrialized powers produced `` nothing substantial.'' The so-called Group of Seven nations are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. In issuing its two-page joint communique Wednesday, the group announced the extension of a Dec. 22 agreement in which the seven nations pledged to work together to keep the dollar currency from falling further against the yen. `` The market was not looking for anything concrete from the meeting,'' and it resulted in nothing new, the dealer said. He said Thursday's release in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for February would have a greater effect on the movement of the dollar, and likely would support the currency. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit reports have affected the dollar's direction in recent years because the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration has supported a lower dollar as a way of narrowing the gap.
