<HEAD>PLO Seeks to Dismiss Action to Close U.N. Observer Mission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge has refused one request to temporarily block legal action to close the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> observer mission. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Palmieri </PERSON> has scheduled an April 20 hearing on another request to block enforcement of the 1987 Anti-Terrorism Act. The law declared the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and its affiliates a terrorist organization. Meanwhile, lawyers for the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> are seeking to dismiss a federal lawsuit that would force the closing of the mission. The government's lawsuit seeks a court order barring the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Zehdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Labib </PERSON> <PERSON> Terzi </PERSON>, head of the observer mission; and five other mission officials or employees from continuing to operate the mission or any other <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> office in this country. But <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> counsel <PERSON> Ramsey </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney general, said in papers filed Monday at federal court that no <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court has jurisdiction to issue such an order because it would violate international law as well as the treaty setting up <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has yet to file a response. In a related matter, <PERSON> Palmieri </PERSON> refused on Tuesday to grant a preliminary injunction, blocking enforcement of the Anti-Terrorism Act. He ruled that a group of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens who say the act violates their First Amendment rights had shown insufficient proof th