<FIRST>r a PM-WrongCounty     04-14 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wrong County,0678</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial in Wrong County Starts Ethical, Legal Arguments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The mistrial granted to a murder defendant whose case was prosecuted in the wrong county has triggered debate on whether he should go free, and on the ethics of his lawyer, who knew about the error but kept mum. `` All this guy's got going for him is me,'' public defender <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` If I've got to help the prosecutor, my God, he'd be better off without a lawyer.'' <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiefelbein </PERSON>, 38, was accused of fatally stabbing a man who invited him to dinner Christmas Eve 1986 at an <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> home that purportedly straddles the line between <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> counties. The mistrial was granted April 6, the second day of his trial in <ORGANIZATION> Fulton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, when a prosecutor learned that the house actually is in <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and that <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> had known it all along. <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> contends that his client should go free because a second prosecution, this time in <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, would violate the constitutional prohibition against double jeopardy. `` It would be a miscarriage of justice if he were able to escape because of a problem like that,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, chief assistant district attorney in <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, where the state may press for a trial. Law officers in both counties assured prosecutors the house was in <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Finley </PERSON>, who learned the truth when she telephoned a witness after the first day of <PERSON> Schiefelbein </PERSON>'s trial. Ms. <PERSON> Finley </PERSON> said she was reviewing the next day's testimony with the owner of the house when `` he informed me that his house was in fact about two houses over the line in <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>.'' The next day, <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> said he had known of the mixup and Judge <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Etheridge </PERSON> declared a mistrial, telling <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> he had `` wasted a lot of time and did your client absolutely no service whatever.'' <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> said Wednesday it `` never even occurred to me'' to tell the judge earlier because ethics rules for lawyers require him to use any defense that is not frivolous. <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> `` had an obligation not to say anything,'' said <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> professor of legal ethics and the main draftsman of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s model code of ethics. `` The defendant in a criminal case is permitted to require the state to go to its proof on every possible issue, and it's the state's responsibility to carry the burden in that respect,'' Hazard said. `` The defendant did nothing to mislead the prosecution, and I think -LRB- <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> -RRB- did the right thing.'' <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Georgia </ORGANIZATION> law professor <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> said legal codes of ethics discourage disclosures of information by defense lawyers but conflict with a lawyer's duties as an officer of the court. `` Frankly, I sympathize with the lawyer,'' said <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON>, a former dean of <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s law school. `` The courts have not given good guidance on this. They've waffled on the issue.'' <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> says federal courts have held that part of a criminal case is proving it is being brought in the right court, so failure to prove that voids the entire prosecution. Another trial would be double jeopardy, he said. <PERSON> Etheridge </PERSON> disagreed with that argument, saying his court never really had jurisdiction over the case so `` anything we did would be a nullity.'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> DeKalb </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutors already have found legal precedents supporting a retrial, but no decision will be made until the case file and the judge's order are received from <LOCATION> Fulton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON> also contends that there are factual issues in the case. He said victim <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadden </PERSON>, <PERSON> Schiefelbein </PERSON> and others in the house had been drinking, that no one thought <PERSON> Hadden </PERSON>'s wound was serious enough to summon help, and he might have died simply from a lack of medical attention. <PERSON> Schiefelbein </PERSON> also contends <PERSON> Hadden </PERSON> was choking him, he said.
