<HEAD>Prisoner Tells of Sandinista Abuse, Threats _ Says Cubans Involved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pilot held five years in Sandinista prisons said he was threatened with death and denied medical treatment as part of systematic psychological torture apparently directed by <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> intelligence agents. <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Amador </PERSON>, 42, shot down during a Contra supply flight in 1983, was one of the first prisoners freed as part of last month's truce agreement between the Nicaraguan Resistance and the leftist Sandinista government He arrived here Saturday to join his wife and three children. <PERSON> Amador </PERSON> and other Contra officials said at a news conference here Wednesday they believe there are up to 12,000 political prisoners inside Nicaraguan jails despite government claims to the contrary. <PERSON> Amador </PERSON> said he had been threatened before leaving <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and told not to talk to reporters. `` They told me, ` If you make declarations to the press in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, we will put a bomb in your car in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> or anywhere else you go,''' said <PERSON> Amador </PERSON>. They reminded him of the assassination of former Nicaraguan dicator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION> after he fled the Sandinista revolution in 1979. <PERSON> Amador </PERSON>, 42, said at least three of the seven crew members on his doomed 1983 flight died in Sandinista hands even though all survived the crash of their plane, which he said was flying medicine, books and clothes to the rebels. When they were captured, some of the men were bound hand and foot and flown to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chipote </LOCATION> prison in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. `` We expected death at any minute,'' said <PERSON> Amador </PERSON>. `` They said they were going to kill us.'' Two crew members stayed behind and were never heard from again, and he later found a third was officially reported dead. At the prison, where he was kept in solitary confinement for 1 -LCB- years, <PERSON> Amador </PERSON> was regularly seated for 12 to 16 hours in a chair while he was threatened and interrogated. In the partially darkened room, he said, he could hear Cuban-accented men speaking Spanish and occasionally heard German, which he believed was spoken by East German advisers. Two Cuban exile Contra sympathizers still in prison in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> later told him they were being interrogated by Cuban G-2 intelligence agents, he said. He said he believes the Cubans were teaching their techniques to the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. `` They worked on the mind with constant death threats,'' said <PERSON> Amador </PERSON>. `` They told me if I did n't talk they would get my family in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, they would kill my children, and they would kill me.'' At one point they falsely claimed they were holding `` someone I loved,'' the pilot said. He said the guards held drills in which they would send soldiers to the door of each cell and point a Soviet-made rifle at the prisoners. `` They were waiting for an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> invasion,'' said <PERSON> Amador </PERSON>. `` They said as soon as the 82nd -LRB- Airborne Division -RRB- landed, we would be eliminated.'' <PERSON> Amador </PERSON> said he was told his family, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the resistance had abandoned him. The pilot suffered what he later found out was a crushed disc during his crash landing, and was in constant pain, which his interrogators used against him, he said. `` They would open the cabinet and show me the medicine for my pain,'' he said. `` Then they would say, ` are you going to talk?''' He said he refused and was never given the pain-reliever. Doctors in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> later said his jailers had unintentionally helped him by forcing him to sleep on the floor, giving some relief to his back.
