<HEAD>KGB Chief Blames National Unrest On Education, Secret Services</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> secret police blamed ethnic unrest that broke out in two southern republics and other areas of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on poor education and foreign secret services. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON>'s speech on Wednesday in the <LOCATION> Volga </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Cheboksary </LOCATION> was his first public comment on ethnic tensions in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> since rioting occurred in the <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> republic on Feb. 28. At least 32 people were killed in the rioting, 26 of them ethnic Armenians. Thousands of people began mass protests in neighboring <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> in mid-February to demand that the <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> be annexed to <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>. Three-quarters of the region's residents are ethnic Armenians, who traditionally are Christians. Azerbaijanis traditionally are Moslems. <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> did not mention <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, but said `` anti-social actions of a nationalistic nature took place in a number of regions of this country,'' according to a report issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency. `` I believe that one of the major reasons for those anti-social actions is a serious negliect of the internationalist education of popular masses,'' <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> was quoted as saying. He also blamed wrong approaches to solving social-economic problems, and said `` groundless notions'' about the problem-free development of relations between nationalities also played a part. The latter was an apparent reference to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s claims in the past to have solved the problem of relations among nationalities Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said at a <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting in February that the problem is one of the country's most serious, and that the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> will devote an upcoming meeting to it. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, a country of more than 100 ethnic groups, tries to teach citizens to de-emphasize nationalistic feelings in favor of what is termed a spirit of friendship and equality with other ethnic groups. But ethnic groups often resent domination by Russians and other Slavs, and ages-old tensions exist among some of the ethnic groups. <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> also said that foreign secret service organizations that he did not identify played a part in stirring up ethnic tensions. `` It is an open secrety that secret services of imperalist powers and foreign anti-Soviet centers actively join extremist nationalistic actions,'' he said. `` Later on they start playing the part of open instigators of hostile actions aimed at kindling hostility among nations,'' <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> said. `` One should not underestimate the danger of this method of subversive actions against this country. However, in my opinion, the main attention should be concentrated on a timely solution of the emerging socio-economic problems, on the education in patriotic and internationalist spirit,'' he said. In a televised speech in September, <PERSON> Chebrikov </PERSON> accused the West of trying to undermine Soviet economic reforms and sow discord among nationalities. Besides the tensions in <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION>, there also has been an increase in nationalist activities in the Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>, and among Crimean Tatars who were deported from their homeland by <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON> because of alleged cooperation with Nazi invaders in World War II.
