<HEAD>Study: Prison Population, Already at Capacity, to Grow 21 Percent
by 1992</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Get-tough criminal laws may satisfy public opinion, but they are failing to cut crime rates and are forcing prison officials to cope with even more prison crowding, a new study concludes. `` The prison route, the idea that we ought to send everybody to prison and keep them there, just does n't work,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Crime and Delinquency. `` In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, for instance, the number of inmates has tripled since 1977, and the crime rate has not dropped 1 percent,'' he said Wednesday. The mandatory sentencing laws _ so-called `` get-tough'' measures _ will play a key role in the projected 21 percent increase in the nation's prison population by 1992, said <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, director of research for the San Francisco-based criminal-justice think tank. The study, based on the crime and incarceration rates for nine states, projects a 30 percent increase in parolees over the same five-year period. The nine states studied were <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. Again using <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> as an example, <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said its current inmate population of 69,000 could almost double to 125,000 within 10 years. `` I'm not saying it's going to happen,'' he said, `` but it certainly could happen if we keep the current policies intact.'' <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said the money for prisons is siphoning off funds that could be used for other human services _ medical, education and welfare _ that eventually might make a dent in prison population growth. `` The generation we need to be concerned about is not the one in prison right now, but the kids who are 10, 11 and 12 years,'' <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said at a news conference. The most immediate solution to crowding is early-release programs for prisoners not in maximum security, he said. <PERSON> Austin </PERSON> said the average prison term is two years, and simply trimming three months from each would provide significant relief, `` especially since studies have shown us that releasing these people early does n't drive up the -LRB- crime -RRB- rate.'' The new study also highlighted several problems correctional officials likely will face in the future, including an aging inmate population requiring expensive medical services and an increasing number of black and Hispanic males in prison.
