<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 7, The Edison, with 1 graf to give industry
reaction.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> today declined to establish a new clean air standard to protect asthmatics from peak exposures to sulfur dioxide that might last only a few minutes. Those exposures might occur around sources that meet all current standards based on longer measurement times, sources like coal-burning power plants, smelters and factory boilers. A burst of emissions from a plant, or even rare wind patterns, might cause people living nearby to face high concentrations briefly. Environmentalists denounced the decision embodied in a draft affirmation of current standards. `` There is a whole slew of evidence'' accumulated since 1980 that many asthmatics are not being protected by current standards, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, claiming that `` for this administration the wishes of the utility industry always come first.'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuhnke </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> said his organization would try to get a court to order a short-term standard established. At the <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the principal trade association for utilities, spokeswoman <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision `` reflects a careful weighing of all the scientific evidence. She said current standards reduced average sulfur dioxide concentrations by 37 percent between 1977 and 1986. The institute has said a stringent short-term standard could be as costly as an acid rain control program, perhaps $ 5 billion a year. Sulfur dioxide is the major raw material for acid rain, but acid rain is not an issue in <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision about ground-level concentrations of sulfur dioxide. According to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement, new studies have found `` measurable changes in respiratory function and symptomatic effects _ shortness of breath, wheezing, coughing _ in asthmatics exposed for short periods, five to 10 minutes up to one hour, to 0.4 parts per million of sulfur dioxide or more.'' But it said `` these response occurred predominantly in subjects who were exercising and not using preventive medication at the time.'' It added that the effects `` appear to be transient and reversible and, at lower concentrations, are similar to those most asthmatics typically experience from exercise or other stimuli, for example, cold air.'' These effects are not like an `` asthma attack,'' and asthmatics on medication `` will likely not experience a response'' to a short-term peak, the agency said. <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON> said: `` I do n't know of any responsible group of scientists that takes that position. The -LRB- agency -RRB- argument is, just because there are other things that make asthmatics ill, it's OK for power plants to make asthmatics ill.'' Only about 1 percent of the national population of asthmatics, estimated by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> as 30 million people, would be exposed to short-term peaks, <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said
