<HEAD>Warm March Saves $450 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans saved $ 450 million on their heating bills last month thanks to warmer-than-normal weather over most of the nation, the government reported today. That means that a typical homeowner paid $ 88.46 to keep warm during the month, $ 6.26 less than would have been expected in normal March weather, according to figures compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. Savings peaked in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> states, where the average home heating bill of $ 54.28 was $ 9.52 below normal. The average bill of $ 54.79 in the <LOCATION> west </LOCATION> <LOCATION> south </LOCATION> <LOCATION> central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> states </LOCATION> was just about normal for the month. Here is a regional rundown of March heating costs for a typical household and the comparison to costs in normal March weather. _ <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>: $ 126.98, or $ 8.73 below normal Includes <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. _ New <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>: $ 114.63, or $ 4.88 below normal Includes <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. _ East North Central: $ 103.65, or $ 5.84 below normal Includes <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. _ East South Central: $ 86.84, or $ 2.63 below normal Includes <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>. _ Mountain, $ 85.71, or $ 5.71 below normal Includes <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. _ West North Central: $ 83.02, or $ 9.43 below normal Includes <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION>. _ <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>: $ 75.22, or $ 4.42 below normal Includes <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. _ West South Central: $ 54.79, normal Includes <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>. _ <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>: $ 54.28, or $ 9.52 below normal Includes <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> are not included in the monthly weather impacts report.
