<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON> said today that he foresees more bloodshed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> because an accord to end Soviet military involvement there does not address the issue of a new Afghan government. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> said that as long as the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government remains in power and the guerrillas fight to overthrow it, the war will continue and an estimated 5 million Afghan refugees will not be able to return home safely. `` I see trouble and turmoil in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> through the insurgency, through the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> trying to achieve their objective to overthrow this regime and establish their own authority, and that will mean more loss of life,'' <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> told reporters at an informal news briefing. `` That will mean insurgency in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> will not stop unless the Afghan <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> have achieved their end.'' When asked why <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> agreed to sign the accord in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> today, <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> cited the provision calling for the withdrawal of Soviet troops backing the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which borders <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and hosts about 3 million of the 5 million Afghan refugees, represented the rebels in the talks. He said the withdrawal `` made the task of the <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> less strenuous,'' implying that it would be easier for the guerrillas to overthrow the communist regime. `` Once they're -LRB- Soviets -RRB- withdrawn, the logical conclusion ... -LRB- is -RRB- that it will be a little difficult for the present regime to stand for a longer period,'' <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> said. The accord signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> does not guarantee the end of the 10-year-old war in <LOCATION> A