<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A terrorism task force is investigating a Japanese national arrested on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turnpike </LOCATION> with three homemade bombs, each powerful enough to destroy a building, authorities said. The suspect was identified by <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> police today as <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Kikumura </PERSON>, 35, a former bookstore owner who was extradited to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> by the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> two years ago on charges of illegal possession of explosives. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, acting <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Koichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Haraguchi </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> `` has a strong suspicion that he -LRB- Kikumura -RRB- might have a relationship with the <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>,'' a terrorist group that gained notoriety for a series of attacks abroad in the 1970s. However, Japanese police `` have n't made a final conclusion that he is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Haraguchi </PERSON> told a news conference. <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> news service in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Kikumura </PERSON>'s arrest had raised suspicions the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> might be planning attacks during the summit of leaders of advanced industrial nations June 19 in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. The task force was formed by state police and <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> agents in response to concerns about the sophistication of the bombs found in the suspect's car, and `` inquiries from overseas,'' state police Superintendent <PER