<SECOND>PM-Space Station,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Station Completion Will Be Delayed One Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> gave a bad news-good news report to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> today on the impact of money cutbacks for building a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space station: completion will be delayed one year, but a robot laboratory on the station will be in operation earlier than planned. `` The realities of the federal budget environment are clear,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON>, administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, wrote to the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Committees that oversee the space agency. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> had asked for $ 767 million for the space station in the current fiscal year but received $ 425 million. The agency wanted $ 1.8 billion in the year that begins next Oct. 1, but the president's budget proposal would give it $ 1 billion. In letters to Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boland </PERSON>, D-Mass., and Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, R-Wis., <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said that left the agency three options: cutting down on the station, changing the way the program is managed or stretching out the time to build the <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said the third approach `` is the only sensible way'' since more than four years and $ 600 million already have gone into planning the station configuration and because the program management is solid and is producing results. Under the schedule he outlined, the first flight ferrying building materials for the station into space will be early in 1995, a year later than planned. It would be completed in late 1996. The fourth flight, rather than the sixth, will carry aloft a laboratory that can be `` man-tended'' _ visited and serviced periodically by astronauts. `` This approach basically involves a reordering of the assembly sequence leading towards this nation's goal in the mid-1990s _ a permanent presence in space,'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> wrote. Originally, the plans had been to have the station up and running in 1992, the 500th anniversary of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>' discovery of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said the new assembly sequence delays the bulk of attached sicence payloads until later in the construction sequence. It will take 16 flights to have the full station in operation and 11 flights before crews can be housed on the station.
