<HEAD>Ukrainian Crop Yields Increase, Despite Chernobyl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crop yields in the Soviet <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> have increased despite the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear accident two years ago, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. The official news agency said the April 26, 1986, disaster caused no `` irreparable damage'' to the region's agriculture. Chernobyl is about 80 miles north of the Ukrainian capital of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>. In the seven months after a blast and fire split open one of Chernobyl's reactors, 31 people died. Thousands were exposed to dangerous levels of radiation. There were concerns that the agriculture of the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, traditionally one of the breadbasket regions of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, might suffer from the release of radiation. <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Alexei </PERSON> <PERSON> Denisenko </PERSON>, deputy chairman of the state agro-industrial committee of the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, as saying all farm products within the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> area are checked for radiation and pronounced safe before they are sold. He said grain yields per hectare in the <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> region, which includes Chernobyl, were up by 31 percent in 1987 as compared with the previous year. Such increases are not believed linked to mutations in plants that might be caused by radiation, he said. `` Crop rises are attributed only to introduction of intensive technologies of cultivation, as well as to intrduction of contract forms of labor organization,'' <PERSON> Denisenko </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Denisenko </PERSON> said the type of crops grown at some farms were switched on the recommendation of scientists. For instance, farms which had been growing vegetables now are planted in grain and potatoes which do not accumulate radioactive decay products, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said.
