<HEAD>Shultz Says US Will Continue Arming Afghan Rebels</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto GEV7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> on Thursday pledged continued supplies of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms to Moslem guerrillas fighting the Communist government in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> after he signed the accord on the withdrawal of Soviet troops. After eight years and four months of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> pleas with the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> to pull its soldiers out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and Foreign Minster <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> put their signatures on an accord requiring Soviet withdrawal by Feb. 15, 1989. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 and an estimated 115,000 now are there helping fight the Moslem insurgency. The secretary acknowledged that <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s future remains cloudy. Although the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> is leaving, he said, the superpowers will continue arming the factions and more work by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> will be needed to establish an independent government and bring home the estimated 5 million Afghan refugees. `` I do n't think anyone knows how that will take place,'' he told a news conference, but added: `` History has been made today.'' <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> mediator <PERSON> Diego </PERSON> <PERSON> Cordovez </PERSON> negotiated the agreement signed Thursday by <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, and by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as guarantors. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told reporters: `` For over eight years the <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> people have suffered a brutal war that has brought unmeasurable death, dislocation and dest