<HEAD>Uninsured Workers Tell Hard-Luck Stories To House Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Uninsured workers with medical problems told their hard-luck stories Thursday to a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel weighing a sweeping plan to require that employers offer minimum health benefits. The employees _ including a a grocery store clerk from <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and a doctors' office receptionist from <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> _ said they have had to cope with inadequate medical care, unaffordable bills or both. <PERSON> Annette </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>, the receptionist, said the federal Medicaid program paid for her daughter <PERSON> Colleen </PERSON>'s two-month stay in the hospital after she was born prematurely. But she said five subsequent hospital stays have cost $ 22,000 _ and there's no one to pay it but herself and her husband on their wages of $ 6 an hour each. `` Even if I paid $ 100 every month, she'd be in college if not out of college by the time we ended up paying this bill,'' said Mrs. <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON>. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, the clerk, said his parents were uninsured, had diabetes and died in their 30s for lack of proper medical care. He said he has diabetes and no insurance, and must depend on clinics with spotty care and no evening hours. `` If I get sick I must choose between working and supporting my family or going to the doctor and losing a day's pay,'' said <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>. `` If my employer had a mandatory insurance program, I could go to a regular pharmacy and see a doctor in the evening.'' The testimony came at a hearing before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on health and the environment. There are an estimated 37.2 million Americans without health insurance. About two-thirds of them are workers or dependents who would be covered by the plan under consideration by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. The bill, introduced by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., and Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., would require employers to provide a minimum package of health insurance to people working 17.5 hours a week or Benefits would have to include hospital and doctor care, prenatal and well-baby care, diagnostic testing and catastrophic protection. Employers would pay at least 80 percent of the premium. Pool arrangements and a phase-in period would make plans more affordable to small or new firms. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version of the bill, already approved by <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, also says very small or new employers would only have to provide catastrophic protection. The business community is divided on the plan. Many firms say they are philosophically opposed to mandated benefits, but corporations with health plans complain they are indirectly footing the bill for firms without them. The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, representing hundreds of Fortune 500 companies and other employers, said in a statement Thursday that `` with each month, we hear from more members who think that a federal mandate is far from the worst alternative. And, many of the changes we wanted have been accepted.'' <PERSON> Willis </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldbeck </PERSON>, president of the group, said the Kennedy-Waxman bill `` clearly does not have the support of the business community'' but said there is `` considerable strength to the growing trend of acceptance among many major companies.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lester </PERSON>, owner of a small carpentry and construction business in <LOCATION> Warren </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, said the bill would help small companies like his. He said he offers health insurance as an ethical obligation but its high cost keeps him from expanding. Furthermore, <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> said, `` in my attempts to be responsible now and in the future, I am put at a competitive disadvantage against those -LRB- employers -RRB- who do not insure.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> is a prime opponent of the Kennedy-Waxman bill and said Thursday it would cause many workers to lose other benefits and maybe even their jobs. The group is proposing alternatives it says would encourage rather than require employers to offer coverage. Among them: eliminating state minimum benefit requirements and allowing unincorporated businesses the same tax deductions enjoyed by incorporated firms. The state of <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> has a law similar to the Kennedy-Waxman bill. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> legislature on Wednesday passed an even more sweeping measure that guarantees health coverage to everyone, not just people with jobs.
