Supreme Court spokeswoman saying case will have to go through
normal appeals process.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman underwent an abortion in defiance of a court order obtained by the would-be father, but attorneys for both sides still want the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to settle the dispute. At issue is whether a woman has the sole authority to decide to have an abortion or if a father has rights that give him a say in the decision. Attorneys for the 18-year-old Terre Haute woman told the high court Wednesday that she had terminated her first-trimester pregnancy, but said the decision was hers alone. Their notice came a day after they asked the high court for an immediate review of the lower court injunction that prohibited an abortion. A spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said today that the case will go through the normal appeals process because speed is no longer essential. `` The case will go through the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> since it is not an emergency any more,'' said the spokeswoman. `` It probably will get back to us eventually. But there is no emergency now, and it has to go through the channels.'' A 61-page brief by the man's attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said the woman's reasons for wanting an abortion are `` an immature reasoning process, are insubstantial and border on the frivolous, and do not outweigh the strong interests of the father in seeing the child born and in his custody.'' <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> described the woman as an unemployed high school dropout who began a relationship with the man, a delivery truck driver in Terre Haute, following a date on New Year's Eve. The lower court ruling cited testimony that the woman wanted an abortion to preserve her figure so she would look good in a bathing suit and to avoid being pregnant during the summer, <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> said. The woman's attorneys refused to say where or when the abortion was performed. `` Faced with the decision of continuing with an unwanted pregnancy and with violating a court order, she made the decision she felt was right,'' said the notice signed by her attorney, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waples </PERSON>, legal director of the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>. `` She did what she had to do to protect both her physical and emotional health,'' it said. <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON>, general counsel for the national Right to Life organization, said Wednesday he thinks `` somebody was exploiting and victimizing her to get her to get an abortion.'' `` An extremely serious and distressing thing has happened,'' he said, adding that his client `` is absolutely devastated that his child has been taken from him.'' <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> said he and his client have n't considered seeking a contempt citation against the woman for violating <ORGANIZATION> Vigo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s order issued last week. On Monday, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> issued a permanent injunction. `` He loves this girl,'' <PERSON> Bopp </PERSON> said of his 24-year-old client. `` He's not interested in punishing her.'' If allowed to stand, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s ruling invites other <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> courts `` to engage in the same pernicious and impermissible inquiry into, and overruling of, a competent adult woman's decision to terminate her first trimester pregnancy,'' <PERSON> Waples </PERSON> told the court. The woman's attorneys said her first trimester would have ended sometime during the next two weeks. <PERSON> Waples </PERSON> argued <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s inj