<FIRST>r w AM-Inventories     04-14 0472</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Inventories,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rise in Business Inventories Slows After Months of Big Gains</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Deficit Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rebounding sales helped dampen growth of business inventories in February to a slight 0.1 percent after four big monthly increases, the government reported Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said inventories increased by only $ 825 million, pushing the total of unsold items on store shelves and backlots to a seasonally adjusted $ 715.9 billion. The small gain followed a string of much steeper increases that came in the months after the stock market crash. Inventories rose 0.7 percent in January, 0.9 percent in December, 0.8 percent in November and 1.2 percent in October. Economists had feared the inventory buildup would force production cutbacks and slow economic growth early in 1988. But Thursday's inventory numbers, along with a separate report on trade showing a $ 2.3 bilion increase in imports in February, provide evidence that domestic demand has not weakened. The February increase in goods held on shelves and backlots was occurring while business sales were climbing 0.6 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 468.3 billion, reversing a 0.5 percent drop in January. `` It's really two sides of the same puzzle,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, who heads <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` If inventories continued to rise at the same time that sales were falling, that would clearly be bad news. ... But that's not happening ... so it's OK.'' <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Chimerine </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Wefa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, a forecasting service headquartered near <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, said imports were at least partially responsible for the inventory growth `` A lot of the inventories that had built up were imported goods. ... That's one of the reasons I'm less concerned about the trade numbers than I might have been,'' he said. Another <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report Thursday showed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> merchandise trade deficit widened to $ 13.8 billion in February from $ 12.4 billion in January. The February rise in inventories was held back by a 1.1 percent fall in inventories held by retailers. This decrease reflected primarily a 5.2 percent drop in the backlog of unsold cars. Excluding autos, retail inventories were up 0.4 percent. Inventories held at the wholesale level were up 0.9 percent, while manufacturers' inventories grew by 0.5 percent. The 0.6 percent overall sales rise was led by a 1.2 percent increase in wholesale sales in February, a 0.6 percent rise in sales by retailers and a 0.1 percent rise in sales by manufacturers. In an advance report on Wednesday, the government said retail sales increased 0.8 percent in March. The combination of rising sales and slightly rising inventories pushed the inventory to sales ratio down from 1.54 in January to 1.53 in February. That means it would take 1.53 months to exhaust inventories at the February sales pace. That ratio is not considered abnormally high.
</TEXT>
