<HEAD>Retiring Pilots Started Out When Flying Was Man's Work</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT PLEASANT, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If you wanted to spend as much time in the air as <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sylvia </PERSON> <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>, you'd have to lift off right now and not set your plane down until late 1992. The two _ pilots, flight instructors and business partners with a combined total of more than 40,000 hours of flying time _ retire their wings this year. Ms. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who was one of the first women in the state to receive the pilot examiners rating back in the 1950s, retires Friday, while Ms. <PERSON> Roth </PERSON> plans to retire in June. She was the first woman in the nation to be designated an airline transport pilot examiner by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in 1968. The women, both 62, will be honored Friday by the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. They ran a flight school in <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> for 16 years. Over their combined 90-year careers, they've taught thousands of pilots to fly and many of their former charges now are with major airlines around the world. But flying was a man's pursuit when they started flying. `` I started when I was 17,'' Ms. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` I just wanted to fly.'' `` Airplanes were something different. And <PERSON> Amelia </PERSON> <PERSON> Earhart </PERSON> was doing her thing at that time,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Roth </PERSON>. `` They were doing all sorts of different things and setting records.'' Flying is easier today than it once was _ what with better planes and more sophisticated cockpit equipment, they said. But it's not quite as much fun, Ms. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. `` When I was learning to fly there were so few restrictions,'' she said. `` You could take an airplane _ a J-3 Cub that did n't have anything in it but an air speed indicator and altimeter _ and just go anywhere in the country.'' During their careers of teaching students the two have had `` close calls but no disasters,'' Ms. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. Student pilots tend to react in predictable ways, and instructors can usually anticipate problems. `` You know what to expect,'' she said. `` Most people have the same apprehensions and the same fears.''
