<HEAD>PCBs From Mother's Milk Passed Down Six Generations, Researcher
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Toxic PCBs passed from mother to child through breast milk will still be measurable in the parent's great-great-great grandchildren, a <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> researcher told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee Thursday `` The problem is, these compounds refuse to go away for any reasonable amount of time,'' said <PERSON> Wayland </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swain </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Eco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, in testimony before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on investigations and oversight. <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> drew on earlier research into the transmission of polychlorinated biphenyls _ PCBs for short _ to calculate the level of the substance passed to an infant through nursing and retained in the infant's body. An infant nursed by a mother who regularly consumed <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> fish would be exposed to 6.2 milligrams of <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> by the end of 12 months, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. Of that amount, 5.3 milligrams would be retained in the infant's body. `` It is clear that infants nursed by mothers who have consumed <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> fish exceed recommended consumption guidelines -LRB- for adults -RRB- for their entire breast-feeding experience,'' <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. The level of PCBs retained by such infants was more than seven times the maximum consumption level recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. PCBs are passed to a child not only through beast feeding but from the mother's body through the placenta before birth, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. A 20-year-old woman giving birth to a child passes on sufficient PCBs so that even if all exposure to the substance were stopped, `` I would still measure PCB in the body fat ... six generations in the future,'' <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said. Production of PCBs, believed to cause cancer, has been banned for years, but the substance continues to enter the environment through such sources as older electric transformers. Recent research suggests that the decline in <ORGANIZATION> PCB </ORGANIZATION> levels in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lakes </LOCATION> has slowed, and that the substance continues to circulate from the sediment into the water and back into the sediment again in a perpetual cycle that produces continuing contamination of the food chain. Children exposed the PCBs as infants tend to be shorter, have smaller heads, be more likely to catch infectious diseases, and exhibit an inability to focus on their surroundings, <PERSON> Swain </PERSON> said.
