 </LOCATION>. She allegedly was carrying several leaflets and clippings from `` the bourgeois press with fabrications about the Chernobyl accident, concealed in her luggage.'' `` She also attempted absent-mindedly to leave behind in her train compartment a maliciously slanderous book called ` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Quadrille,''' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. Another tourist, who was not identified, was caught carrying dozens of copies of `` People on the March,'' a pamphlet which authorities say urges Soviets of ethnic German origin to emigrate to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` Some of the latest items of ideological contraband include video recordings of various sermons, karate lessons, with a sadistic bent, pornography and anti-Soviet films like ` Rambo' or the <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> ` Afghan Series,''' the dispatch said. The latter was apparently a reference to the <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON> movie `` The Living Daylights,'' in which the fictional British agent 007, played by <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dalton </PERSON>, outwits the Soviet army in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Soviet officials have bitterly complained that <PERSON> Sylvester </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallone </PERSON>'s muscled Vietnam War veteran Rambo presents a negative stereotype of Soviets. The report from <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said people carrying material judged to be ideological contraband will be deported from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.
