<FIRST>u w AM-TaxFreedom Bjt   04-14 0686</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Freedom, Bjt,670</SECOND>
<NOTE>For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Average American Will Have Paid Tax Obligation by May 5 This Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The `` average'' American will have to work 126 days this year _ two more than in 1987 _ just to pay federal, state and local taxes, the <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. `` Tax Freedom Day'' will fall on May 5, the latest ever. The best taxpayers have fared in the past decade was in 1984 _ when most of the big 1981 federal income-tax reduction had taken effect _ when Tax Freedom Day fell on April 28, economists for the foundation said. But federal tax increases enacted in 1982, 1984 and 1987 `` have lopped off big chunks of the'81 cuts, and Social Security hikes have made further inroads until, like the <LOCATION> Cheshire </LOCATION> Cat in ` Alice in Wonderland,' nothing remains but the smile,'' the foundation said. Last year, the big day was May 4; this year's May 5 date is two days later because 1988 is a leap year, which meant there was a Feb. 29 this year. With the approach of the Friday midnight deadline for filing federal tax returns _ the first under the heavily revised tax law _ there were these other tax developments: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, whose telephone `` assistors'' have been giving the wrong answer to about 28 of every 100 tax questions this year, disclosed some factors it will consider in determining whether to waive certain penalties for taxpayers who follow such bad advice The agency said penalties for late filing, negligence and failure to pay can be waived if the taxpayers proves he or she acted reasonably. It will consider pertinent factors such as whether the taxpayer also sought the correct answer in an <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> publication, as well as what specific question was asked of the assistor and what was the actual answer. It also would help the taxpayer to know the name of the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employee and the time and date of the telephone call. _ House Republicans and several business organizations began a campaign to block future income-tax increases, amend the Constitution to require a balanced budget and pass a `` bill of rights'' to help taxpayers in disputes with the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> Seventy-eight <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> representatives have signed a promise to oppose raising income taxes, while 190 -LRB- mostly Republicans -RRB- lawmakers have signed a petition requiring the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to allow a vote on the balanced-budget amendment. Such a vote requires the assent of 218 representatives. `` The federal budget can be balanced in less than four years without raising taxes if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> controls the growth of spending to less than the inflation rate,'' <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Keating </PERSON>, vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taxpayers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers. _ The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> released a survey indicating that 75 percent of business owners polled think the tax laws are more complex since the 1986 revision About 55 percent say their companies are spending more time on tax forms, but two-thirds would not be willing to pay more in order to get simpler taxes. The <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based research organization, assumes that individuals pay all taxes _ including those collected from corporations _ when it calculates Tax Freedom Day. The economists simply divide all federal, state and local tax collections among taxpayers and assume that every penny earned each year goes to government until tax obligations are satisfied. Viewed from another perspective, the foundation estimates the average taxpayer will work 1 hour and 50 minutes each eight-hour day to pay federal taxes, and another 55 minutes for state and local taxes. That's two minutes longer for federal taxes than in 1987 but the same as last year for state and local taxes. By the same measure, housing will require 1 hour and 24 minutes -LRB- unchanged -RRB-; food and tobacco, 56 minutes -LRB- two minutes less -RRB-; transportation 40 minutes -LRB- unchanged -RRB-; medical care 39 minutes -LRB- unchanged -RRB-; clothing 22 minutes -LRB- one minute less -RRB-; recreation 21 minutes -LRB- unchanged -RRB-; and everything else will take 53 minutes of work, one minute less than last year.
</TEXT>
