<HEAD>With AM-Helmsleys</HEAD>
<HEAD>The King, The Queen, &amp; Court</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhotos</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> bought his first property, a dilapidated office building, for $ 1,000 in 1936. A decade later he sold it for $ 165,000; now his real estate equity is estimated at $ 1.4 billion. <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Mindy </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenthal </PERSON>, the daughter of a <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> hatmaker, had been the <LOCATION> Chesterfield </LOCATION> cigarette girl before she settled on a career in real estate and, ultimately, married <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>. Now this king of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> real estate and the queen of the <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> hotel chain are in a court devoid of royalty; they surrendered Thursday and pleaded innocent to federal and state charges of tax evasion, falsifying business records and, in <PERSON> Leona </PERSON>'s case, extortion conspiracy The charges are so shocking because they involve people whose wealth is nearly unbounded. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> was listed 21st on the Forbes list of the 400 richest Americans last year; he owns the Empire State Building. Their estate in <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, central to the charges, consists of a 28-room Tudor mansion on 29 acres. But that is not the only <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> residence: <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> also spend time at a duplex atop the Park Lane Hotel, and at a lakefront condominium in <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> shower each other with gifts -LRB- sometimes paid for with company money, according to the indictment -RRB- and their generosity sometimes extends to others In 1986, they made the single largest philanthropic gesture in the country, giving $ 33 million to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. Neither of the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> was born of wealth. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>'s father was a notions buyer for a wholesale dry goods firm; the son graduated from high school but never attended college. His first job, as office boy at the real-estate firm he eventually came to own, paid $ 12 a week. His credo? `` All you have to do is buy, and if you make a mistake, the market comes along and takes care of it,'' he once said. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 79, owns 50,000 apartments and 7 million feet of commercial space. He bought the Empire State Building, then the world's tallest building, in the 1950s: `` Every morning you would look out of the window and the building is staring you in the face. So, you'd say, ` Well, I got ta buy it.'' On July 4, 1976, <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> lit the Empire State Building in red, white and blue _ a tribute not to the Bicentennial, but to his wife's birthday. It cost $ 100,000. `` It was less than a necklace,'' he said. <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>, 67, is <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>'s second wife; his previous marriage ended in divorce in 1972 after 33 years, with no children. <PERSON> Leona </PERSON>, too, was married before, to a lawyer whom she divorced in 1959. Her only son died in 1982. The former showroom model and advertising mannequin was a successful real estate broker when <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> met her in 1971; he hired her as a $ 500,000-a-year senior vice president and married her a year later. By all accounts, she is just wild about <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>; <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION> records that she calls him `` gorgeous one ... pussycat ... snooky, wooky, dooky.'' Shortly after their marriage, in 1973, a man wearing a gas mask broke into their <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> bedroom. `` Wake up darling, we have company,'' <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> told her husband, nudging him awake. The naked Helmsleys chased the intruder, but before he fled he stabbed <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> in the chest with a bread knife, puncturing her lung. When <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> put <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> in charge of the <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> hotels in 1980, he was not providing her with a sinecure. She took complete charge, and became the star of ads for the hotel chain which trumpeted her demanding nature as a guarantee of quality. `` It's the only palace in the world where the Queen stands guard,'' said one ad for the Helmsley Palace in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. The royal appellation is matched by a volatile, queen-size temper, according to many employees. `` She comes on as extremely forthright, but that sometimes turns into brutality,'' said one former employee, advertising executive <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Maas </PERSON>. `` She's icy, without compassion; she is remorseless and pitiless.'' According to the federal indictment, <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> did more than harass her employees _ she shook them down, demanding kickbacks in exchange for their continued employment. Sources said some two dozen <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> employees testified before the grand jury under grant of immunity. <PERSON> Harry </PERSON>, by contrast, is known as a courtly gentleman. He does not envy <PERSON> Leona </PERSON>'s celebrity _ the ads, the interviews, the profiles on `` 60 Minutes.'' `` I think one person should take the limelight. It dilutes if there are two,'' <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> said in 1986. `` I have a different aspect of the business. I like to plan buildings, organize them and finance them. Once I build it, I could n't care less, and that's where she comes in. She is fantastic at entertaining and day-to-day operations _ details I hate. The only thing I like is adding up a column of figures and getting the bottom line.'' Even prior to their latest legal problems, <PERSON> Leona </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON> received some unwelcome publicity when it was reported she failed to pay more than $ 38,000 in sales tax for jewelry at <ORGANIZATION> Van </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cleef </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Arpels. She was never charged, but sources said she was given immunity for her cooperation with authorities. Then last year, a series of reports in the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> detailed allegations that the <ORGANIZATION> Helmsleys </ORGANIZATION> had charged millions of dollars in renovations of their <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> mansion to their business. Those revelations, the basis of the indictments, were fueled by tips from the Queen's disgruntled subjects. `` Most of the calls seem to have been prompted by people's dislike of Mrs. <PERSON> Helmsley </PERSON>,'' said Post reporter <PERSON> Ransdell </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierson </PERSON>
