<HEAD>Historian Urges Setting National Arts Goals for 1990s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> says he will urge President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s successor to appoint a special commission to set national arts policy goals for the 1990s, which he predicted will be a decade of `` innovation, experiment and idealism.'' `` The time for revaluation is upon us, and it should take place at the highest level,'' said <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, a Pulitzer Prize-winning historian and former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> adviser to Presidents Kennedy and <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> delivered the first <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanks </PERSON> Lecture on Arts and Public Policy here Wednesday night in honor of the late chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> during the <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administration. The lecture and a black-tie dinner were cosponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit arts advocacy organization, with support from the <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON>, a humanities professor at <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, said that after `` the last rather static years'' of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration, the nation is ready to renew its commitment to government support of the arts and find ways to ease artists' growing financial burdens `` We must pay more attention to the unintended consequences of legislation indirectly affecting the arts,'' he said. <PERSON> Schlesinger </PERSON> complained that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was `` notably harsh in its treatment of writers and artists'' when it abolished charitable deductions for non-itemizers in 1986 and prohibited artists from deducting expenses until they begin receiving income from their works. `` Government, instead of carelessly discriminating against writers and artists, should at least give them a fair shake in the tax code and elsewhere, especially when most writers and artists and their families live from hand to mouth anyway,'' he said.
