<HEAD>Parliament Approves Private Television In Spain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> voted Thursday to end the 32-year state monopoly on television broadcasting by passing a law authorizing the creation of three private TV networks. The law takes effect following publication in the Official State Bulletin. The law stipulates that no individual nor group may own more than 25 percent of any of the three networks, a provision seen by major publishing groups as an attempt to limit the influence of the established media. Participation of foreign investors is limited to a second 25 percent share in any of the three networks. There are two state-controlled national television networks in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and three more local networks controlled by the regional governments of <LOCATION> Galicia </LOCATION>, the Basque Country and <LOCATION> Catalonia </LOCATION>. Spanish National Television was founded in 1956 during the authoritarian regime of Gen. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>. Spaniards watch more TV than citizens of the other 11 <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> member nations except <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. Channel 10, a London-based company with <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> and foreign participation, began broadcasting in <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> via satellite in January. Since entering office in 1982, the government of Socialist Prime Minister <PERSON> Felipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> had pledged to enact legislation creating three nationwide private TV networks. Minister of <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> and Tourism <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> <PERSON> Caballero </PERSON> has estimated that none of the three networks will be ready to go on the air for 18 months to three years following enactment of the law. The ministry has estimated the cost of upgrading the existing transmission network and land lines at between $ 45 million to $ 180 million. Once the new law goes into effect, the government is expected to request public bids for the private network licenses based on criteria to be set by the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. In the last three years, several publishing groups in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> have formed groups in preparation for the bidding.
