trim. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Government and <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> leaders today agreed to renew technical talks on implementing a cease-fire and to start high-level negotiations to end the six-year civil war. The stalled cease-fire technical talks were to start immediately in the southern border post of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, site of earlier meetings. The high-level talks were to start in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Friday. A government delegation traveled to <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> almost immediately after the agreement was announced at noon by the Contras and <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinoza </PERSON>, information minister for the leftist Sandinista government. The Sandinistas backed off from their demand that the technical talks be held in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and agreed to a Contra request that they be in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. In exchange, the Contras stopped insisting that Friday's political talks begin only if the Sapoa talks were successful. `` The Contras agreed that if the talks are not finished today, they'll conclude in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Espinoza </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> in a telephone interview. Earlier today, <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> representatives <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> and <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Stadthagen </PERSON> flew into the capital's Sandino airport in a private aircraft and were met by Tourism Minister <PERSON> Herty </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewites </PERSON>. It was the first time the government had allowed Contras into <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. On Wednesday, a Sandinista negotiator accused the Contras of not being serious about ending the civil war. `` We have serious doubts they want to enter into a definitive cease-fire,'' Deputy Foreign Minister <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Tinoco </PERSON> told reporter. `` There's a problem of confidence,'' he said, adding that the Nicaraguan government did not want to see the talks unravel. `` If they -LRB- Contras -RRB- do n't come on the 15th -LRB- Friday -RRB-, we'll have to see the alternatives.'' The cease-fire pact was signed March 23 in <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>. The talks are to work out details of how to get Contra forces into several zones inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> as a prelude to ending the war. The military talks stalled April 8 after six rounds in which the two sides agreed only to establish seven zones to which Contra fighters would be confined during a 60-day truce that went into effect on April 1. Still to be worked out are security for the rebels in those zones, methods of resupplying them and other details concerning the guerrillas during the two months allowed for negotiating a permanent cease-fire. Rebel fighters are scheduled to be in the zones by Friday, but they have not even begun gathering. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have agreed that once they verify the rebels are in the zones, half of the 1,400 jailed Contras will be freed. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is estimated to have more than 3,000 political prisoners. The Sandinistas released 100 soon after the provisional truce was signed.
