<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> frigate on patrol in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> apparently struck an underwater mine today, injuring six sailors, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said today. The ship, the USS <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, was in no danger of sinking, said <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON>. No one was killed and the six sailors did not sustain life-threatening injuries, he added. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said that four of the sailors had second-degree burns; the other two had slight back injuries. None of the injuries was considered life-threatening. All were flown from by helicopter from the ship for medical treatment. The ship is based in <LOCATION> Newport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, and left there for <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> duty on Jan. 11. `` At approximately 10:10 this morning EDT, the USS <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> ... experienced an underwater explosion in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> at a point approximately 70 miles due east of <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bell </LOCATION> -LRB- a navigational aid -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. The explosion `` caused flooding in the engine room and some hull damage. The flooding is under control, and the ship is in the process of pumping out the water. It's operating under auxiliary power.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said that the USS Wainwright, a cruiser, `` is en route to the site to offer assistance and should be there soon.'' The incident occurred in the central <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, well to the south of the spot near the Iranian-controlled <LOCATION> Farsi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> where a reflagged Kuwaiti tanker, the <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, hit a mine during the first of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s convoy operation last July. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said there had been no recent reports by mine-sweepers in the area that mines had been sighted. The spokesman refused to say that the underwater explosion had been caused by a mine, citing the paucity of information from initial reports. `` It really is too early to tell,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. `` Underwater explosion is the way to describe it. We do n't know what caused the explosion. All we've got is an underwater explosion at this point.'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was steaming in the area after completing an escort operation Wednesday night. The spokesman said he assumed `` there were no other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vessels in close proximity,'' but could n't say for sure. `` They say the flooding is under control and they're pumping the thing out and doing that under auxiliary power,'' <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> said. Within hours of the explosion, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said, the ship had begun steaming toward port in <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>. The <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> is the same type of guided-missile frigate as the USS Stark, the frigate that was hit last May in an Iraqi air attack. Thirty-seven Americans died in that attack. Ships of the <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazard </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> class normally carry a crew of about 190 sailors and 13 officers. The Pentagon said the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was carrying about 225 men, however, because it had a helicopter detachment aboard from <LOCATION> Mayport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>.. One Pentagon official who asked not to be named said the explosion `` does not appear to have been caused by any failure of systems on board the ship. Another source added: `` The <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> hit something; we are assuming it was a mine.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said the <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> was under the command of Cmdr. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> X. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rinn </PERSON>. It fixed the location of the explosion at 26.25 degrees north and 52.15 degrees east. At the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> had been told of the incident. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that he did not know how <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> was told, but that the president was `` routinely informed'' about such matters by national security adviser <PERSON> Colin </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> or a member of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> staff. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the incident `` only emphasizes our concern for stopping the Iran-Iraq war,'' which has led to the mining of the gulf. He said the administration intended to step up pressure in the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> for a resolution that would not only put an end to the war but put the group on record in favor of sanctions against belligerents in the war.
