<HEAD>Afhan Agreement Hailed in Both East &amp; West</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER C. PUTNAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The accord for a Soviet troop withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> was hailed Thursday by countries in both the East and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> as a vital first step toward peace, and some offered to help Afghan refugees. In southern <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, however, skepticism remained over some aspects of the plan, particularly the continued aid to combatants. The agreements, signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> by representatives of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, will take effect May 15 and will commit <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> not to support `` directly or indirectly, rebellious or secessionist activities'' against each other after nine years of civil war and Soviet entanglement. In <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> welcomed the agreements and said it hoped they would yield further improvements in superpower relations. `` The Soviet occupation of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> has been a serious impediment in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> relations,'' <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The implementation of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreements will, we hope, lead to further improvements in the atmosphere between East and West.'' Austrian Vice Chancellor and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Alois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mock </PERSON> called the agreements `` a step to the strengthening of East-West relaxation.'' The accords open the possibility that `` other regional conflicts be settled peacefully,'' <PERSON> Mock </PERSON> said. Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> expressed concern, however, about a continued flow of weapons to Afghan rebels and said some of them were reaching <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s Sikh extremists through neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The Sikh extremists, fighting for a separate nation in <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, used rocket-propelled grenades for the first time last month. Officials in the northwest Indian state say the rebels also have increased their stock of AK-47 assault rifles. Indian officials recently charged that <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> was helping Sikhs acquire weapons. <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> denied the charge. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION>, an independent English-language daily, said in an editorial titled `` Meaningless Agreement'': `` <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> will be able to withdraw its troops without having to acknowledge the plain fact that it has failed to pacify <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in the face of resistance by U.S.-backed mujahedeen. But on the face of it, the agreement will be pretty meaningless otherwise. `` For it will stipulate that the Americans and the Russians will continue to be entitled to provide arms to their respective clients. And while <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> will formally agree not to interfere in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s internal affairs, it will in reality continue to do so inasmuch as it will still serve as a conduit for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms supplies to the mujahedeen.'' The accord was praised in communist nations. Non-aligned communist <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, which has repeatedly condemned <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intervention in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, said the agreements represent `` an important first step which could lead to a final peace settlement in that country.'' In a commentary, the state <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said the final solution of the conflict is still far away because the region has been `` burdened by different international interests.'' `` All sides involved must now show maximum goodwill, statesman-like wisdom and responsibility,'' the Czechoslovak <ORGANIZATION> CTK </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. Both <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> said they would join a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> military force observing the accord in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, both neutral Scandinavian countries, also have agreed in principle to send observers to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Danish newspapers said <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> also have been asked to join the force, reportedly to be led by a Finnish general. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> planned to assist in the relocation of 5 million civilian refugees, said a Foreign Ministry spokesman in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Acting Foreign Ministry spokesman <PERSON> Koichi </PERSON> <PERSON> Haraguchi </PERSON> said, `` Also, it is our intention to extend financial assistance to facilitate the safe and honorable return of the refugees to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> also announced plans to aid refugees, with an $ 18.7 million grant for resettlement. Foreign Secretary Sir <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> said the grant was conditional on the setting up of `` properly coordinated international arrangements'' for the return of millions of Afghan refugees from neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>.
