<FIRST>r a AM-CondomPatrol     04-14 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Condom Patrol,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Used Condoms Collected From Sewage Plant To Test ``Safe Sex''
Advice</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Health workers are counting used condoms that float to the surface of the city's sewage treatment plant pools in an effort to find out how many people are heeding advice about safe sex to avoid AIDS. Hundreds of condoms float in the water at open-air pools at waste water treatment plants. For the last eight months, city workers have been using long-handled fish nets to scoop the multicolored condoms from the sewage and count them each day. The study, which should be completed in a year, may help determine whether people are heeding warnings to use condoms as a way to prevent the spread of the acquired immune deficiency syndrome virus, officials said. `` We talk a lot about using condoms, but the question is whether we're really doing it,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON>, who heads a federally funded AIDS study in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>. `` We're serious about it, we really want to find out whether more condoms are being used, or whether people are just buying them and storing them by the bedside for potential future use.'' The study includes counting the number of condoms sold at drugstores and those given away free by the health department, Ms. <PERSON> Dwyer </PERSON> said. Though officials do n't know how many condoms are flushed down toilets or simply thrown away, they said they had no intention of going through garbage. `` It's certainly not a very pleasant job, but it is important,'' said <PERSON> Courtland </PERSON> <PERSON> Storck </PERSON>, the AIDS surveillance supervisor for the health department. `` If it does work, and we hope it does, then hopefully other cities would adapt a similar program.'' The health department said it has so far retrieved between 200 and 400 condoms each day floating in the sewage pools. A <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> doctor first suggested the study method in <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, but officials say the first such count was made in the late 1970s in <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>.
