<DATELINE>OSWIECIM, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 1,500 Jewish youths, many carrying <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> flags, took part in a `` March of the Living'' Thursday at the site of the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Birkenau </LOCATION> death camps as <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> honored its victims of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, hundreds of academics and historians gathered at the State Jewish Theater for a two-day conference on the struggle and martyrdom of Jews and Poles during the 1939-45 Nazi occupation. The march and the conference began a week of observances of the 45th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Ghetto Uprising, in which several hundred Jews fought a three-week battle against <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s army. The uprising began April 19, 1943. The observance is the largest ever organized in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to honor the memory of the millions of victims of the Nazi Holocaust who died on Polish soil. Among those attending the conference were several Polish government ministers, senior <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials and <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> bishops. Despite the somber commemorations, the chief foreign ministry spokesman denounced <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for violating the basic human rights of young Palestinians demonstrating against the Israeli occupation of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stefan </PERSON> <PERSON> Staniszewski </PERSON> told a <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> news conference that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> wanted to pay homage to the Jewish ghetto fighters who `` were Polish citizens and ... fought together with us'' against the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION>. But he said `` this emotional attitude ... does not influence our policies towards <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' `` The brutality of the repressions used by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities toward the <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> population evokes popular outrage and condemnation around the world,'' said <PERSON> Staniszewski </PERSON>. `` We categorically protest against the Israeli policies.'' As light snow fell, the march began near the <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> camp's main gates, where the legend in German reads, `` Work makes you free. The blue-jacketed youths, marching behind a banner reading `` March of the Living,'' trekked two miles to the site of the <LOCATION> Birkenau </LOCATION> death camp. There, as a cold wind whistled through the vast open field still surrounded by double rows of barbed wire fences and wooden watch towers, the young Jews lit a memorial flame and scattered soil from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> by the monument. They followed a cantor in saying Kaddish, the Hebrew prayer for the dead. <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> is the German name for the Polish city of <LOCATION> Oswiecim </LOCATION>, where the camp was located. The monument also commemorates the camp at <LOCATION> Birkenau </LOCATION>, where the Germans built huge gas chambers and crematoria. In an emotional ceremony by the stark, gray international monument honoring those who died at the two camps, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> officials declared that only a strong Jewish state could prevent another Holocaust. The marchers carried blue-and-white <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> flags. `` It is the obligation of every Jew to feel solidarity with every other Jew,'' said Israeli Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Itzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Navon </PERSON>, the highest-ranking <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> official ever to visit <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. `` Only by strengthening the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, multiplying and increasing our numbers,'' can we prevail, <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> said, speaking in Hebrew and English. More than 4,500 foreign visitors have come to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> to take part in the observances that end April 20, including some 2,000 Israelis and hundreds of Jews from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. The observances climax Tuesday, the anniversary of the outbreak of the uprising, in which several hundred Jewish insurgents staged a desperate three-week struggle against the final Nazi extermination drive to liquidate the ghetto's last 75,000 inhabitants. One visitor to the camp's museum, <PERSON> Ayelet </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuper </PERSON>, 15, of <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, said it was emotionally wrenching to look at a room full of children's shoes taken from victims before they were murdered. `` And there was a small crutch, like for an 8-year old,' she said. `` That got to me a lot.'' More than 4 million people died at <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Birkenau </LOCATION>, about 70 percent of whom were Jews.
