<HEAD>NASA Chief Says Joint Mission Should be to Moon, Not Mars</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs for item slugged AM-Space Station on the AM-Advisory</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 If the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> team up for an interplanetary mission, a trip to the moon would be preferable to shooting for Mars, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> FLetcher </PERSON> said Thursday. A Mars mission would probably span four or five presidential administrations, requiring a degree of stable relations that has not been demonstrated between the two countries, <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has favored a joint mission to Mars, but such a proposal has not gone beyond the talking stage. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said a program of cooperative unmanned activities should take place before astronauts and cosmonauts climb into a space ship for the two-year round trip to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION>. `` Flying out to <LOCATION> Mars </LOCATION> together before building such a foundation could, for several reasons, be less practical,'' he said. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> spoke to the National Space Symposium in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION> on the same day that the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> formally advised <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that cutbacks in money will delay completion of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space station for a year until late 1996. The first of 16 shuttle flights needed to put men and materials into orbit is expected to be early in 1995, instead of 1994. That puts the completion target date four years behind the schedule set originally. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had planned to have the space station up and working in 1992 as a celebration of the 500th anniversary of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>' discovery of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. In a letter to the chairmen of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committees that oversee <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> FLetcher </PERSON> said that by revising the schedule, a robot laboratory should operating in 1995. The laboratory had been slated for the sixth shuttle supply mission; it now is on the fourth. `` The realities of the federal budget environment are clear,'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> told Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boland </PERSON>, D-Mass., and Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> had asked for $ 767 million for the space station in the current fiscal year but received $ 425 The agency wanted $ 1.8 billion in the year that begins Oct. 1, but President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s budget proposes $ 1 billion <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said that left <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> three options: cutting down on the station, changing the way the program is managed or stretching out the time to build the station. The third approach `` is the only sensible way,'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said. More than four years and $ 600 million already have gone into planning the station configuration. The scope of the station ca n't be cut further `` without jeopardizing the safety and usefulness of the station,'' <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said. The facility, which will be home to crews of six and eight for months at a time, originally was to cost $ 8 billion, but that figure will have quadrupled when all costs _ including those of stretch out and delays _ are taken into account. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> plan to attach their own modules to the station structure and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> will contribute the shuttle docking facilities. <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> called the space station a major investment in the nation's future by providing a research and technology laboratory, an <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> and celestial observatory, and `` a point of departure for the expansion of human presence and activity into the solar system.'' In <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON> said both the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the Soviets realize that many technical unknowns are involved in a manned Mars mission, such as the effects of prolonged weightlessness on humans. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has experience with moon walkers, while the Soviets have amassed data through lengthy stays on their space stations.
