<HEAD>Plane Crash Blamed on Crew, Air Traffic Control Error</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crash of an <ORGANIZATION> Aeroflot </ORGANIZATION> passenger jet in February in which 20 people died was blamed on errors by the crew and an air traffic controller, investigators said. A report on the investigation of the crash in the Siberian city of <LOCATION> Surgut </LOCATION>, 1,400 miles from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, was published Wednesday by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. The state <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flght </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said the pilot of the Tupolev-134 asked for permission to use a runway not normally used at the Surgut airport and tried to land the craft in poor visibility. The official report said the plane carried 45 passengers and a crew of six. Seventeen passengers and three crew members were killed, and all of the other 31 people aboard were injured. `` Since the commander did not stick to the flight parameters set by the air traffic controller, the plane found itself in a position, as to the landing strip, which made safe landing impossible,'' the report said. `` The plane therefore made a rough landing away from the landing strip, it was wrecked by overloads and burst into flames,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The report said co-pilot <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuneiko </PERSON> was flying the plane, while commander <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shavrovich </PERSON> was talking with the air traffic controller about switching runways. `` Flight director <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Maltsev </PERSON> met the crew's request, but in doing so, in violation of the rules, he failed to switch on ground radio facilities for a landing approach and organize observation of weather in the direction of the landing course,'' <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. The plane was on a 1,600-mile flight across the western <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> when it crashed at its final stop. Rescue operations were impaired by poorly trained personnel and insufficient technical facilities at <ORGANIZATION> Surgut </ORGANIZATION>, the report said. `` By the results of the investigation, the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> is taking necessary steps to rule out a recurrence of such aircraft accidents,'' the report said, but did not give details.
