<BYLINE>By PHYLL MESSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Evangelist <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said Thursday he welcomed tough measures taken against fallen TV minister <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> and said that <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> is not ready for a <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> or <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in the White House. `` I have no problem with Reverend <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> running, as long as he loses,'' <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said. `` I do n't think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people want a reverend _ it has nothing to do with Democrat, Republican, black, white, liberal, conservative. I do n't think the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people are ready for a reverend to be in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, and I think it's a pretty good idea one never is.'' <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>'s comments came as part of a panel discussion on televangelists on the second day of a three-day convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION>. An estimated 685 editors attending the convention also heard from <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and his fellow Democratic presidential hopeful, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, as well as from <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and Costa Rican President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON>, winner of the Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts to end fighting in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said he was pleased that television representatives in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Religious </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> had agreed to recommend that all Christian stations drop <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON>'s religious program if he returns to preaching before his one-year suspension expires. `` That does n't mean all the stations have to comply with that requirement,'' <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said. `` But my guess is that most of them will.'' <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>, along with panelists <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadden </PERSON>, sociology professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION>, and <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Okla. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> reporter <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Hargrove </PERSON>, told the editors that the sex scandals that brought down <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tammy </PERSON> <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakker </PERSON> marked the end of an era for televangelists. `` We're witnessing a serious readjustment of the work of religious politics,'' <PERSON> Hadden </PERSON> said. `` The questions about financial accountability already had been raised. The sex scandals were the final icing on the cake,'' <PERSON> Hargrove </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON> said he believes `` it was inevitable that these catastrophies occurred'' and said it was not the press that brought down the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Swaggart </PERSON>. `` They brought themselves down.'' `` Frankly,'' he said, `` an inevitable housecleaning was overdue. Yes, it's hurt everybody ... but the major hurt is the terrible damage done to the value systems and the principle systems of young people in this country.'' <PERSON> Falwell </PERSON>, who took over the debt-ridden <ORGANIZATION> PTL </ORGANIZATION> ministry after the <ORGANIZATION> Bakkers </ORGANIZATION>' departure and resigned from it late last year, said one good thing had come out of the Bakker-Swaggart sex scandals: the end of televangelists' celebrity status. `` There will never again, and I thank God it's true, be a person that people look to as God. Celebrity status is history.'' Earlier in the day, the editors heard a plea from <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to cover all the details of a comprehensive trade bill now before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. He called the measure one of the most important now on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` You hold the keys to developing thoughtful commentary on events,'' <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said.
