<HEAD>House Subcommittee Chairman Angered Over Aid Request for NATO
Allies</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: RECASTS lead to reflect that Obey angered over administration
response to documents request, sted administration position;
INSERTS 1 graf with Obey quotes after 3rd graf pvs, bgng: He then.
Picks up 4th graf pvs, At the</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> appropriations panel on Thursday called for suspension of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid to its three poorest <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies, and stormed out of a hearing to protest the administration's failure to produce details of previous assistance to the countries. Rep. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Obey </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the subcommittee on foreign operations, told <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> witnesses he was `` fed up with getting this mush from you You must really think we're saps up here.'' He then suspended the hearing after only 50 minutes and strode out of the room. `` There was no sense in my sitting listening for the information only to be told they they did n't have it,'' Obey told the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> later. `` That was the same thing they said before.'' At the root of the dispute are demands by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members spend more money on the defense of the alliance, in what is known as `` burden sharing.'' Obey's outburst was prompted by the administration's failure to provide the committee with detailed lists of the surplus military equipment being transferred to <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> this year. Obey said he had asked for the lists several months ago to help the committee decide how to allocate funds for the administration's 1989 spending request of $ 1.4 billion for the three countries, where the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> maintains military bases and some 15,000 personnel The three are the poorest members of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, and the administration contends the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must fund them in order to ensure continued basing rights. Obey, a vocal foe of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> spending on <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> allies, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not `` be engaged in unilateral welfare efforts'' for these countries. Rather, he said, the aid should be a joint <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> effort. `` My view is that there should be zero funding this year for base rights countries,'' he said. Obey claimed that taxpayers in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, are paying more for the defense of <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> than those in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. `` My taxpayers are fed up with this, and so am I.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> taxpayer spends more than $ 1,000 a year on the defense of the free world, while British taxpayers spend per capita $ 488, the French $ 511, the West Germans $ 433 and the Japanese $ 163, Obey said. `` We're being taken for a ride.'' Obey railed against such <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members as <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> `` who constantly lecture us on our deficit and on managing our economy'' but fail to share the burden of maintaining the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. Deputy Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, defending the administration's spending request _ which is 41 percent higher than the base rights funding of 1981 _ said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests clearly lie in a continued <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> presence in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` Our border begins there,'' he said. Deputy Assistant Secretary of Defense <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodworth </PERSON> said in his testimony that while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> defense spending grew much more than that of other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members in the years between 1981 and 1986, `` that pattern is now reversed.'' He said several <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> countries, among them <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, increased their defense spending by about 3 percent in 1987, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> increase was only 0.1 percent and in 1988 it will decline more than 3 percent.
