<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Philippine President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> visited the home of her Chinese ancestors on Thursday, while her nation remained her nation was on full military alert amid concerns of a coup attempt during her absence. Presidential spokesman <PERSON> Teodoro </PERSON> <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> played down the threat of a coup attempt at home, despite the escape from prison of former Lt. Col. <PERSON> Gregorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON>, who tried to overthrow the president in August. `` Mr. <PERSON> Honasan </PERSON> has lost all capability of mounting any serious threat on the government,'' <PERSON> Benigno </PERSON> said. `` If there was any question about that, then the president would have wavered in her decision to come to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but not for one minute did she waver in her plans.'' The president, accompanied by seven cabinet ministers, was greeted by Vice Foreign Minister <PERSON> Liu </PERSON> <PERSON> Shuqing </PERSON> and taken to the <LOCATION> Diaoyutai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> House </LOCATION>, where she will stay during her three-day visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. On Friday she will be officially welcomed by President <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shangkun </PERSON> outside the Great Hall of the People and will hold talks with Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON>. She is also to sign a trade protocol and a science and technology agreement. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> is also to meet senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> on Saturday before leaving for an overnight stay in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Fujian </LOCATION> province, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> visited her ancestral village of <LOCATION> Hongjian </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s great-grandfather, <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuhuan </PERSON>, lived there until leaving for the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> 120 years ago. Village residents waved yellow banners and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> flags and set off firecrackers while a school band played. Crowds lined the roads passing through fertile, terraced farmland. At the Xu family ancestral temple, which had been restored and painted for the visit, Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> burned incense and bowed three times before memorial tablets. `` I came to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for reasons of state and for reasons personal to me, for I am both head of state of my country and, in a way, a daughter of this village,'' she told 49 relatives she was meeting for the first time. `` The end of traveling, we are told, is to return. I have returned for my family, and for other Filipinos of Chinese descent, to retrace their steps and attain some understanding of the industry and creativity that led them forth to new beginnings in other lands,'' she said. She ended the speech by saying in Chinese, `` I and my daughters and my colleagues again thank you for your welcome which we will never forget.' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> visited a kindergarten where she gave yellow `` <PERSON> Cory </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'' T-shirts to the children and looked at family photos in the home of an uncle, <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Yuanxiang </PERSON>. Her visit to <PERSON> Hongjian </PERSON> lasted a little more than an hour. Fujian Gov. <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhaoguo </PERSON> hosted Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> at a lavish banquet and thanked the president for her gift to <PERSON> Hongjian </PERSON> of a playground, to be built with $ 15,000 in donations by <LOCATION> Philippine </LOCATION> businessmen. The Philippine military was put on full alert nationwide, and opposition leaders suggested she should scrub the trip to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> because of political unrest at home. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s last trip abroad was in November 1986 to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. She said that canceling the trip would be `` the greatest folly'' because she wanted to show <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` that we have at least achieved the internal political stability and peace to play a responsible and important role that is expected of us in <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> affairs.''
