<FIRST>u i AM-Hijack-Passenger     04-14 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hijack-Passenger,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Citizen Says Hijackers Overlooked License</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Egyptian-American </ORGANIZATION> released after eight days as a hostage said the Islamic radicals who seized a <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> jumbo jet overlooked his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> driver's license. `` One of them searched my wallet, and there was my driver's license,'' <PERSON> Ramadan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said during an interview at the home of a relative in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> `` I was so lucky. He did n't realize what it was.'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> was one of 12 passengers freed Tuesday night shortly before the hijackers of the <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747 flew from <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> with more than 30 passengers and crew still aboard. Fearful the hijackers would harm him if they knew of his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizenship, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said he hid his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> passport in his briefcase and used his Egyptian documents. When the jet stopped in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> immediately after the hijacking, `` they collected al our briefcases and put them in a closet and closed it,'' he said. For the rest of his captivity, he said he worried that one might search his case and discover the document, `` but they had no time to do it.'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, who displayed bruises on his wrists, said the hijackers used plastic handcuffs on the passengers after two days in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and left them on constantly after that. `` Clamping your hands 24 hours _ You have to eat, your hand is tied; go the the bathroom, your hand is tied,'' he said. The eight-day ordeal left him nervous, emotionally stunned and wary of flying, <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said. `` It became to me like a phobia,'' he said. `` It could happen again.'' He withheld his American address because `` these guys, they have long hands.'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON>, a consulting engineer who travels widely, said security at <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION> airport was loose, `` like a farmer's market.'' He said he saw passengers who set off alarms on metal detectors pass unsearched as he was boarding the flight for <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>. He agreed with other passengers' reports that the hijackers appeared to take on weapons and two new colleagues during four days at <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION> airport in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, their first stop. But he said he did not actually see any weapons or new men come aboard. He said screens were drawn across the first-class cabin where the hijackers stayed and all the aircraft's window shades were pulled down. `` After we left <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION>, I saw three machine guns,'' which he said were small weapons resembling the Israeli-made Uzi. He said he also saw 10 hand grenades, thick ropes, explosives and plastic hand grenades only after the plane had been in <LOCATION> Mashhad </LOCATION>. He said two new hijackers appeared to join the six younger ones when the plane was in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. He described the newcomers as older men, 30 to 40, who were giving orders to the others. One by one, he said, they called passengers to the front compartments to question them about their jobs, nationalities, families and religion. He said the people called forward most often were the two Kuwaitis who were shot to death in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, although passengers did not know of the killings until their release. <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said the hijackers also asked the branch of Islam he belonged to: Sunni or Shiite. All of the Kuwaiti men released so far have been Shiites, members of the branch that predominates in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and southern <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, but is a minority in most of the Islamic world. `` I was reading the Koran all the time. They noticed I'm a religious person,'' he said, speculating that might have helped in his release. He said he tried to pray and that others tried to join in. But he said the attempt to practice standard Islamic prayers, which require standing, then kneeling toward <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, made the hijackers nervous. `` They said, ` Hey guys, if you want to pray, pray in your seats.'''
