n. The Son of <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> law gets its title from the nickname of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> serial murderer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkowitz </PERSON>, whose case inspired a similar law in that state. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> did not intend to block felons from profiting ... only to have defense lawyers pocket that money,'' <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> said. The law calls for 25 percent of the proceeds from any such works to go to dependents of the felon, if he has any, and 25 percent to the victims of the crime or their dependents. The state can recover prosecution, incarceration and other costs from the remaining 50 percent. State investigators have found <PERSON> Varon </PERSON> received $ 50,000 for the <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> film, which was broadcast last year starring <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> as <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, and that <PERSON> Varon </PERSON> now is attempting to sell a book, <PERSON> Butterworth </PERSON> contends. He said the investigation showed <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON> received only $ 5,000 of that amount and donated it to a non-profit institution for Alzheimer's research.
