` We are going to ask for restitution. At one point or another everybody in this division has worked on this case this past week.'' <PERSON> Witmer </PERSON> has been at odds with <LOCATION> Clearwater </LOCATION> officials since 1985, when an occupational license for his UFS Stop-Smoking Clinic first became an issue, according to a police affidavit. He conducts the clinics at various hotels. <PERSON> Witmer </PERSON> obtained the license in previous years. But he refused to renew it this year, claiming he was exempt because of his religious status. The city would not recognize a religious exemption. On April 4, <PERSON> Witmer </PERSON> called police and said three members of what he described as his own `` religious cult'' planned to kill or seriously injure city officials because they believed that the city was harassing <PERSON> Witmer </PERSON>. He said he unwittingly helped the plot by releasing $ 6,000 to the conspirators. <PERSON> Witmer </PERSON> promised to try to stop his followers from harming city officials, but he refused to identify them until he was held in contempt of court April 6. On the way to jail, <PERSON> Witmer </PERSON> named the `` conspirators.'' But the names he gave were of two <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> police officers who had contact with <PERSON> Witmer </PERSON> during one of his prior arrests. In 1976, he told the editors of a <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> campus newspaper that he would `` check into hiring a professional to rearrange your faces'' because he thought the newspaper libeled him, according to an arrest warrant. The warrant also said during 1976 he threatened the wife of a professor who told him the university would not renew his stop-smoking clinic contract. In 1979, his bid to conduct similar clinics at <ORGANIZATION> FSU </ORGANIZATION> was a