<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Infants born with only a fraction of a normal brain should not be immediately used as a source of donor organs even though they are doomed, say two medical ethicists who argue that doctors must wait for true `` brain death'' to occur. Such infants, called anencephalics, have a brain stem, which enables them to breathe. But they have no cerebral cortex, the part of the brain that allows thought and voluntary movement. Most die within 24 hours and all within weeks of birth, and they are increasingly viewed by some within the medical community as a potential pool of donor organs for children needing transplants. At issue is both the appropriateness of using anencephalics as donors _ and how soon. `` Organ donation is very laudable and people say these kids will inevitably die,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Shlomo </PERSON> <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON>, co-author with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Arras </PERSON> of a commentary in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` But then what makes that different from a number of newborns with congential fatal diseases? Or other kids and adults in vegetative states?'' <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> said. `` And what if there are not enough anencephalics and the transplant needs are greater two years from now? Who do we look at next? `` These are steps we can take only after very, very careful review,'' said <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON>, a pediatric neurologist at <ORGANIZATION> Montefiore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center-Albert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Einstein </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>, in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. There are between 2,000 and 3,000 anencephalic infants among the 3 million children born in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> each year, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> estimates. The problem can be detected before birth with ultrasound and abortion is considered appropriate by some doctors as late as the final three months of pregnancy, the commentary said. `` Should we be encouraging pregnant women, in essence, to carry these children to term to provide spare parts?'' <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> said. Questions about their use as organ donors were raised after newspaper reports last October that organs had been taken from anencephalic infants and transplanted into other children in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` In the West German case, they took a baby from delivery, put a tube -LRB- of oxygen -RRB- in its mouth, took it to the operating room, harvested the organs and buried it,'' said <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON>. `` And in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, although it did not pass, there was a bill in the legislature in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to have these children declared ` brain-dead' at birth,'' he added. <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON> said legal definitions of brain death used in making medical determinations require an end of all brain functions, including those of the brain stem. The debate took a new turn in December, when the <LOCATION> Loma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Linda </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> developed guidelines under which anencephalic babies are to be sustained on respirators and used for transplants only if brain death occurs within a week. Otherwise, they are removed from the respirators and allowed to die naturally. Six anencephalic infants have been kept alive by respirator for a week under those guidelines, though none ultimately became an organ donor, said <PERSON> Loma </PERSON> <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Anita </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON>. `` We wrote our article before the protocol -LRB- guideline -RRB- was developed,'' said <PERSON> Shinnar </PERSON>, `` and this certainly lessens the magnitude of the ethical debate. `` We are no longer talking about actively taking a life, though this protocol is not without its problems as well. What about extending the tragedy for the parents of an anencephalic child?'' he said. `` The issue is not that the practice is common, because it's not,'' he said `` But the argument over whether this is a good, sound idea or something that should be opposed _ as we feel _ has to take place before it becomes so.''
</TEXT>
