<HEAD>West Germany Said Doing All It Can To Aid U.S. Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Finance Ministers Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the West German central bank said Thursday that his country has done all it can to stimulate its own economy as part of the effort to lower the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. `` We have the lowest interest rates in the world ... and it would be irresponsible to pursue more expansionary monetary policies,'' <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> luncheon. His remarks came amid turmoil on world financial markets. The dollar fell and stocks tumbled in reaction to news that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit for February widened by more than 11 percent to $ 13.8 billion. A heated dispute over interest rates last year between <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and the West Germans has been cited as one of the contributing factors to Oct. 19 stock market plunge. Since that time, world financial leaders have gone out of their way to stress harmony and coordinated efforts. With <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON> looking on, <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> sidestepped questions at the luncheon about whether the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> should tighten the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> money supply, which would drive up interest rates and make the dollar more attractive. However, he said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, by keeping its interest rates low, `` could n't have done more.'' <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION>'s dollar reserves have increased by $ 15 billion in the past year to $ 50 billion and indicated it was among the central banks intervening Thursday to buy dollars on world exchange markets. `` Today was a day where, I think, we have demonstrated to the markets our readiness, and our willingness ... in the future,'' he said. <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON> cautioned against overreacting to Thursday's trade deficit figures. `` One should not be confused by a monthly trade figure. That's a very temporary statistic. The true conditions for more stable exchange rates are much better than some years ago,'' he said. He also said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> should not expect to be in equilibrium with every trading partner all the time. He said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, as an aging nation with a stable population, needs to be a net exporter. <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which was $ 2.2 billion in the first two months of this year, is far smaller than <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s, at $ 8.5 billion, and less than <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>'s, at $ 2.7 billion, he said.
