<SECOND>AM-Farmland Values,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmland Prices Rise for First Time Since 1982</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Farmland prices are up for the first time in six years but still are far from returning to the peak levels of 1982, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. As of Feb. 1, the average value of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmland, including buildings, was $ 564 per acre, up 3 percent from a 19-year low of $ 548 per acre recorded last year, the department said in its annual report. But the Feb. 1 reading was still down 32 percent from the record high of $ 823 per acre in 1982. In real terms, allowing for an inflation of nearly 4 percent last year, farmland nationally dropped again to an average of $ 288 per acre, down 1 percent from $ 290 a year earlier. That would be the lowest since the early 1960s. Farmland values vary greatly across the country, and not all regions or states share in the increase. More than a dozen states showed a further decline or no gain from a year ago. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Hexem </PERSON>, a farmland analyst in the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said there are too many variables _ interest rates and farm income estimates, for example _ to make a prediction of a future trend. `` It do n't think it necessarily follows that they're going to be higher next year,'' <PERSON> Hexem </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I think there are just too many uncertainties.'' <PERSON> Hexem </PERSON> added: `` We just ca n't put ourselves into the minds of those who are looking at the markets. One's expectation of what's going to happen in terms of returns to the land are kind of peculiar to that individual And if that individual is more optimistic than others, then he or she is probably more inclined to get into the market and bid prices up.'' The report, which <PERSON> Hexem </PERSON> supervised, noted that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm income was a record high in 1987, but `` was enhanced by government payments equivalent to nearly 30 percent of net cash income.'' Higher farm income and lower debt improved the equity position of farmers in 1987, and interest rates averaged lower than in 1986. However, those rates edged up slightly late last year, the report said. Regionally, the <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> showed a 9 percent increase in farmland prices as of Feb. 1, continuing an upward trend that began in the mid-1940s, the report said. The Corn Belt also rose 9 percent, and the <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plains </ORGANIZATION> averaged 7 percent higher, the first advances since the early 1980s. `` In both regions, values rose in all states, particularly <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION> -LRB- up 19 percent -RRB-,'' the report said. `` <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>'s 14 percent gain led the Lake States' 7 percent growth, while values were up 6 percent in the Southeast and 2 percent in <LOCATION> Appalachia </LOCATION>.'' A 4 percent drop in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> farmland values was offset by higher prices in other states, which left the <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> states essentially unchanged for the year. `` The upturns in farmland values did not extend to the Western regions, where most state values continued downward into 1988,'' the report said. `` Regional values were down 3 percent in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plains </ORGANIZATION>, 2 percent in the Mountain states and 2 percent in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> region. But the rates of decline were lower than in the past two years.''
