<FIRST>r a AM-TaxFraud     04-14 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Fraud,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indictment Hits Tax-Shelter Schemes Day Before Tax Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TED DUNCOMBE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly 6,000 taxpayers cut their payments by $ 88 million by claiming huge writeoffs for energy-saving devices that may not have even worked, authorities said Thursday as they announced the indictment of 12 people. The 86-count indictment handed up Thursday represents one of the largest tax shelter frauds ever prosecuted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> S.G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. The indictment charges that taxpayers in 47 states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> paid at least $ 44 million to two corporations for a stake in energy-saving devices that purportedly would give the investors tax credits. The scheme cost the government $ 88 million for the 1982 and 1983 tax years, according to the indictment, but authorities said they expected to recover much of the money from the taxpayers. `` This prosecution involves a very sophisticated attempt to lure taxpayers into making investments that would, according to their promoters, result in many times the investment in tax savings,'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said. All 12 defendants stand charged with conspiracy to defraud the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, aiding the filing of false tax returns and mail fraud. Three defendants _ <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuffrida </PERSON>, 51, of <LOCATION> Belle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Terre </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Salvatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Giuffrida </PERSON>, 47, of <LOCATION> Dix </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Medina </PERSON>, 41, of <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jeffeson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION> _ are also charged with racketeering through mail fraud and interstate transportation of money and securities taken by fraud. The taxpayers did not necessarily know they were involved in an illegal scheme, because the marketing was thoroughly professional with videotapes, glossy brochures and seminar presentations, said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> <PERSON> Gabbrielli </PERSON>, who will prosecute the case. According to the indictment, two leasing companies, both based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> state </LOCATION>, offered taxpayers the chance to lease an energy device for an initial $ 5,000 to $ 25,000, depending on the model. The companies told the taxpayers they could claim investment and energy tax credits for the purported fair market value of the device, ranging from $ 65,000 to $ 280,000. The heart of the fraud case stems from the purported fair market value, which authorities said was actually $ 304 to $ 1,855. `` The figures were completedly inflated,'' <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> said. `` Of course, there were questions about whether there were really these energy savings.'' The devices, which prosecutors did not describe in detail, were to be installed at a commercial site, which would then share any energy savings with the taxpayer. The taxpayer in turn would pay a portion of the electricity savings back to the leasing companies and an array of bogus manufacturers. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Matthews </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> district director of the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the indictment was the culmination of a three-year investigation. `` We think it is time and money well spent,'' he said. The two leasing companies marketing the devices were <ORGANIZATION> OEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Garden </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leasing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Melville </LOCATION>, N.Y. If convicted, the <ORGANIZATION> Giuffridas </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Medina </PERSON> face up to 345 years each in prison and fines ranging from $ 6.6 million to $ 10 million, plus forfeiture of assets. The other nine, if convicted, face prison sentences of up to 275 years and fines of up to $ 6.5 million. Also charged in the indictment were <PERSON> Zayle </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernstein </PERSON>, 48, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eckard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 46, <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cleary </PERSON>, 43, <LOCATION> Levittown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> DeRaffele </PERSON>, 46, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rochelle </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Tobin </PERSON>, 48, <LOCATION> Cherry </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Irwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, 55, <LOCATION> Crystal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Enden </PERSON>, 47, <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marci </PERSON>, 46, <ORGANIZATION> Coram </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Oster </PERSON>, 30, Miller Place, N.Y.
