<HEAD>LaserPhoto CN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An engine on a <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> jetliner exploded into jagged pieces Thursday, slicing through both sides of the plane and forcing the pilot to make an emergency landing as some passengers screamed and fainted. Two flight attendants suffered bumps and bruises when the plane carrying 56 passengers plunged after the explosion, <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON> said. Turbine blades ripped through the right rear bathroom and a work area for attendants as the plane cruised at 31,000 feet. `` If somebody had been in the bathroom or the stewardesses' quarters, they would have been killed,'' said passenger <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> `` My first thought was, ` This is it.''' `` It blew a big hole in the plane,'' said passenger <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, `` I'm 240 pounds, and it was big enough that I could crawl through it.'' `` All the kids were screaming,'' <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON> said. Piedmont Flight 486 was flying from <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, when its right jet turbine disintegrated about 9:45 a.m., <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> officials said. The plane, a <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-28, has two engines, one mounted on each side of the cabin. The plane, 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, immediately lost air pressure in the cabin; several passengers later complained of headaches, earaches and elevated blood pressure. `` It began with a wearing noise and loud vibrations about five or 10 times straight, and then there was an explosion in the back of us,'' said passenger <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C </LOCATION>. Turbine blades and engine parts ripped through the fuselage, punching holes in both sides of the plane. A hole on the right side, adjacent to the engine that disintegrated, was 2 feet wide by 6 feet tall. On the opposite side, the hole was 2 feet by 1 foot. The pilot noticed a fire indicator signal for his No. 2 engine, manufactured by <PERSON> Rolls </PERSON> <PERSON> Royce </PERSON>, and decided to land at <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, where he `` landed without incident'' at <LOCATION> Yeager </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, about 10 a.m., <PERSON> McGuire </PERSON> said. Assistant airport manager <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Huffman </PERSON> said the F-28 was 40 miles south of <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> and traveling north when the explosion occurred. The plane made a deep descent after the explosion `` but they got it under control. They all did a good job,'' <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON> said. A <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> investigator was dispatched to <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> to investigate, airport officials said. <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> owns 25 of the German-built F-28 4000s, said another <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> spokesman, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Kress </PERSON>. Piedmont uses the jets, slightly smaller than <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 737s or McDonnell-Douglass DC9s, because many airports in its mountainous region have short runways. <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>'s airport, named for test pilot Gen. <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeager </PERSON>, is located atop a mountain 2 miles north of the downtown area. Immediately after the explosion, oxygen masks dropped from the ceiling and flight attendants and adult passengers went through the aisles and assisted children, passengers said. But some masks did n't work and passengers had to be moved to other seats. <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, who was sitting three rows from the rear of the plane, said a woman in the seat behind him who was traveling with two children passed out. `` She fainted. I turned around and she was blue. The baby was blue. And her 3-year-old was blue,'' <PERSON> Gonzales </PERSON> said. `` I grabbed her and put a mask on her, gave the baby to a woman who was sitting next to her and I took the 3-year-old up with me.'' About 90 minutes after the emergency landing, most passengers were placed on Flight 249, a Charleston-to-Chicago nonstop flight that was diverted to <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>. However, a few passengers flocked to rental car companies; they planned to continue their trip by car. Before Flight 249 took off for <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, paramedics checked the blood pressure of several passengers. `` It's a little high,'' <PERSON> Hinton </PERSON> said of his own blood pressure. `` But if I do n't get on that plane today, I'll have trouble flying again.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> has on file only two injury-related accidents involving <ORGANIZATION> Fokker </ORGANIZATION> F-28s, said spokesman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopatkiewicz </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>. One jet was involved in a minor taxiway collision in 1985, and in 1986, an unassisted handicapped passenger fell off the boarding stairs when a guardrail gave way, he said During the past 4 -LCB- years, only seven <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> flights resulted in injuries to passengers, the records show. The worst was on Oct. 25, 1986, when a jet overshot a <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION> runway, causing three serious injuries and 31 minor ones. On Aug. 10, 1968, a <LOCATION> Piedmont </LOCATION> plane crashed on approach to the <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION> airport, killing 35 people.
