<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet media on Thursday called the <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> accord in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> `` the news we've been waiting so long for,'' but there was only sketchy mention of the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION>'s commitment to bring its soldiers home. Radio <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> used only one sentence to sum up the consequences of the pact for the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops deployed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` It was agreed that the withdrawal of Soviet troops is to start on May 15, and to be completed within nine months,'' it said. Other media reports, including state-run television's top evening news broadcast, made no reference to the pullout at all. Instead, most reports emphasized that the goal of the pact is the peaceful settlement of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s 10-year-old civil war, and reiterated Soviet backing for the embattled Marxist government of President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>. Most Soviets, however, would be aware of the implications of the accords. Communist Party chief <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, who has called the Afghan involvement his nation's `` bleeding wound,'' said last week that the pullout would begin in mid-May if the U.N.-brokered <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> negotiations were successful. Soviet leader <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON> sent troops into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on Dec. 27, 1979, to preside over the replacement of one Marxist leader by another. They stayed on to help combat a nationwide insurgency in a military operation that has cost thousands of Soviet lives and billions of rubles, sparked domestic dissent, and poisoned the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION>'s relations with other Moslem and Third World nations. Human rights activist <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, who was sent into internal exile for almost seven years after criticizing the intervention, called the agreement signed in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> `` an enormous event.'' `` It was a horrible war, a horrible mistake by the Soviet leadership that had awful consequences for the Afghan people,'' said <PERSON> Sakharov </PERSON>, the 1975 Nobel Peace laureate, who was reached by telephone at his <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> apartment. `` I am waiting with great impatience for May 15 to see the troop withdrawal begin,'' he added. From the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> withdrawal of the SALT II arms control treaty and the boycott of the 1980 <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Olympics by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 61 other nations to the canceling of grain and other trade agreements involving foreign suppliers, the Soviets paid the price for sending tanks and troops across the Afghan border. A <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> newspaper editor recently told a Western reporter of receiving a letter from a man whose only son was killed in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` Now the others are coming home,'' the writer of the letter said. `` But what did my boy die for?'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has estimated Soviet casualties since 1979 at 33,000-38 ,000, more than one-third of whom were killed Those figures do not include `` heavy losses'' to disease, the department said in a report issued in December. The agreement signed by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> commits the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> to ending its military intervention. State-run media's initial reporting on the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreements seemed designed to assure Soviets that their government's stated goal of achieving peace in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s civil war had been met, at least in part. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>, in a statement to reporters after the ceremony, spoke not of the withdrawal of Soviet troops but of the end to all outside interference in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> mandated by the agreements. `` The entire spectrum of possible activities and actions to meddle in the affairs of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> has finally been blocked,'' he said, in remarks reported by the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency and shown on Soviet TV. `` Outside interference'' has been the term used by Soviets to describe the aid by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s anti-Marxist <ORGANIZATION> Mujahedeen </ORGANIZATION> insurgents. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> said he wanted to do `` justice'' to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> role in bringing about an Afghan settlement, but depicted the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> as the major peacemaker. The Afghan pact, he said, `` has been predetermined by my country's policy of solving acute international problems exceptionally by political means, which has been proclaimed by <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>.'' `` Vremya,'' the evening news program, made no mention at all Thursday night of the troop withdrawal. The newcast, with an estimated audience of 150 million, began with reports on the regular Thursday meeting of the ruling Politburo, the construction of an atomic icebreaker, and private farming plots in a region of the Russian federation. About 20 minutes into the broadcast, `` Vremya'' showed an eight-minute report on what a correspondent in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> called a `` historic event of exceptional international importance.'' Another newscaster on state-run TV also waxed eloquent in reporting the agreements, which were also signed by top diplomats from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. `` Today in the World,'' an evening program, led off with a highly unusual editorial comment from anchorman <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Kudrin </PERSON>, who told viewers, `` We begin today with news that we've been waiting so long for.'' On Feb. 8, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said the future political system of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> was `` none of our business,'' and stressed that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> had dropped a previous condition that a coalition government be formed before the beginning of a military withdrawal. <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> on Thursday reiterated <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> backing for <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, saying what is crucial in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> is `` every kind of support for the success of the national reconcilation policy'' proclaimed last year by the Afghan leader.
