<HEAD>Soviet Health Officials Explain 1979 Anthrax Outbreak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM PAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top Soviet health officials said Thursday that an anthrax outbreak that killed 64 people in <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION> eight years ago was caused by contaminated meat, not an accident at a germ-warfare laboratory. The officials, including Dr. <PERSON> Petr </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Burgasov </PERSON>, the Soviet's deputy minister of health at the time, made the comments during a conference on the disease at the <ORGANIZATION> Johns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hopkins </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> `` There is no reason for any suspicion,'' said <PERSON> Burgasov </PERSON>, who along with two companions had treated victims in <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>. `` If there had been an explosion, not 96 people would have been affected, but literally hundreds of thousands of people.'' The officials offered a detailed explanation of the April 1979 accident, discounting sketchy reports at the time by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials that it was caused by exposure to a lethal biological agent. The Soviet explanation, presented first in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> earlier this week, has been hailed by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> academicians as the most detailed, public account of the outbreak. The three Soviet doctors said they are spending a week in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> attempting to convince Western physicians, scholars and politicians of their explanation. <PERSON> Burgasov </PERSON> acknowledged that the Soviets' failure to disclose the incident led to suspicion in the West. `` The fact that there was no data given at the time always leads to suspicion,'' he said. The disease, which is caused by a bacteria, killed 64 of the 96 people it afflicted, <PERSON> Burgasov </PERSON> said, speaking through an interpreter at a lecture attended by about 100 people. Anthrax, which also kills cattle, is transmitted most commonly by contact with infected animals, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Textbook </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. Burgasov and Dr. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Sergiyev </PERSON> said the disease was traced back to a bone-meal animal feed that had been improperly processed at a Soviet manufacturing plant. The meal was fed to animals who subsequently died. The meat was sold privately and illegally to people in <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>, the doctors said. `` In 1979 there was very little meat -LRB- in the region -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Burgasov </PERSON> said. `` Meat was a luxury, it was used only on special occasions.'' He said children did not become sick because they were fed daily at child care centers with food that came from a central distribution center. Vegetarians and people who did not eat the underground meat did not get sick, <PERSON> Burgasov </PERSON> said. `` This is why we became suspicious of the meat.'' `` All of the tragedy of this illness passed right before my eyes,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Nikiforov </PERSON>, an expert in infectious diseases who treated many of the victims. Using graphic slides, <PERSON> Nikiforov </PERSON> showed symptoms of the two types of anthrax _ contaneous and gastrointestinal _ that afflicted victims in <LOCATION> Sverdlovsk </LOCATION>. Those who had contaneous anthrax, characterized by lesions on the skin, eventually recovered. Victims of gastrointestinal anthrax, in which the disease infects the stomach and intestines, died within a two days of toxic shock, <PERSON> Nikiforov </PERSON> said. Dr. <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Langmuir </PERSON>, a former chief epidemiologist at the national <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, said he finds the Soviet account credible. <PERSON> Langmuir </PERSON>, who moderated the discussion at <PERSON> Johns </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, said he expects to learn more during the remainder of the Soviets' stay. Anthrax expert Dr. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Brachman </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Emory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Univeristy </ORGANIZATION> called the Soviets' presentation in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> a `` landmark report'' in an interview Tuesday with the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Brachman </PERSON> said the Soviet doctors provided `` a pretty good indication that this incident was an outbreak of gastrointestinal anthrax'' caused by contaminated meat.
