<DATELINE>NAPLES, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A car bomb blew up in front of a club for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military personnel in <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION> on Thursday, killing five people and wounding at least 17, Italian officials said. There was no immediate claim of responsibility for the blast that happened shortly after 8 p.m. -LRB- 2 p.m. EDT -RRB- at the USO club. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> initially reported one sailor was killed and four injured, but <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Haney </PERSON> later said authorities in <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION> could not confirm any <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military deaths. He said three sailors were hurt. Italian media quoted officials as saying three men and two women died in the blast. Witnesses said one of the bodies at the entrance of the club was draped in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> flag. Italian hospital officials said at least four Americans were among the injured. Italian media said the bomb exploded during a reception at the club for the commander of the USS Paul, a torpedo boat destroyer docked in <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate official could not confirm the report. Passers-by screamed and ran when the explosion occurred outside the club, which is in one of <LOCATION> Naples </LOCATION>' busiest areas. `` It was a huge boom and we were all knocked to the ground. When we got up, all we could see was flames everywhere,'' an unidentified Italian woman told the state-run <ORGANIZATION> RAI </ORGANIZATION> television network from her hospital bed. `` We can confirm there are no fatalities from the three ships in port,'' said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Baumann </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, adding that there was a possibility that `` there could be a sailor dead from the local command,'' although he knew of no such death. The ships were the USS Paul, based in <LOCATION> Mayport </LOCATIO