<HEAD>Sandinistas, Contras Iron Out Differences On Renewing Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Leaders of the U.S.-supported Contra rebels and the leftist Sandinista government said Thursday they had reached a compromise that would allow cease-fire talks to go ahead. The agreement to start high-level negotiations in the Nicaraguan capital Friday came during the first official visit of Contra representatives to the capital since the war started more than six years ago. The two sides also resumed stalled talks on technical details of a temporary cease-fire, such as how to provide the rebels with humanitarian aid and security. Maj. Gen. <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacaso </PERSON>, chief of staff of the Sandinista army and head of the government's delegation to the technical talks, said before the meeting he was confident the two sides would `` finish discussing the plan'' for implementing the temporary cease-fire. Contra political representatives at the meeting included <PERSON> Aristides </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON> <PERSON> Matamoros </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alejandro </PERSON> <PERSON> Montiel </PERSON> <PERSON> Arguello </PERSON>. The rebels' military delegation included <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> <PERSON> Centeno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivas </PERSON>. In a compromise, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> backed off demands that the technical talks be held in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. In exchange, the Contras retreated from their earlier insistence that Friday's high-level negotiations be conditioned on the successful outcome of the Sapoa talks. `` The Contras agreed that if the talks are not finished today -LRB- Thursday -RRB-, they'll conclude in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>,'' government Information Minister <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Espinoza </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. Two Contra delegates, <PERSON> Ferrey </PERSON> and <PE