<HEAD>UN Chief Proposes New Iran-Iraq Peace Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The secretary-general considers the positions of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> too far apart for a cease-fire to work and has proposed a new peace plan under which he would control the timing of a truce and other factors. <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> expressed his views in a written report submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday after meeting with envoys of both nations. A copy of the confidential 15-page report was made available to <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday by sources close to the proceedings. The secretary-general has held four rounds of meetings in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with the combatants, at the council's request, in an effort to get their clear support for a resolution adopted last July. It demands an immediate cease-fire in the 7 -LCB- - year-old war and withdrawal of troops <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> concluded the talks this week and said in his report: `` I considered the positions of the two governments ... to be insufficient for purposes of implementing Resolution 598,'' then asked them to reply to a new proposal. He said he was awaiting their responses. His latest plan, a modification of others, gives the secretary-general authority to control the timing and intervals for implementing the resolution. It says the secretary-general would set a date for implementing the plan, and on that day a cease-fire would commence and an impartial body would begin investigating which side started the war. After an interval of several days, to be determined by the secretary-general, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> would begin withdrawing their forces. After another interval, also set by <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON>, other elements of the resolution would be carried out and both sides would announce their intention to repatriate all prisoners of war. <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> has not commented publicly on the talks, but diplomats say <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> peace efforts are stalled because of intransigence by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and, to a lesser degree, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has said it accepts the resolution if <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> does so explicitly. The Iranians have said only that they endorse an outline given by the secretary-general for implementation, not the resolution itself. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> insists <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> be declared the aggressor before a cease-fire takes effect. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in September 1980 after several border skirmishes. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is urging the council to impose an arms embargo on <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> to force its compliance with the resolution. An embargo resolution is being drafted but the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> wants to allow more time for diplomacy. In his report, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> said he emphasized to both sides that a cease-fire must be `` an irreversible step towards the overall solution,'' not a recess used to rearm. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has expressed concern that without a permanent cease-fire and immediate troop withdrawal, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would use a lull to rearm, repair its damaged oil refineries and prepare for renewed warfare.
