<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Jackson Campaign Chairman Faces Revolt on Home Front</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 These are the best of times and the worst of times for <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, the flamboyant speaker of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Assembly </LOCATION> and national chairman of <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s presidential campaign They are heady times for <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> as the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign continues to exceed expectations and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> emerges as a serious contender for the Democratic nomination for president. They are also tough times for <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> as he is under siege as never before on his home turf, in the halls of the state Capitol, where his 7 -LCB- - year rule of the Assembly is in danger <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> voices quiet confidence in both arenas. In the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign, he modestly understates his current role or potential influence at the Democratic National Convention. In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> political circles, his public calm conceals a desperate battle to hold his powerful office. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s appointment as <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s national chairman last November was widely reported as a major boost to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s campaign. As the black leader of a predominately white legislative body and as a pre-eminent fund-raiser for <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Democrats, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> was seen as someone possessing the political skills, prestige, experience and contacts <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> needed most to broaden his constituency among white political leaders and voters. That's exactly what has happened to the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign. And while <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> publicly gives all of the credit to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, his influence in the campaign appears strong, and <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> is increasingly being viewed as a key player in picking the next Democratic nominee if the convention becomes deadlocked. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who originally backed <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> for the 1988 nomination, acknowledges that he was initially attracted to the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> campaign as a vehicle to `` get in the room'' of major players who would pick the Democratic nominee if the convention deadlocked. `` I need to get a horse with 1,000 chits -LRB- delegates -RRB- to get in the room. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> looks like my best agent,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> as saying a year ago. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> confirmed that quote earlier this month, but said `` I'm beyond that now,'' and that his goal is `` trying to secure the nomination for Mr <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>.'' `` I've been there once, -LRB- in the inner circle picking a presidential nominee -RRB- and I'm going to be back,'' <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said, referring to 1972, when he co-chaired the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> delegation which was key to winning the nomination for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> McGovern </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> claims to have raised $ 1 million for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a good chunk of the candidate's overall treasury. And he talks regularly by telephone to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a compulsive caller. But while <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s potential influence on national politics is greater than ever before, his political base is <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> is crumbling. The 54-year-old <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, who was raised in a one-room house in racially segregated <LOCATION> Mineola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tex. </LOCATION>, hitchhiked to <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> after high school and worked as a janitor while living with an uncle and attending college and law school. He started a storefront law practice in 1959 which, by his own description, was primarily `` pimps and prostitutes,'' and became active in civil rights demonstrations. Within five years, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, then 30, had won a seat in the state Assembly. By 1971, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> was chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, a powerful fiscal post which paradoxically made <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> nominally the legislative author of then-Gov. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s state budgets. Then, in a 1980 coalition with the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> minority, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> defeated two other Democrats to become Assembly speaker, an office which the late <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Unruh </PERSON> had transformed a decade earlier from a ceremonial presiding officer's job into a fund-raising and policy-making post second in influence only to the governor. The speaker's office, replete with both the subtle and overt trappings of power, fit <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> like a glove. His wit and flamboyant style made him an instant success as a fund-raiser, helping him raise up to $ 5 million annually for other Democrats, thereby cementing his hold on the office and freeing him from dependence on a coalition with Republicans. Being speaker, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said, was like being `` the Ayatollah of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>,'' with power to set the legislative agenda and assign or remove colleagues from legislative committees. It also gave him an office in the Capitol he describes as `` bigger than my home town,'' which matched nicely the taste for lavish parties, $ 1,000 suits and $ 100,000 sports cars which <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> acquired as his private law practice has evolved from criminal to corporate. But as the Democratic majority in the 80-seat Assembly has slipped under <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> from 47 to the current 44 seats, complaints grew that his flamboyance and sometimes embarrassing remarks were hurting Democrats more than his fund-raising was helping them. This came to a head earlier this year when five conservative Assembly Democrats, motivated by a variety of relatively obscure personal disagreements with <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, bolted his leadership. Without their support, <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> retains the title and outward trappings of the speakership, but without a working majority. The five have aligned themselves with Republicans to push anti-abortion, death penalty and wiretap bills which <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> previously bottled up in committee, and they have even defeated routine legislative housekeeping rules backed by <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> at first punished the five, stripping them of most legislative duties and banishing them to smaller Capitol offices. More recently, he has ignored or downplayed the defeats, contending it never was his intent to dictate policy. The five dissident Democrats, who hold the balance of power in the Assembly, say they have no intention now of trying to oust <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>. `` Why should we? We are controlling the policy agenda,'' says one of the five, Democrat <PERSON> Rusty </PERSON> <PERSON> Areias </PERSON>. That means <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> can probably continue to occupy the speaker's office until the current Assembly session adjourns Aug. 31 <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> says he will re-elected speaker next year. But unless he wins back the five dissident Democrats, his hopes for another term as speaker depend on either winning at least two more Democratic seats this year to create a majority not dependent on the five rebels or forging another coalition with Republicans. As Sacramento-based political columnist <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> puts it, `` There is a growing sense in the Capitol that <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>'s days as speaker are numbered. But no one has figured out the number yet.''
