<HEAD>Business Leaders' Confidence Rises In First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Confidence among top business executives in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy following October's stock market crash has rebounded, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. During the first quarter, the business research group's measure of business confidence ticked up to 51 after falling to a five-year low of 47 in the final quarter of 1987, the group said Wednesday. The measure reflects a scale of 0 to 100. More than a third of the 1,000 executives polled said they expect to have greater problems finding qualified employees this year than in the previous year. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said nearly 20 percent of the executives polled expect employment in their industries to rise this year, but 29 percent expect job losses. Business services and the instruments and primary metals industries hold the brightest employment prospects, while banking, gas and electric utilities and the insurance industry are likely to be hit with job losses, the board reported. `` The moderate rise in business executives' confidence parallels an upturn in consumer confidence during the first quarter,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Malin </PERSON>. `` A strong irony in the latest survey is that all of the increased optimism revolves around likely business conditions later this year, not now,'' he added.
