<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Hit New Highs; Dollar Up Marginally</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning stock closing figures,
other details. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> reached new highs again on Thursday morning, while the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar rose marginally against the Japanese yen in early foreign exchange activity. The bellwether Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues climbed for the fourth consecutive day, adding another 67.52 points to Wednesday's record close to finish the morning session at 27,053.07. It was the first time the Nikkei average ever topped 27,000, surpassing its previous intraday high of 26,988.36 points hit in early trading on Monday. The Nikkei index has come within five points of the 27,000 mark in intraday trading three times this week, but slipped back each time amid the continuing market rally. In currency trading, the dollar opened at 126.20 yen, down 0.25 yen from Wednesday's finish, but later edged higher and was changing hands at 126.35 yen by late morning. <PERSON> Fumihiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Morimoto </PERSON> of the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> said the market was supported by continued strength on Wall Street and somewhat by the agreement among the seven top industrialized nations to continue cooperating to keep the dollar from falling further. In a two-page joint communique after a meeting Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the finance ministers and central bank governors of the seven nations announced the extension of a Dec. 22 agreement in which they pledged to stabilize the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. The so-called Group of Seven nations are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. A dealer at a major <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> investment firm, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the foreign exchange market likely would be affected more by the release Thursday of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade figures for February. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit has affected the dollar's direction in recent months because the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration has supported a lower dollar as a way of narrowing the gap.
