<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar plummeted in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> today after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government reported the American merchandise trade deficit unexpectedly widened in February. Gold prices dropped during the morning session. The dollar fell almost two and a half cents against the British pound, nearly three pfennigs against the West German mark and more than two and a half Japanese yen after the trade report. The tumbling <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency compelled several major central banks to intervene and buy dollars to cushion the fall, traders reported. The merchandise trade deficit widened to $ 13.83 billion in February from $ 12.44 billion in January, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. Economists had expected the deficit to narrow to between $ 11.2 billion $ 11.8 billion. Dealers said the dollar was not affected by Wednesday's announcement by finance ministers and central bankers of the seven major monetary nations that they had reaffirmed their December commitment to stabilizing exchange rates The move was widely expected and had already been discounted in the market, dealers said. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar fell marginally to 126.15 yen, closing 0.30 yen lower than Wednesday. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 123.75 compared 126.30 yen in the morning. `` The news of the -LRB- Group of Seven -RRB- meeting was nothing substantial,'' said a dealer at a major <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> investment firm in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Here are dollar rates after the trade report was released, with midmorning rates in parentheses and compared with late Wednesday: 1.6650 -LRB- 1.6920 -RRB- West German marks, down from 1.6895; 1.3745 -LRB- 1.4010 -RRB- Swiss francs, down from 1.3983; 5.6510 -LRB- 5.7385 -RRB- <LOCATION> French </LOCATIO