<HEAD>Trade Deficit Wides Unexpectedly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to update market reaction to trade report
and include business inventories report, picks up 6th grav pvs,
``On Wednesday ...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened unexpectedly in February to $ 13.8 billion, its biggest shortfall since October, the government said today. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the excess of imports over exports rose $ 1.4 billion from January's $ 12.4 billion imbalance. The dollar fell shortly after the announcement and on Wall Street, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average was down about 38 points to about 2069, reflecting traders' disappointment with the news. Financial markets had expected the deficit to shrink slightly. For the first two months of 1988, the deficit ran at an annual rate of $ 157.6 billion, below the record $ 171.2 billion of last year but still worse than second highest imbalance of $ 156.2 billion in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. Imports of foreign manufactured goods, oil and farm products increased by $ 2.3 billion in February. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports also rose, but by a smaller $ 1.3 billion from January. In another report today, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said business inventories rose a slight 0.1 percent in February, much slower than the pace in recent months. The department said the gain in inventories pushed them up by $ 825 million during February to a seasonally adjusted $ 715.9 billion. The gain came as total business sales were climbing 0.6 percent to a seasonally adjusted $ 468.3 billion in February, reversing a 0.5 percent decline in January. On Wednesday, top finance ministers of seven major industrial nations said the countries will keep working to stabilize the value of the dollar against other major currencies. The finance ministers and central bankers of the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> nations </ORGANIZATION> also announced they would develop a plan to use gold and other commodities as a way of measuring inflation pressures. Mindful of investors' continued uneasiness at any signs of disunity, the finance leaders went out of their way in their joint statement to emphasize their strong desire to cooperate with each other in keeping the global economy from toppling into a recession. The statement reaffirmed a Dec. 22 agreement that had been issued after long-distance discussions in which the seven countries pledged to work together to keep the dollar from falling further against major currencies. The dollar rose against most other major currencies Wednesday although most traders stayed on the sidelines waiting for today's trade deficit figures The group meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consists of finance ministers and central bank leaders from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. In their first face-to-face meeting since before the October stock crash, the finance ministers also were critical of the newly industrialized nations of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> for not doing enough to reduce global trade imbalances. In other economic news on Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said retail sales rose 0.8 percent in March and automakers said sales of domestic cars and light trucks fell 10.8 percent in early April compared with a year earlier. The drop in auto sales came after three months of unexpectedly strong results. One analyst, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, described it as a `` hiccup.'' Retail sales were helped by Easter buying at department and food stores. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it was the fifth consecutive monthly increase and the largest since December. On Wall Street, stock prices retreated slightly as the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average fell 2.98 points to 2,107.10. It was the first Dow decline after gains totaling more than 129 points in six sessions.
