<TEXT>
 Entertainer <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> has reached an agreement to buy <ORGANIZATION> Resorts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> from property developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, ending a much-publicized takeover battle, the two dealmakers said today. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, who was in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> this morning to meet with state gaming regulators, said he and <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> came to the agreement after a day-long meeting in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Wednesday. Shareholders other than <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> would be paid $ 36 a share under the plan, giving the deal an indicated value of about $ 206 million. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who paid $ 135 a share for his stake in the company, also is getting paid in cash, said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Nusbaum </PERSON>, the developer's attorney But he would not provide details of the payment to <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> except to say his client is `` pleased he is making a profit.'' Under terms reached between the two high-living businessmen, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> would acquire Resorts' troubled 1,250-room Taj Mahal hotel and casino project under construction in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> to add to his battery of gaming operations. He also would acquire other unidentified assets. <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, who hosted the `` <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON> Show'' for 23 years, would control the existing Resorts Hotel and Casino in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> and all <LOCATION> Paradise </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> operations in the <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. The agreement ends a lengthy jousting match that observers initially expected would see <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> emerge as the victor. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON