<FIRST>u f PM-FinanceMinisters 2ndLd-Writethru   04-14 1052</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Finance Ministers, 2nd Ld-Writethru,1079</SECOND>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs pvs grafs 9-10, Baker who is, with new grafs 9-13 on
Baker remarks. Removes last 4 grafs pvs to shorten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The world's top financial leaders today tried to put the best face on a surprisingly large <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit in an effort to calm currency markets thrown into disarray by the unexpected dose of bad news. The dollar plunged immediately after the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that the imbalance between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports and exports surged to $ 13.8 billion in February, the highest monthly imbalance since the record October figure. The trade deficit report came one day after the world's seven major industrial countries held high-level talks in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and pledged renewed cooperation to support the value of the dollar at current levels. Before today's trade report, the seven countries had been successful for four months in their efforts to stabilize the greenback. Basking in that success, the seven nations had issued a glowing communique on Wednesday in which they renewed their commitment to use intervention as a way to keep the dollar from falling further. Intervention is the process by which governments buy currencies on the open market in order to prop up their value. The bad trade number immediately tested the economic powers' resolve as the dollar plunged precipitously, dropping below a level of 125 yen That benchmark is considered to be the target the industrial powers are aiming at in their dollar-stabilization drive. Currency traders reported that the central banks of <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> were intervening today in an effort to break the dollar's fall. Treasury Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, the prime architect of a three-year effort to manage currency exchange rates, was grim-faced and said nothing as he arrived for today's session of finance ministers, being held as part of the spring meeting of the 151-nation <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION>. While <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> did not talk to reporters before the closed-door sessions began, a text of his remarks to the finance ministers was released later. In those comments, <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> played down the significance of the February surge in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. `` The trade figures released this morning should be seen in context. As we have said before, too much emphasis should not be placed on any one month's figures,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. `` Monthly trade figures are by their nature erratic.'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the important thing to realize was that the overall trend pointed to an improving <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade performance this year. He said one of the reasons for this optimistic view was the success that the major industrial countries have had in coordinating an economic policy. He said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has made great strides in cutting the federal budget deficit while <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> have all taken significant actions to boost domestic growth, efforts that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has long urged as a way of increasing the demand for American products. West German Finance Minister <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> also tried to play down the significance of the one-month surge in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. `` It is a monthly figure. We do not expect that it will change the basic trend,'' <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> said during a break in the closed-door talks. Asked if the countries would now be forced to set a new base level for the dollar, considering the fact that it had dropped below the 125-yen level, <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> said, `` That is a very good question, a thousand-dollar question.'' Neither <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> nor <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Poehl </PERSON>, the head of the West German central bank, would confirm that central banks were intervening today to support the dollar. But <PERSON> Stoltenberg </PERSON> said, `` The central banks will cooperate. There is no doubt. We announced it yesterday.'' The so-called Group of Seven, including the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, issued a two-page communique Wednesday reaffirming their Dec. 22 pact to keep the international value of the dollar stable. But today's new assault on the dollar served to emphasize just how difficult it may be to uphold that commitment. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its six allies decided in September 1985 to push the dollar lower to correct <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s huge trade deficit, but the countries have been trying since February 1987 to halt the currency's decline. The effort did not meet with much success last year, and the steadily deteriorating dollar was cited as one of the reasons the world's financial markets were thrown into turmoil last October. But since Dec. 22, the major industrial countries have crafted a new strategy to stabilize the dollar and that agreement has held for the past four months, backed up by periodic intervention in currency markets, the process of buying the dollar to prop up its value. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> first unveiled his commodity price indicator at the last meeting of the seven countries' finance leaders in September. Some nations expressed skepticism then, wondering whether the idea was a veiled effort to re-introduce a gold standard. But <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> picked up enough converts to get the proposal endorsed, although other finance ministers stressed that many details of the plan, including just what commodities to include, still remain to be worked out. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> has insisted that his approach is not an effort to return to the gold-based monetary system that existed between the end of World War II and 1973. For most of that time, the price of gold was fixed at $ 35 an ounce and the currencies of other governments were set at fixed rates based on the dollar. President <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> broke the link with gold in 1973 as the so-called <PERSON> Bretton </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> system crumbled under the weight of rising inflation and large trade imbalances. In another victory for <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, the joint statement Wednesday singled out the newly industrialized countries in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> for criticism for their continued high trade surpluses. It urged those nations to do more to lower their own barriers to other countries' exports and to allow their currencies to rise in value in relation to the dollar These developments are seen as critical by the administration if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is to make progess this year in reducing its trade deficit, which hit a record $ 171 billion in 1987. Almost one-fourth of that total came in trade with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>.
