 Three utility districts have reached a $ 20 million settlement with bondholders who were left holding $ 2.25 billion in debt after the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supply </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> defaulted on bonds for two abandoned nuclear power plants. The settlement was announced Thursday by <PERSON> Junius </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, a court-appointed special master overseeing negotiations to settle a huge lawsuit in the case. The securities-fraud suit is tentatively set to go to trial in September in <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz </LOCATION>. The settlement, still subject to final drafting as well as formal approval by the court and utility district officials, involves the <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Chelan </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> counties public utility districts, <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> said. It comes two days after the city of <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> announced it had settled its part in the lawsuit for $ 50 million. City attorneys said that was much less expensive than fighting the case and taking the risk of being held responsible for all or part of the potential $ 2.25 billion judgment. The latest settlement, worked out by attorneys for the utility districts and for <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, which represents the bondholders' interests, brings the total of all settlements to $ 176 million The litigation continues against remaining defendants, who include the supply system, utilities that sponsored the plants and others, <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> noted. The bond default was the largest in the history of the municipal bond market. The power system abandoned the two plants six years ago following cost overruns and studies indicating the power from the plants was n't needed. The two abandoned plants, at the <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> nuclear reservation in south-central <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and at <LOCATION> Satsop </LOCATION>, west of <LOCATION> Olympia </LOCATION>, were among five nuclear power plants <ORGANIZATION> WPPSS </ORGANIZATION> attempted to build during the 1970s. One is currently operating at <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION>. The remaining two, also at <LOCATION> Hanford </LOCATION> and Satsop, were mothballed when partially complete because of financing problems and doubts about the need for the power they would produce.
