<HEAD>Wider U.S. Trade Deficit Sends the Dollar into a Tailspin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: An AM version expected by 5:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar ended sharply lower in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> Thursday after news that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened in February sent the currency into a tailspin that was only partially stemmed by coordinated central bank intervention. Gold prices rose. Dealers had expected the trade deficit to narrow in February and had built up long dollar positions _ or had bought dollars that they had n't yet agreed to sell _ which had to be quickly sold off. The dollar plummeted against most major currencies within minutes of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announcement that the trade gap had widened to $ 13.8 billion in February from $ 12.4 billion in January. `` The trade figure caught everyone on the hop,'' said <PERSON> Marek </PERSON> <PERSON> Stefanowicz </PERSON>, a corporate adviser at <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Within minutes of the start of the dollar's fall, the central banks of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> intervened to buy dollars, dealers reported. Later, several of the central banks, notably the <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bundesbank </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION>, confirmed their intervention. The interventions were not particularily large, dealers reported, but were effective because all the banks intervened at once. The intervention did not push the dollar any higher but was able to stem its decline. `` It is only the central banks keeping the dollar at these levels,'' said a trader at a British merchant bank. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.8755 to buy one pound, more expensive than $ 1.8445 late Wednesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's: 1.6635 West German marks, down from 1.6895; 1.3745 Swiss francs, down from 1.3983; 5.6390 French francs, down from 5.7295; 1.8680 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8950; 1,244.00 Italian lire, down from 1,252.50; and 1.2368 Canadian dollars, up from 1.23675. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar fell 0.30 yen to close at 126.15 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 123.60 yen. Gold rose in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid price of $ 451.00 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $ 449.25. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold was higher, closing at a bid $ 450.50 compared with $ 449.50 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.34 to close at a bid $ 449.48. Silver bullion prices rose on the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> market where the metal was trading at a late bid price of $ 6.43 a troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $ 6.41.
