<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs; Subs graf 8, Senate passage, to update.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> today approved a $ 1.1 trillion federal budget for fiscal 1989 after earlier deciding not to shift $ 50 million in spending from energy research to health care programs. The spending plan was passed on a 69-26 vote. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, which passed its version of the budget earlier, must now agree on a compromise measure. Senators earlier had voted 57-38 against a proposal that would have transferred $ 50 million away from the superconducting super collider, a physics research program planned by the government and expected to cost about $ 4.4 billion ultimately. There still would have been $ 40 million in spending left next year for the massive project. The amendment would have used the money instead for childhood immunizations, community health centers, and to train nurses and other health care workers to take care of the elderly. `` It speaks to ... kids, old folks, poor people,'' Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., the amendment's author, said of it `` Their lives today are as important as our other knowledge in the future.'' But opponents who spoke, most from the seven states competing for the super collider, argued that the project's scientific and economic benefits were too great to jeopardize. `` We can protect the health of our citizens without jeopardizing the economic health of our nation,'' said Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Tenn </LOCATION>., whose state is seeking the project <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passage put <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on track to completing its budget work unusually early in the year, largely because the summit agreement between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and congressional leaders solved most of the normally testy problems. But one of the questions the summit allegedly tamed _ how much money the government will spend on domestic programs _ reared its head Wednesday. That occurred when the lawmakers voted 93-0 to add $ 1.4 billion for drug programs such as law enforcement and prison construction, a measure legislators found difficult to oppose in an election year. The budget originally allowed $ 148.1 billion in domestic spending, the cap set in the summit pact. To get around that, the amendment's supporters said the drug spending would only occur if it could be paid for by better collection of taxes and debts owed the government. And they noted that the summit accord provided for additional spending in cases of a `` dire emergency.'' Asked if he believed the White House would accept the extra spending, Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who wrote the provision with Sen. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., said, `` They're damned fools if they do n't recognize it's a dire emergency. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> had earlier approved another anti-drug measure by a 76-18 vote, adding $ 125 million for federal prisons and agents. The language, sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., provided the money by reducing federal travel spending The lawmakers began considering amendments after untangling themselves from arguments that began Monday, when they began debating the budget, over the spending plan's $ 136 billion deficit. Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the budget committee, argued that the real size of the deficit was cloaked because the huge surpluses of the Social Security system are included in the fiscal calculations Soon, lawmakers began trying to remove other special funds _ covering money set aside for transportation, banking and other programs _ from the deficit computations. Eventually, an amendment sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the budget panel, was approved that handed the problem to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which will suggest answers to budget problems next year. Other than the new domestic spending, the budget follows the summit pact's strictures. It contains no new taxes, since $ 14 billion in new levies called for by the summit have already been enacted. It also allows $ 294 billion for military spending and $ 16.1 billion for international assistance. The major differences between the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget and the spending plan <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed in February are in domestic spending. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would spend more on energy, agriculture, housing and community development than the president, and less on natural resources, law enforcement and income security. Like the president, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> would give vast boosts to spending for space and science, education, and aviation safety. The proposal's computed deficit of $ 136 billion meets precisely the deficit target set in the Gramm-Rudman balanced budget law for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. The law is designed to eliminate the government's red ink by 1993. The House approved its version of the budget last month. The two chambers must approve identical spending blueprints, but the president's signature is not required. The budget is not binding. It is used as a guide by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as it passes legislation that actually provides money for federal programs.
