<HEAD>Dow Jones Plunges 100 Points; Dollar Slides; Interest Rates Rise</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Grafs 1-10 new with closing stocks, late dollar and bonds.
Picks up 11th graf: The bulge ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stock prices and the dollar plunged and interest rates shot higher today after an unexpected bulge in the trade deficit sent shock waves through the financial markets. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped about 101 points, while in the currency markets the value of the dollar fell 2 percent against major currencies. Interest rates on a key long-term <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond jumped to a three-month high. Traders scrambled to sell dollars, bonds and stocks after the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported this morning that the nation's trade deficit had risen to $ 13.8 billion in February. That was the biggest shortfall since the record of $ 17.6 billion in October and the second monthly increase in a row. Many economists had been expecting the deficit to narrow. The Dow Jones industrials tumbled 35 points within 20 minutes of the opening bell on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> then stabilized for a few hours. But the slide resumed in the afternoon and the average skidded to a 101.46-point loss at 2,005.63, a 4.8 percent drop, according to a prelimary calculation. It was the worst decline since the Dow plunged 140.58 points on Jan. 8. The Dow's decline triggered a ban on the use of a form of computerized program trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the first time the `` collar'' has been triggered by a decline of 50 points or more in the Dow. Prices also fell on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-share index fell 1.3 percent, dropping 23.2 points to 1,787.2. Currency brokers reported the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> and other central banks, concerned about a rout in the dollar, swooped into foreign exchange markets to buy dollars with Japanese yen, British pounds and West German marks to try to stabilize the currency's value. The dollar was down about 1.9 percent against the British pound, about 1.9 percent against the West German mark and about 2.2 percent against the Japanese yen at midafternoon. The impact also was felt in the bond market, an important barometer of the economy and interest rates. By late afternoon, prices of the key 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond were down 1 \ points, or about $ 12.50 for every $ 1,000 in face amount, and its yield, which moves inversely to price, surged to 8.855 percent, the highest in three months The bulge in the trade deficit suggested <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s trade problems remain more stubborn than earlier believed, leading some traders to believe that the dollar needs to fall further to make <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods more competitive in the global market. However, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Frequency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the February deficit was smaller than the deficit of $ 14.4 billion in February 1987, indicating that trade flows are improving. Central banks that bought dollars to halt the currency's slide ranged across the board, from the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Italy </ORGANIZATION> to the central bank of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, a currency analyst in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. A seven-nation accord announced Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had little effect on the currency market, <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> said, because it merely reaffirmed a December agreement by finance officials of the countries to support the dollar The seven nations are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
