<HEAD>Chemical, Hanover, Security Pacific and Bank of New York Report
Earnings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: With AM-Bank Bid, Bjt</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Four major bank holding companies _ <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ reported sharp rises Thursday in their first quarter profits from a year ago. Analysts said the results generally were in line to slightly better than expected and showed that the banks' continuing efforts to trim expenses were paying off. Chemical, the nation's fourth-largest banking company, said net income for the first three months of this year rose 45.6 percent, to $ 125.5 million, or $ 1.95 a share, from $ 86.2 million, or $ 1.58 a share, a year ago. Manufacturers Hanover, ranked sixth, reported a 73.2 percent jump in its earnings, to $ 140.3 million, or $ 2.56 a share, from $ 81.0 million, or $ 1.68 a share, in first quarter 1987. Security Pacific, No. 7, netted $ 147.2 million, or $ 1.30 a share, compared with $ 116.5 million, or $ 1.06 a share. No. 26 <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, which is engaged in a hostile battle to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, reported net earnings of $ 54.4 million, or $ 1.47 a share. That was up 15 percent from $ 47.3 million, or $ 1.32 per share, a year earlier. `` Most banks have been pretty good restraining overhead costs. That has helped the results,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, a banking analyst with <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION>. `` Fee income and trading activity is also very strong.'' Chemical said fees for trust and other banking services totaled $ 211.1 million, up 33.9 percent from the previous year. It said securities trading profits were $ 32.7 million in the quarter, up from $ 21.9 million last year. The company also said its provision for loan losses rose to $ 105.6 million from 87.2 million. Manufacturers Hanover said it lowered its loan-loss provision to $ 141.6 million from $ 152.5 million last year. The company also reported big increases in trading revenue and other fees. Revenue from all trading activities was $ 67.3 million, up 72.4 percent from $ 39.1 million in the first quarter. `` Strong core operating results were in line with what we had been projecting, and our financial plan to replenish common shareholders' equity is on track,'' Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> McGillicuddy </PERSON> stated. As part of that plan, <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> announced earlier this week it reached an agreement in principle to sell its consumer finance subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hanover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Security Pacific Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flamson </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> said his bank also was beginning to see positive results from its programs to control expense growth `` We expect to be implementing more new expense reduction plans ...'' he said. At <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> said strong performances by the company's core businesses contributed to the overall earnings growth. Core businesses at <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> are corporate banking, securities processing, retail banking and trust and investment management.
