<HEAD>Wider U.S. Trade Deficit Sends the Dollar into a Tailspin</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar plunged on foreign exchange markets Thursday after traders were shocked by an unexpected jump in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. `` The market was caught by surprise,'' said <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Sapiro </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illinois </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Financial markets had expected the trade gap to shrink in February from its January level of $ 12.4 billion, so when the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced a $ 13.8 billion deficit Thursday morning, panic selling of dollars set in, <PERSON> Sapiro </PERSON> said. But gold prices benefited from the report. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> quoted a bid of $ 452.65 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, up more than $ 6 from late Wednesday's $ 446.60. The central banks of several nations, including the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION>, bought dollars to help stabilize the currency, but the dollar still lost about 2 percent of its value against the West German mark, British pound and Japanese yen. `` They stemmed what would have been a momentary freefall,'' said <PERSON> Varick </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Switzerland </ORGANIZATION>, of the banks' intervention. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said the dollar fell 2 pfennigs against the mark immediately after the trade report, regained some ground and then fell again before closing near its lows for the day. The trade report came on the heels of an agreement among the <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seven </ORGANIZATION> industrial nations that reaffirmed a Dec. 22 pact to keep the dollar stable. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said that agreement contributed to the dollar's slide. `` The -LRB- dollar -RRB- rates on Dec. 22 were substantially lower -LRB- than they are now -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said, suggesting that the currency markets interpreted the ministers' agreement as supporting the dollar at lower levels. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> predicted traders would test the dollar at its lower levels to see if the central banks will again step in to support the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. If the dollar does not resume its fall Friday `` it will come back somewhat,'' <PERSON> Sapiro </PERSON> said. However, he did not expect any dramatic improvement. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.8755 to buy one pound, more expensive than $ 1.8445 late Wednesday. In later <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> trading, sterling jumped to $ 1.8739 from $ 1.83755 late Wednesday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's prices, included: 1.66275 West German marks, down from 1.6950; 1.3720 Swiss francs, down from 1.4055; 5.6325 French francs, down from 5.74375; 1,233.00 Italian lire, down from 1,255.75; and 1.2365 Canadian dollars, down from 1.23775. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late Wednesday's, rates, included: 1.6635 West German marks, down from 1.6895; 1.3745 Swiss francs, down from 1.3983; 5.6390 French francs, down from 5.7295; 1.8680 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8950; 1,244.00 Italian lire, down from 1,252.50; and 1.2368 Canadian dollars, up from 1.23675. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ended before the trade figures came out, the dollar fell 0.30 yen to close at 126.15 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 123.60 yen and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it fell to 123.725 yen from 126.44 late Wednesday. Gold bullion prices rose in response to the trade report, said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, vice president and bullion dealer at <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. On the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a troy ounce of gold climbed to $ 454 from $ 447 late Wednesday. The metal's gain was smaller in earlier <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading. Gold closed there at a late bid price of $ 451.00 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $ 449.25. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold closed at a bid $ 450.50 compared with $ 449.50 late Wednesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.34 to close at a bid $ 449.48. Silver was up on the Comex in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, closing at $ 6.450 a troy ounce, compared with late Wednesday's $ 6.325. In earlier <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> trading, silver traded at a late bid price of $ 6.43 a troy ounce, compared with Wednesday's $ 6.41.
