<HEAD>Fight Still Raging Over Putting Spotlight on Foreign Investors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with British ambassador's letter after 15th
graf, ``If you''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 One week before planned floor debate on sweeping trade legislation, lawmakers remain deeply split over whether to require public disclosure of foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I think Americans should be allowed to know who is investing in this country,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, told reporters Wednesday. `` I do n't see any justification for secrecy.'' But <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> hinted that within the week leaders might yield to the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and other critics and bar the provision sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, from the 1,000-page trade bill. Actually, the <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> amendment is not even part of the bill. A panel attempting to draft a compromise between rival <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> versions of the trade measure was unable to reach agreement on foreign investment disclosure and simply left the issue hanging. The provisions in <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>'s amendment are complex. They would require foreigners and overseas-based companies to register with the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> if they owned 5 percent or more of an American company or real estate in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if assets of the property were worth at least $ 5 million. Such an investor would be required to disclose his name, address, nationality, principal business, share in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investment, date that it was acquired, the purchase price, location of the property, its name and the primary business in which it was involved. Some of this information already must be filed with the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, but is not publicly available. It would be under <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>'s plan. Companies with a 25 percent share in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business or property with assets or annual sales of more than $ 20 million would have to disclose much of the detailed information required of corporations by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on its 10-K form. The items range from a list of directors and officers to a financial balance sheet. As soon as <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> introduced the measure, it caused an uproar. It flies in the face of business secrecy customs strictly observed for centuries throughout much of the world. Indeed, business disclosure laws are carefully drawn and limited within the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Critics of the amendment say it would immediately cut off the flow of capital to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from overseas and cause economic disaster. `` If we impede that flow, we will be slitting our own economic throats,'' declared Rep. <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Lent </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who has fought the amendment repeatedly as a member of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. One of the first victims would be such financial markets as the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> where foreigners are regular investors, Lent said. `` Buying in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Toyko </LOCATION> and other markets will flourish at the expense of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and our markets, which are envied throughout the world, will be impaired,'' he argued. He scoffed at the notion that foreign investment constitutes a danger and thus should be publicly spotlighted. `` If you wake up in the morning and say that foreign investment is evil, is dangerous, that is a kind of naive, xenophobic view,'' Lent said. British Ambassador <PERSON> Antony </PERSON> <PERSON> Acland </PERSON> said in a March 15 letter to Lent that the <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> amendment would affect some British companies that invest in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and `` put them at a real commercial disadvantage.'' `` It would discourage new investment from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Acland </PERSON> said in the letter, which Lent inserted in the March 29 Congressional Record. <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> waves such objections aside, citing figures suggesting that foreign investment in farmland, factories, banks, businesses, buildings, government securities and elsewhere within the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy has shot up over the last seven years. `` Foreign money has been financing a record borrowing binge, while disguising the fact that we are living dangerously beyond our means,'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> said. `` Floating on a feather bed of foreign financing, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has fallen from its status as the world's largest creditor nation in 1982 to become the largest debtor nation in history, with a foreign debt exceeding those of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> combined,'' he added. The administration sent out strong signals over the last few months that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto the trade bill if it contained <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>'s plan. That threat supplied powerful ammunition to the measure's critics on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., sought to break the deadlock at one point with a modification under which the need for disclosure would be studied and existing <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> information would be shown to lawmakers on a confidential basis Administration officials, however, sent back word that this proposal also would be likely to provoke a veto, and the idea was dropped. Not much information about foreign ownership of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> property exists in the public domain. However, studies have shown that citizens of other countries held title to less than one percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmland. But the sheer volume of ownership is not the sole issue, <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> contends. He said it is important that <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> know exactly who owns what. `` Because of the lack of adequate reporting requirements,'' he said, `` we can not determine whether new foreign owners of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assets are legitimate businesses, hostile nations like <LOCATION> Libya </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, corrupt Third World dictators like the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Ferdinand </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> or organized drug traffickers laundering their ill-gotten gains.''
