<HEAD>Deficit Widened To $13.8 Billion In February</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads with 5 new grafs updating with impact on financial
markets, including closing Dow Jones industrial average; SUBS grafs
18-19 bgng ``The deficit ... '' to CORRECT figures on balances with
Japan and newly industrialized nations.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Assocated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The monthly <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit widened by more than 11 percent in February to $ 13.8 billion, the government said Thursday, sending both stock prices and the dollar on a nosedive. The Dow Jones Industrial Average of 30 stocks plummeted 101 points or by about 5 percent and the value of the dollar against the Japanese yen and the German mark dropped about 2 percent on the foreign exchange markets. Only concerted intervention by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> and central banks in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in buying up large volumes of dollars with yen, marks and British pounds prevented the dollar from falling further. Triggering the turmoil was the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report that the gap between the nation's imports and exports expanded by $ 1.4 billion from January's imbalance of $ 12.4 billion. It was the second straight monthly jump in the trade imbalance that had declined in November and December from a record $ 17.6 billion defict last October. `` We've stumbled here a little bit,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldinger </PERSON>, an analyst for Capital Insight, an economic consulting firm based in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` It reminds us that we have a major, major problem.'' Analysts had largely predicted beforehand that the February deficit would shrink slightly, the normal seasonal pattern for this time of year. `` For the second time in only seven years, there was huge, atypical increase in imports in February, showing that Americans have not lost their appetite for foreign goods,'' said <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON>, an economist for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` It means we have not solved the budget and trade deficit problems,'' <PERSON> Sinai </PERSON> said. `` And if policymakers and consumers do n't tighten their belts, the markets will, showing up in a tumbling dollar, spikes in interest rates and ultimately, in a recession, although not likely this year. Imports of foreign manufactured goods, oil and farm products increased by $ 2.6 billion in February to $ 37.4 billion. Leading the surge were imports of electrical equipment from abroad, up $ 323 million, and auto and truck parts, up $ 298 million. American exports also rose, but by a smaller $ 1.2 billion from January to $ 23.6 billion. For the first two months of 1988, the deficit is running at an annual rate of $ 157.6 billion, below the record $ 171.2 billion for all of last year but still worse than second highest imbalance of $ 156.2 billion in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. `` The nation's trade problems are severe and far from over,'' said <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Oswald </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION>'s chief economist. `` While exports are up by $ 10 billion from a year ago, so are imports, leaving <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> no further along the path towards reducing the jobs-destroying deficit.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials downplayed the February numbers, instead focusing on longer trends that show a grudgingly slow improvement since last summer. The trade deficit over the last three months has averaged $ 12.8 billion compared with a monthly average of $ 15 billion the previous three months. `` Monthly trade figures are by their nature erratic,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>. `` The figures seen this morning should be seen in context.'' With both exports and imports higher than they were in January, Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said there is no reason for alarm. `` So the market goes down a little bit,'' he said. `` The same thing happened last fall, and there's a great frenzy for no reason. I certainly do n't see it as a reason to pass protectionist legislation, which is the undercurrent of the opposition's program. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil imports jumped 1.2 million barrels a day in February to 8.1 million, the highest they have been since September 1986. As a result, the trade deficit with members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> shot up by $ 270 million over January to $ 1.3 billion. The deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the country with the largest trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, also increased dramatically, by $ 500 million to more than $ 4.5 billion. But it narrowed slightly with the so-called newly industrialized countries _ <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ falling by about $ 20 million to $ 2.9 billion. Imports of manufactured goods from abroad increased by $ 2.3 billion in February and were $ 1.8 billion higher than the monthly average of $ 27.1 billion in 1987. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is not building its capital stock sufficiently to meet domestic demand,'' said <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jasinowski </PERSON>, chief economist for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION>. `` The foreign sourcing during the period of the high dollar continues to represent a source of troubling import dependency.'' But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> manufacturers also fared better in February, raising their exports by $ 1.2 billion to $ 16.1 billion, the third highest month on record after November and December of last year. Despite the increase in auto and truck parts shipped here from abroad, exports of Japanese autos themselves to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> declined by more than $ 120 million to $ 1.5 billion in February. Auto imports from other countries, however, rose by nearly $ 390 million. Agricultural exports _ chiefly big increases in animal feeds, cotton and soybeans _ rose by $ 280 million over January to $ 3.2 billion, the highest they have been since 1984.
</TEXT>
