<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Top finance officials of the world's seven major industrial powers have agreed to continue efforts to stabilize the value of the dollar. The group, consisting of finance ministers and central bank leaders from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, issued a statement Wednesday announcing the extension of a Dec. 22 agreement that has so far successfully halted the currency's three-year decline. The two-page joint communique followed a full day of private meetings hosted by <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has launched an investigation into the finances and management of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest airline company. The department wants to determine if <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> and its management are `` fit, willing and able'' to carry commercial air traffic, <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnley </PERSON> said at a news conference Wednesday. In a separate action, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> imposed $ 823,000 in fines against <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, for violating safety regulations and said it has begun a new round of safety inspections of the Miami-based air carrier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The French communications giant <ORGANIZATION> Hachette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> made its second major venture into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> publishing market this week with an announcement that it will buy a major magazine publisher for $ 712 million. <ORGANIZATION> Hachette </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday it had agreed to buy <ORGANIZATION> Diamandis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a privately held concern that publishes a dozen magazines, including Woman's Day, Car & amp; Driver, <ORGANIZATION> Popular </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Photography </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Road </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Track and Stereo Review. The announcement came four days after <ORGANIZATION> Hachette </ORGANIZATION> reached an agreement to buy <ORGANIZATION> Grolier </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Danbury </LOCATION>, Conn.-based book publisher, for $ 450 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of domestic cars and light trucks fell 10.8 percent in early April from a year ago after three months of unexpectedly strong results, according to domestic automakers. The automakers said Wednesday they sold 230,486 domestic cars and light trucks in the eight selling days of April 1-10, down from 290,826 domestic vehicles in nine selling days the same period last year. Sales per day fell by 10.8 percent.
