<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has endorsed far-reaching legislation to permit banks to enter the securities business as long as consumers are protected adequately. <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and science subcommittee on Wednesday that the commission supports the Senate-passed repeal of the Glass-Steagall Act `` as long as the investor protection concerns arising from the entry of banks into securities activities are simultaneously addressed.'' Glass-Steagall is a Depression-era law that separated banking from the securities business in the aftermath of the 1929 financial crash.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A recent poll of more than 1,000 top executives indicates their confidence in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy is recovering in the wake of the stock market's collapse six months ago, a new study says. The Conference Board, a business research concern, said Wednesday that its measure of business confidence rose to 51 after falling to a five-year low of 47 in the final quarter of 1987. The measure reflects a scale of 0 to 100.
