<HEAD>Precious Metals Futures Rally On Investor `Flight To Safety'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Precious metals futures rebounded in price Thursday, erasing the previous two days' steep losses as investors shocked by the widening trade deficit sought security in gold, silver and platinum. On other markets, stock-index and bond futures fell sharply in response to the trade figure; energy futures advanced for the fourth straight day; grains and soybeans were mixed, and livestock and meat futures were mostly higher. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report that the trade deficit widened by $ 1.4 billion in February to $ 13.8 billion prompted some investment fund managers to sell stocks and bonds and move that money into precious metals, which tend to hold their value in troubled times, analysts said. `` We're getting some investor flight out of stocks and bonds and into precious metals, sort of a flight to safety,'' said <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Savakl </PERSON>, metals analyst for <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Commodity Exchange, gold for June delivery moved back above the psychologically important level of $ 450 a troy ounce after settling at $ 449.60 on Wednesday. The trade figure was a bullish suprise for the metals markets, which had sold off in recent days on expectations of a reduction in the trade deficit to $ 11 billion or less, <PERSON> Savakl </PERSON> said. The weaker dollar and late-morning news reports of an explosion in downtown <LOCATION> Johannesburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, lent further support to the markets. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> is a rich source of gold and platinum, and heightened violence there could disrupt mining of the metals. On the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold settled $ 6.90 to $ 8.80 higher with the contract for delivery in June at $ 456.50 a troy ounce; silver was 12.5 cents to 14.1 cents higher with May at $ 6.47 a troy ounce. Platinum on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> was $ 17.60 to $ 18.30 higher with July at $ 540.40 a troy ounce. Financial futures markets registered disappointment in the trade figure. The contract for June delivery of the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 stock index fell 13.7 points to 258.40 on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The June Treasury bond contract on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> fell 1 9 @ 32 points to 89.16. Energy futures posted solid gains on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> for the fourth straight day on continuing expectations that many oil-producing countries will agree to limit production to support prices. `` There's a lot of confidence coming back into the market,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 18 cents to 31 cents higher with May at $ 18.30 a barrel; heating oil was .35 cent to .49 cent higher with May at 49.51 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .06 cent lower to .46 cent higher with May at 52.36 cents a gallon A late rally pushed grain and soybean futures to a mixed close on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, possibly marking the end of a recent sharp downturn in prices. Prices had fallen on Tuesday and Wednesday and continued lower on Thursday until shortly before the closing bell, when C & amp; D Commodities, the largest speculative trading firm on the floor, began buying contracts and sparked `` a spectacular closing rally,'' said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Lespinasse </PERSON>, a trader for <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Wheat settled -RCB- cent to 2 cents lower with May at $ 3.16 -LCB- a bushel; corn was -LCB- cent lower to 1 cent higher with May at $ 2.04 \ a bushel; oats were -RCB- cent to 1 \ cents lower with May at $ 1.61 -LCB- a bushel; soybeans were 1 -RCB- cents to 5 \ cents higher with May at $ 6.77 -LCB- Steady cash markets supported cattle futures on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Hog futures were mixed on profit taking while frozen pork bellies advanced. Live cattle were .07 cent to .70 cent higher with April at 73.82 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .40 cent higher with April at 79.47 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to .15 cent higher with April at 45.02 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .30 cent to .42 cent higher with May at 52.07 cents a pound.
