<HEAD>SEC Alleges Insider Trading at Carl's Jr. Fast-Food Company</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS that Carl L. Karcher no longer a vice president in 9th
graf and that stock price declined in 10th graf. Picks up 10th graf
pvs: Those named.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two brothers and a son who control the <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s Jr. hamburger chain were accused of using inside information to benefit their relatives in a $ 2.5 million civil lawsuit brought Thursday by federal regulators Sixteen people, all but one of them members the family that lends its name to <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> <PERSON> Enterprises </PERSON>, were named in the insider-trading complaint filed Thursday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Founder <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>, who appears in <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s Jr. television commercials harking back to his youth on an old-time family farm, would be liable for $ 1 million in damages under the formula used in the complaint. The complaint alleges that in October 1984, the insiders or their relatives sold stock and debentures to make profits or avoid losses when the price of shares in the publicly held company plummeted because of an adverse quarterly report. `` We have to show people in these situations you do n't tell your brother, your family, your relatives,'' said <PERSON> Irving </PERSON> <PERSON> Einhorn </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> regional administrator, in announcing the filing. <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>, chairman of the Anaheim-based company that has 450 outlets in the West, promised a vigorous defense. `` These charges are totally false,'' <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> responded. `` My wife and I did not sell any of our stock, nor did we tell anyone else to do so. ... To suggest that any of us would intentionally violate the securities laws is highly offensive.'' <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> and his brother, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>, president and chief operating officer, are accused of passing information to their wives and children, but are n't accused of trading in the stock. The 12 other defendants, including the founder's son, <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>, a former vice president who now is a franchise holder, and <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> DeShano </PERSON>, who still is accounting director, are accused in the complaint of acting on the information. The rest of the defendants, none of them company employees, are children of the elder <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> brothers and the childrens's spouses. <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> stock closed at $ 15.50 per share Thursday in over-the-counter trading, down 87 -LCB- cents from Wednesday's close. Those named in the complaint made profits or avoided losses totaling $ 310,000, <PERSON> Einhorn </PERSON> said. The complaint seeks an injunction `` ordering them to disgorge profits derived and losses avoided.'' It also seeks triple damages from each of those accused of profiting. Against those accused of passing on information but not of making trades, it seeks damages of triple the amount of any profit allegedly made by those they tipped. That brings the total amount of penalties sought to $ 2.5 million. <PERSON> Einhorn </PERSON> attributed the losses to `` a downturn in profits after the Olympics,'' which brought hundreds of thousands of visitors to the city in the summer of 1984. He said alleged offenses were uncovered in random computer checks conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dealers </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Einhorn </PERSON> said. Shortly thereafter, the company, which operates or franchises 450 outlets in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, launched an ambitious effort to expand nationwide. That effort was abandoned two years later because of losses, and the company returned to profitability in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Karcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 16 million on sales of $ 369.5 million in 1987. The rest of the relatives accused of profiting from the inside information are <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>'s son, <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON>; daughters, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher-Garett </PERSON>, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> LeVecke </PERSON>, <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher-Everly </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>'s son-in-law, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fergus </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. Also <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>'s daughter, <PERSON> Doneta </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomason </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> David </PERSON>; and Mrs. <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Rosemary </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruns </PERSON>, and her husband, <PERSON> William </PERSON>
