<HEAD>Plunge In Dow Average Triggers Ban on Computerized Trading Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS closing Dow average to 2,005.64 in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A restriction on computerized stock trading that went into effect when the Dow Jones industrial average tumbled more than 50 points Thursday stemmed the slide only briefly and actually may have worsened it, brokers said. The widely followed barometer of 30 blue chip stocks dropped 101.46 to 2,005.64, its largest loss since falling 140.58 on Jan. 8. It marked the second time the so-called `` collar'' on index-arbitrage program trading was triggered since the restriction was announced in February as part of an effort to restore stability to a market still suffering after-effects of the October market disaster. It also was the first time the collar was triggered by a downward move in the Dow average. The collar was triggered for the first time ever on April 6, when the average rose 64.16 points. Under the collar rule, traders are banned from using the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s automated order system to execute index-arbitrage program trades for the rest of the day when the Dow average moves up or down 50 points from the previous close. The <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the collar went into effect at about 1:55 p.m. Thursday when the average tumbled below the 50-point limit, battered by massive selling over disappointing news on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, fears of higher interest rates and a weaker dollar. Although computerized program trading was halted, brokers who utilize the strategy began using an old-fashioned manual method for selling stocks and the Dow average kept falling. `` I guess there's really a lot of selling that's built up,'' said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DaPuzzo </PERSON>, manager of retail equities at <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` You ca n't ignore the fact that there's heavy selling and profit-taking going on. Right now the selling is more chaotic because people want out at the same time.'' Others said the collar may have worsened the Dow average's drop because after the 50-point threshhold was reached, only sellers remained in the market. `` Once this thing goes below 50, nobody shows up to do any buying,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthel </PERSON>, a technical strategist at <ORGANIZATION> Butcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Singer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In index arbitrage program trading, brokers use computers to buy massive amounts of stocks in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and the equivalent stock-index futures in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, or vice versa, in order to profit from price disparities. The technique has been mentioned in some studies of the stock crash as a possible contributor to the volatility and soaring volumes that pummeled the market and frightened millions of investors into selling.
