<TEXT>
 Unexpected news of an increase in the nation's trade deficit touched off a freefall slide in the stock market Thursday, leaving the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average with its second three-digit loss this year Dow Jones's average of 30 blue chips plunged 101.46 to 2,005.64, for its largest loss since it fell 140.58 on Jan. 8 and its fifth biggest point drop ever. Declining issues overpowered advances by about 11 to 1 in the overall tally on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, with 144 up, 1,601 down and 248 unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> volume came to 211.81 million shares, against 185.12 million in the previous session. The <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>'s composite index fell 6.06 to 147.14. Before the market opened the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> reported that the nation's trade deficit widened to $ 13.83 billion in February from $ 12.44 billion the month before. That came as a shock to market participants, who had been looking for a continued narrowing in the gap between imports and exports. The dollar dropped sharply in foreign exchange markets on the news, and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> credit markets also took the news badly. Prices of long-term <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bonds fell more than $ 10 for each $ 1,000 in face value, putting their yields in the 8.85-8 .9 percent range Just a few weeks ago government bond yields got as low as about 8.3 percent. Stock-market analysts said persistent strength in imports, in particular, raised fears that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> might soon feel the need to tighten credit to restrain the economy as well as to support the dollar. `` You got a nasty bit of news,'' said <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Wachtel </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. `` The market is saying that the economy is too strong.'' The decline in the Dow reached 50 points at midafternoon, activating for the second-time the `` collar'' set up by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in early February. At that point the exchange asked its member firms not to use its main computerized trading system for program trading. But prices kept falling. Analysts noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> had climbed nearly 130 points from April 5 through Tuesday, largely on anticipation of favorable trade news. This morning's report, they said, effectively wiped out the basis for that rally. Multipoint losers among the blue chips included <ORGANIZATION> Merck </ORGANIZATION>, down 7 | at 159 |; <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION>, down 4 -RCB- at 111 -RRB-; <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>, down 2 \ at 37 -RCB-; <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION>, down 4 ~ at 77 ~, and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, down <ORGANIZATION> Digital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equipment </ORGANIZATION>, which reported approximately flat first-quarter earnings on Wednesday, lost 5 \ to 103 -LRB- One of the few issues that bucked the downtrend was Resorts International class A shares, up 3 -LRB- at 31 -RRB- in American Stock Exchange trading. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> and <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffin </PERSON>, who have been battling for control of the company, reached an agreement that would