<HEAD>Stocks Fall Nearly $100 Billion On News Of Bigger Trade Deficit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT closing Dow to 2,005.64, sted
2005.63.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Deficit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Dow Jones industrial average plunged more than 100 points, the dollar sank and interest rates jumped Thursday after the government announced a $ 13.8 billion trade deficit in February, the biggest since last October. The Dow Jones average of 30 stocks skidded 101.46 points to 2,005.64, a 4.8 percent decline. It was the year's second worst drop after a 140.58-point slide on Jan. 8. The value of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stocks fell $ 99.7 billion, or 3.7 percent, <ORGANIZATION> Wilshire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said. The White House and most economists said the trade deficit was still improving in spite of the setback, but the markets took the news badly anyway. Most traders had convinced themselves the imbalance between imports and exports would be less than $ 12 billion, and they bailed out when the disappointing report hit at 8:30 a.m. EDT. `` There was a lot of wishing-makes-it-so -LRB- attitude -RRB-. People wanted to see a good number,'' said <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON>, chief economist of High Frequency Economics. He had predicted a $ 14 billion gap. The decline in the Dow triggered a ban on a form of computerized program trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. It was the first time the ban has been prompted by a decline of more than 50 points. Last week, it was triggered by an increase of more than 50 points. The Dow had climbed nearly 130 points from April 5 through Tuesday, largely on anticipation of favorable trade news. The news killed that rally as declining issues outnumbered advancing ones nearly 11 to 1 on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>. The trade deficit report also battered <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> markets, where the <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times-Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> 100-stock index fell 1.3 percent. The dollar lost roughly 2 percent of its value against the Japanese yen, British pound and West German mark in spite of heavy intervention by virtually all the major central banks. Big trade deficits tend to push the dollar down by giving trading partners an oversupply of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency. The selling pressure on the dollar challenged an agreement to support the currency that was reaffirmed Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> by finance officials of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. The Group of Seven nations failed to freeze the dollar but they did `` let the market know they're there,'' said <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON>, a currency analyst at <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. Interest rates leaped as pessimism swamped the bond market. The trade deficit signaled to some investors that an overly strong domestic economy was sucking in too many imports. Traders also feared a weak dollar could push up import prices, causing inflation and hurting fixed-income securities. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s benchmark 30-year <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond recovered about halfway late in the day as stocks were sinking, but still finished with a decline of roughly $ 11 for every $ 1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to the price, rose to roughly 8.87 percent, a three-month high. The bond market's dismal performance was surprising because inflation signs did not crop up in the commodities markets, said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Worseck </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> A.G. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. The trade deficit was the highest since the record gap of $ 17.6 billion in October. It was up from January's $ 12.4 billion gap. But <PERSON> Weinberg </PERSON> noted it was down from a deficit of $ 14.4 billion the previous February. `` It's just one of those glitches that keep the financial markets interesting. The trend is still for improvement in the trade deficit,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Solloway </PERSON>, director of economic research at <ORGANIZATION> Argus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Solloway </PERSON> said traders had become the victims of expecting too much and then not getting it. `` We just ca n't too far ahead of ourselves. We all would like to see faster improvement, but it may be expecting too much,'' he said. For the first two months of 1988, the deficit is running at an annual rate of $ 157.6 billion, below the record $ 171.2 billion of last year but still worse than second highest imbalance of $ 156.2 billion in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. Exports rose to $ 23.6 billion, up 5.5 percent from $ 22.3 billion in January and up 22 percent from $ 19.4 billion in February 1987. Imports rose to $ 37.4 billion, up 7.5 percent from $ 34.8 billion in January and up 10.9 percent from $ 33.7 billion in February 1987. The deficit with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the country with the largest trade surplus with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, also increased dramatically, by $ 500 million to more than $ 4.5 billion. But it narrowed slightly with the so-called newly industrialized countries _ <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> _ falling by about $ 20 million to $ 2.9 billion. Commerce Secretary <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Verity </PERSON>, who is in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, said in a statement released by his office that the February figures were disappointing despite what he called an `` underlying favorable trend.'' `` The figures show a substantial improvement from the average $ 15 billion deficit per month during the second half of 1987,'' <ORGANIZATION> Verity </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We look forward to continued export-led growth.'' In another report Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said business inventories grew 0.1 percent in February, a small rise after four big monthly increases. A healthy rise in sales kept inventories from rising. Economists had feared the inventory buildup would force production cutbacks and slow economic growth early in 1988. But the inventory numbers, along with the trade report showing a big increase in imports, provide evidence that domestic demand has not weakened.
