<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Reeling from setbacks in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, the courts, and at the cash register, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> faces new problems with federal government investigations under way. But the airline's president says he welcomes a major federal investigation into the management of its parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> as a way to highlight his company's performance. The <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> launched an unprecedented inquiry Wednesday into <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s finances and management, to determine whether the company is fit to carry commercial air traffic. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> also on Wednesday slapped Eastern with $ 823,000 in new fines for safety violations and said it was beginning an inspection of the carrier's entire fleet. Eastern President <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> DOT </ORGANIZATION> probe `` certainly is n't going to help'' <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s financial troubles, which include the loss of $ 900 million over the past 10 years. Eastern also reported a nearly 20 percent drop in passenger revenue during March. `` The very idea of an investigation into safety is scary to the flying public, but we welcome it because we hope the whole story of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> dedication to safety and performance will finally be told,'' Bakes said. Bakes blamed the labor unions at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, which was near bankruptcy when <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> acquired it in 1986, for pol