<HEAD>Senate OKs $1.1 Trillion Spending Plan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to specify that development money is for grants
to local governments; subs pvs grafs 9-10, ``But the ... 1989,'' to
clarify that $1.4 billion is part of total $2.6 billion increase. A
version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday approved a $ 1.1 trillion budget that calls for bypassing last fall's deficit-reduction pact with President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to expand the war on drugs The fiscal 1989 spending blueprint, passed 69-26, also includes increases for education, the space program and AIDS research while freezing or cutting back transportation, housing and development grants to local governments. `` We made tough choices,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> He defended his plan while conceding that the deficit problem remains unsolved. `` We ca n't keep consuming more than we earn and living on credit,'' he said Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., called the budget a `` lost opportunity'' that resulted from `` a decision to coast rather than deal with the deficit'' in an election year `` The next president and the next <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will be left with enormous problems,'' he said. The House approved a different version of the spending plan last month. The two chambers will begin negotiations next week toward a final budget resolution. Conforming with last fall's deficit-reduction agreement with the president, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan earmarks $ 294 billion for military spending and $ 16.1 billion for international assistance. It includes no new taxes beyond the $ 14 billion enacted last December for fiscal 1989, which begins Oct. 1. The agreement also capped spending by domestic agencies. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> plan, like <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s proposed budget, conformed with those limits. But the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> voted 93-0 Wednesday night to bypass the spending caps to provide an additional $ 2.6 billion for anti-drug efforts beginning next year. The money would go for treatment programs, law enforcement and interdiction of smuggled drugs. The amendment offered by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> DeConcini </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ariz </LOCATION>., and <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, called for increasing government tax and debt collections to cover the $ 1.4 billion portion of this new money that would be spent during the 1989 fiscal year Sponsors said they were n't busting the deficit agreement, because that pact includes a clause allowing exceptions for dire emergencies. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget claims to reduce the deficit to $ 136 billion, as required by the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law. Like the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> adopted the administration's optimistic economic scenarios in order to show less red ink. The <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates the deficit would be $ 35 billion higher. The deficit was $ 150 billion in fiscal 1987, and it is expected to dip to $ 147.5 billion this year. Overall, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget would cut the deficit $ 7.2 billion below what would otherwise be expected under current law, according to budget committee figures. Less than half of those savings would come from spending cuts, with the bulk relying mostly on sales of government assets to show a deficit reduction. The DeConcini-D'Amato drug amendment and a smaller one, also shifting more money to drugs, were the only two substantive amendments adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in four days of debate. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday rejected, 57-38, a proposal by Sen. <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> Weicker </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Conn </LOCATION>., to postpone starting construction of the superconducting super collider research project until after next year, and using the $ 50 million saved for health care Senators also defeated, 66-29, an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Armstrong </PERSON>, R-Colo., to cut development programs to pay for a reduction in the capital gains tax Like <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s budget, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan greatly increases space and science spending. The space program would get a 27 percent increase and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> 11 percent more than during the current fiscal year. AIDS research would get more than $ 1.3 billion. `` This is one of the most futuristic budgets in the history of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Domenici </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, the senior Republican on the budget committee. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> plan also boosts aviation safety programs by 19 percent, to allow for hiring of more air traffic controllers and purchase of new equipment. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved a more modest boost in the space program, opting instead to protect housing, development and transportation programs from cutbacks. Neither plan contemplates major changes in agriculture programs. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> version includes $ 500 million for buying commodities to continue the distributions to the needy. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget adopts <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s proposal to increase military pay by 4.3 percent but civilian federal salaries by only 2 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> opted for a 3 percent pay hike for all federal employees. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> budget action came on the earliest date in years, but <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was still missing its April 15 deadline for finishing budget action. The budget is a congressional resolution that does not require the president's signature. It serves as a guideline for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as it produces its annual spending bills.
