<HEAD>Domestic Sales Drop in Early April But Upturn Expected Later in
Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of domestic cars and light trucks fell 10.8 percent in early April from a year ago, a drop that analysts labled a statistical blip and that some industry participants blamed on unique holiday and tax factors. Automakers reported Wednesday they sold 230,486 domestic-built cars and light trucks in the eight selling days of April 1-10, down from 290,826 domestic vehicles in the nine selling days of the same period a year earlier. Because of the difference in selling days, percentage changes for the period reflect changes in average daily sales, not straight totals. `` It's just the usual -LRB- market -RRB- volatility, nothing special. There's no question sales will pick up,'' said <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON>, analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Glantz </PERSON> and others said increased difficulty and confusion among people preparing this year's revised federal income tax forms may have kept more buyers than usual out of the market in early April as the April 15 filing date neared. <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, sales manager of <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyundai </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, said: `` The last two weeks have been slow. You see people waiting to finish their tax returns ... to see how much they can afford.'' The April 1-10 period also included Good Friday, Passover and Easter, a time when many people take extra days off work but are n't likely to wander into dealerships, analysts said Sales were unexpectedly strong during the first quarter of 1988, leading many analysts to increase their forecasts for the rest of the year. Early April marked the first real slowdown. `` It's the weakest period in a long time. -LRB- But -RRB- I think it's just a hiccup,'' said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON>, industry analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` The pressure on dealers to move out excess inventory is lightening up. Inventories were on the low side of normal at the end of March,'' he said. Dealerships had a 58-day supply of domestic cars at the end of March, according to the weekly trade publication <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>'s Automotive Reports. A 60-day to 65-day supply is considered normal. Car sales dropped in early April for all domestic producers except <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, whose sales jumped 31.7 percent, and <ORGANIZATION> Mazda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which began assembling cars in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> late last year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the third-largest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> automaker, saw its car sales drop 7.8 percent from last year but saw its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market share rise to 15.6 percent from 14.3 percent a year earlier. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> truck sales jumped 15.3 percent as its market share rose to 23.9 percent from 20.4 percent a year ago. Of the Big Three, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> suffered the largest drop in domestic car sales, 18.8 percent from a year ago, compared to a 15.9 percent drop for <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> held 49.2 percent of that market, down from 51.2 percent a year ago, while <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s share held steady at 29.7 percent <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s domestic light truck sales fell 12.7 percent and its share of the market shrank to 35.1 percent from 39.6 percent. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s truck sales rose 0.8 percent and its market share rose to 39.3 percent from 38.4 percent a year ago
